WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.085
- [Reporter] North Koreans weeping and wailing,

00:00:02.085 --> 00:00:04.087
collapsing and mourning after learning

00:00:04.087 --> 00:00:05.464
of the death of Kim Jong-Il.

00:00:08.258 --> 00:00:10.844
- [Narrator] This reaction may seem extreme to you,

00:00:10.844 --> 00:00:12.846
but to the people of North Korea,

00:00:12.846 --> 00:00:14.431
they were mourning their God.

00:00:15.766 --> 00:00:18.518
North Korea, the tiny isolated country

00:00:18.518 --> 00:00:22.064
with the capabilities of mass destruction.

00:00:22.064 --> 00:00:26.109
With hostile relations in the West and increasing tension,

00:00:26.109 --> 00:00:28.528
will the Kim dynasty survive?

00:00:28.528 --> 00:00:32.115
The civilians adore and worship their communist dictator,

00:00:32.115 --> 00:00:34.910
or is this all a show?

00:00:34.910 --> 00:00:37.537
From the country's founding in 1948

00:00:37.537 --> 00:00:40.332
to the modern day totalitarian regime,

00:00:40.332 --> 00:00:43.710
this is the entire history of North Korea.

00:00:50.217 --> 00:00:54.221
The birth of North Korea, 1946 to 1953.

00:00:54.221 --> 00:00:56.348
Japanese-occupied Korea.

00:00:56.348 --> 00:00:58.308
The entire Korean peninsula

00:00:58.308 --> 00:01:01.937
was under Japanese occupation after 1905.

00:01:01.937 --> 00:01:05.774
Japan's occupation was unquestioned by foreign powers,

00:01:05.774 --> 00:01:09.403
and it presented its occupation as a civilizing project.

00:01:09.403 --> 00:01:12.322
For the Koreans, the story was quite the opposite.

00:01:12.322 --> 00:01:15.826
1,000s of gorilla fighters bitterly resisted Japan

00:01:15.826 --> 00:01:19.204
until 1910, when they were all but destroyed

00:01:19.204 --> 00:01:22.958
and Korea became fully part of the Japanese empire.

00:01:22.958 --> 00:01:25.419
The story of Japanese-occupied Korea

00:01:25.419 --> 00:01:27.754
is one shared by many colonies.

00:01:27.754 --> 00:01:30.757
Industrialization and economic expansion came

00:01:30.757 --> 00:01:33.218
with discrimination against the native peoples

00:01:33.218 --> 00:01:35.595
as wealth and resources were siphoned away

00:01:35.595 --> 00:01:37.681
to the imperial masters.

00:01:37.681 --> 00:01:40.058
The initial gorilla resistance was over,

00:01:40.058 --> 00:01:43.061
but the resentment of the Koreans did not go away.

00:01:43.061 --> 00:01:45.856
Japan ran Korea like a military colony,

00:01:45.856 --> 00:01:47.607
with armed teachers in schools

00:01:47.607 --> 00:01:50.068
and a massive militarized police force

00:01:50.068 --> 00:01:52.487
overseeing all aspects of life.

00:01:52.487 --> 00:01:56.867
Also, like many colonies, they longed for independence.

00:01:56.867 --> 00:01:58.452
With the end of the first World War

00:01:58.452 --> 00:02:00.370
and all its promises of freedom,

00:02:00.370 --> 00:02:03.081
Korea agitated for its independence.

00:02:03.081 --> 00:02:06.043
Protests swept the nation in 1919,

00:02:06.043 --> 00:02:08.628
which the Japanese put down brutally.

00:02:08.628 --> 00:02:12.674
In one case, they locked 100s of protestors inside a church

00:02:12.674 --> 00:02:14.259
and burned them alive.

00:02:14.259 --> 00:02:16.720
However, the tide couldn't be stemmed.

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:19.264
The wave of Korean nationalism rose,

00:02:19.264 --> 00:02:21.600
and at its head were the communists.

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:24.353
(dramatic music)

00:02:30.150 --> 00:02:32.569
The rise of Korean communism.

00:02:34.571 --> 00:02:37.032
Communist movements were common across the world

00:02:37.032 --> 00:02:38.909
in the early 19th century.

00:02:38.909 --> 00:02:41.411
Galvanized by the success of Vladimir Lenin

00:02:41.411 --> 00:02:43.038
in the Russian revolution,

00:02:43.038 --> 00:02:45.707
the communists promised wealth redistribution

00:02:45.707 --> 00:02:48.126
and end to profit seeking and imperialism,

00:02:48.126 --> 00:02:51.129
and a new prosperous beginning for its people.

00:02:51.129 --> 00:02:54.132
Time would put those promises to the test, but the dream

00:02:54.132 --> 00:02:57.636
of the communist utopia enchanted countless people,

00:02:57.636 --> 00:02:59.471
especially in Korea.

00:02:59.471 --> 00:03:01.807
Korean communists quickly became the tip

00:03:01.807 --> 00:03:03.809
of the anti-Japanese spear.

00:03:03.809 --> 00:03:07.646
Numerous gorilla and civil groups emerged in the 1910s,

00:03:07.646 --> 00:03:09.314
'20s, and '30s,

00:03:09.314 --> 00:03:12.317
trying to achieve an independent communist Korea.

00:03:12.317 --> 00:03:14.986
The Japanese responded with firing squads,

00:03:14.986 --> 00:03:16.822
prison time, and terror.

00:03:16.822 --> 00:03:19.950
This killed many gorillas and forced others to flee,

00:03:19.950 --> 00:03:22.661
including a young man the world would come to know

00:03:22.661 --> 00:03:24.329
as Kim Il-Sung.

00:03:27.916 --> 00:03:29.709
The Rise of Kim Il-Sung.

00:03:30.794 --> 00:03:34.381
Kim Il-Sung was born in 1912 near Pyongyang.

00:03:34.381 --> 00:03:37.426
His early life is drowned in later propaganda,

00:03:37.426 --> 00:03:39.803
but it seems he was raised by Christian parents

00:03:39.803 --> 00:03:42.472
who escaped into China when he was still a child

00:03:42.472 --> 00:03:45.434
after getting involved in anti-Japanese activity.

00:03:45.434 --> 00:03:49.479
In China, young Kim fell in love with communist ideas.

00:03:49.479 --> 00:03:52.274
China had its own active communist movements,

00:03:52.274 --> 00:03:54.401
which Kim joined as soon as he was able.

00:03:54.401 --> 00:03:57.779
In 1931, he became a card-carrying member

00:03:57.779 --> 00:03:59.823
of the Chinese Communist Party

00:03:59.823 --> 00:04:02.659
and got involved with anti-Japanese protests

00:04:02.659 --> 00:04:04.119
and militant action.

00:04:04.119 --> 00:04:08.123
When Japanese forces invaded Manchuria in 1931,

00:04:08.123 --> 00:04:10.208
Kim joined the resistance hoping

00:04:10.208 --> 00:04:14.129
to drive Japan out of China, and eventually his homeland.

00:04:14.129 --> 00:04:17.257
Kim proved to be a successful gorilla leader.

00:04:17.257 --> 00:04:18.925
He quickly worked his way up the ranks

00:04:18.925 --> 00:04:21.970
with successful strike after successful strike,

00:04:21.970 --> 00:04:24.598
operating in both China and Korea.

00:04:24.598 --> 00:04:27.809
In 1937, he led 200 gorillas

00:04:27.809 --> 00:04:31.271
in the Battle of Pochonbo just across the Korean border,

00:04:31.271 --> 00:04:33.857
where his forces defeated Japanese soldiers

00:04:33.857 --> 00:04:35.734
and burned down a police station

00:04:35.734 --> 00:04:37.819
and other occupied buildings.

00:04:37.819 --> 00:04:40.030
The victory put Kim Il-Sung on the map

00:04:40.030 --> 00:04:42.574
and made him one of the most famous gorilla leaders

00:04:42.574 --> 00:04:43.825
in East Asia.

00:04:43.825 --> 00:04:46.036
For later North Korean propaganda,

00:04:46.036 --> 00:04:49.122
it was the true start of Kim's path to power.

00:04:49.122 --> 00:04:51.249
Kim himself wrote about the battle saying

00:04:51.249 --> 00:04:54.544
that "the flames over the night sky of Pochonbo

00:04:54.544 --> 00:04:56.796
in the Fatherland heralded the dawn

00:04:56.796 --> 00:04:58.507
of the liberation of Korea,

00:04:58.507 --> 00:05:01.009
which had been buried in darkness."

00:05:03.220 --> 00:05:05.055
Kim and the Soviets.

00:05:05.055 --> 00:05:08.600
Kim's success earned him the nickname of "The Tiger."

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:12.062
The Japanese military sent out units to hunt him down

00:05:12.062 --> 00:05:14.648
and may have killed his secret first wife,

00:05:14.648 --> 00:05:17.442
which forced Kim to retreat into the Soviet Union,

00:05:17.442 --> 00:05:20.070
where he was officially enrolled in the Red Army

00:05:20.070 --> 00:05:23.323
and spent most of the Second World War in hiding.

00:05:23.323 --> 00:05:27.536
When the USSR declared war on Japan in 1945,

00:05:27.536 --> 00:05:30.497
Soviet armies marched into the Korean peninsula.

00:05:30.497 --> 00:05:32.499
Kim followed shortly after.

00:05:32.499 --> 00:05:35.710
At the same time, US forces landed in the South.

00:05:35.710 --> 00:05:38.296
After evicting the Japanese occupiers,

00:05:38.296 --> 00:05:40.924
the allied powers decided to split Korea,

00:05:40.924 --> 00:05:42.509
much as they had done Germany.

00:05:42.509 --> 00:05:45.470
American officials chose the 38th parallel,

00:05:45.470 --> 00:05:48.139
a previously meaningless line on a map

00:05:48.139 --> 00:05:51.643
as the boundary between the two occupied zones.

00:05:51.643 --> 00:05:54.104
This line, apparently chosen in half an hour

00:05:54.104 --> 00:05:56.565
by two random American kernels,

00:05:56.565 --> 00:06:00.402
would become one of the most important borders in the world

00:06:00.402 --> 00:06:02.320
for the next 80 years.

00:06:02.320 --> 00:06:05.198
Korea had no natural North-South division

00:06:05.198 --> 00:06:08.243
and everyone wanted a united Korean peninsula,

00:06:08.243 --> 00:06:11.037
under their particular ideology, of course.

00:06:11.037 --> 00:06:11.955
The Soviets knew

00:06:11.955 --> 00:06:14.833
they would need a reliable Korean communist leader

00:06:14.833 --> 00:06:18.587
to achieve this, and Stalin personally chose the greatest

00:06:18.587 --> 00:06:21.756
of the Korean communist gorillas for the job.

00:06:21.756 --> 00:06:26.595
In December, 1945, Kim Il-Sung became first secretary

00:06:26.595 --> 00:06:28.513
of the Communist Party of Korea,

00:06:28.513 --> 00:06:30.724
giving Kim power over his nation

00:06:30.724 --> 00:06:33.893
that he would hold for the next 50 years.

00:06:37.522 --> 00:06:39.024
The Kim deception?

00:06:40.358 --> 00:06:43.236
Kim had risen from lowly gorilla fighter

00:06:43.236 --> 00:06:46.573
to leader of his nation, or had he?

00:06:46.573 --> 00:06:50.368
A bizarre conspiracy theory claims that the Kim Il-Sung

00:06:50.368 --> 00:06:54.581
who entered North Korea in 1945 was a not the same one

00:06:54.581 --> 00:06:56.750
who led the battle of Pochonbo.

00:06:56.750 --> 00:06:58.126
According to this theory,

00:06:58.126 --> 00:07:01.546
after the real Kim Il-Sung fled into the USSR,

00:07:01.546 --> 00:07:03.882
Stalin made him disappear

00:07:03.882 --> 00:07:05.884
like so many other communist figures

00:07:05.884 --> 00:07:07.719
who threatened his popularity.

00:07:07.719 --> 00:07:08.928
It sounds crazy,

00:07:08.928 --> 00:07:12.140
but a CIA investigation into the theory concluded

00:07:12.140 --> 00:07:13.350
that it was right.

00:07:13.350 --> 00:07:15.435
They believed that the Kim Il-Sung

00:07:15.435 --> 00:07:17.437
in North Korea was a criminal

00:07:17.437 --> 00:07:21.024
who the Soviets blackmailed into a assuming a false identity

00:07:21.024 --> 00:07:22.984
so they could manipulate him.

00:07:22.984 --> 00:07:26.196
A Soviet officer who worked with Kim also wrote privately

00:07:26.196 --> 00:07:29.407
that the later Kim was an imposter whose name was stolen

00:07:29.407 --> 00:07:31.034
from the famous gorilla leader

00:07:31.034 --> 00:07:33.703
who had actually died years earlier.

00:07:33.703 --> 00:07:36.998
These days, historians think the theory is nonsense.

00:07:36.998 --> 00:07:39.834
Several people who knew Kim as a gorilla confirmed

00:07:39.834 --> 00:07:41.461
that it was the same man.

00:07:41.461 --> 00:07:43.755
The CIA report had simply been wrong,

00:07:43.755 --> 00:07:47.384
which happens far more often than the CIA likes to admit.

00:07:47.384 --> 00:07:51.304
Still, it's not impossible that the entire Kim dynasty

00:07:51.304 --> 00:07:53.390
is built on a Soviet lie.

00:07:58.645 --> 00:08:00.105
A divided Korea.

00:08:01.648 --> 00:08:04.484
Kim The Gorilla and Kim The First Secretary

00:08:04.484 --> 00:08:06.194
were probably the same,

00:08:06.194 --> 00:08:09.614
but no such unity existed for Korea itself.

00:08:09.614 --> 00:08:11.908
Under two contrasting governments,

00:08:11.908 --> 00:08:14.452
the Korean peninsula became a flashpoint

00:08:14.452 --> 00:08:15.912
for the new Cold War

00:08:15.912 --> 00:08:18.581
between communism and capitalism.

00:08:18.581 --> 00:08:21.292
In the south, General John R. Hodge ran

00:08:21.292 --> 00:08:24.379
the US Army's military government of Korea,

00:08:24.379 --> 00:08:26.256
while Kim acted as the figurehead

00:08:26.256 --> 00:08:28.717
for a Soviet-backed government in the North.

00:08:28.717 --> 00:08:31.177
Historians have often overstated the power

00:08:31.177 --> 00:08:33.138
of the Soviets in the North.

00:08:33.138 --> 00:08:36.474
Modern scholars accept that after 1946,

00:08:36.474 --> 00:08:39.102
Kim Il-Sung and the North Korean Workers Party

00:08:39.102 --> 00:08:42.355
were leading the way in setting North Korean policy.

00:08:42.355 --> 00:08:45.984
Kim began a series of communistic reforms in his nation.

00:08:45.984 --> 00:08:49.779
In March, 1940, he began seizing land from landlords

00:08:49.779 --> 00:08:53.241
without compensation and redistributing it to the people,

00:08:53.241 --> 00:08:56.327
remaking the North's economy in a matter of months

00:08:56.327 --> 00:08:59.372
with 1,000s of new small peasant holdings.

00:08:59.372 --> 00:09:02.709
He set out a two-year economic plan to guide production

00:09:02.709 --> 00:09:03.793
and investment,

00:09:03.793 --> 00:09:07.130
relying on new levels of state control over the economy

00:09:07.130 --> 00:09:09.299
and a focus on heavy industry.

00:09:09.299 --> 00:09:11.801
All industry, banks, communications,

00:09:11.801 --> 00:09:14.888
and transport infrastructure was nationalized.

00:09:14.888 --> 00:09:19.601
And in July, 1946, Kim introduced a sexual equality law

00:09:19.601 --> 00:09:22.812
that guaranteed equal working rights for women.

00:09:22.812 --> 00:09:24.731
The reforms were successful

00:09:24.731 --> 00:09:28.485
and North Korea saw an incredible economic recovery

00:09:28.485 --> 00:09:31.488
in the first few years after 1945.

00:09:36.659 --> 00:09:38.328
Divided communists.

00:09:39.537 --> 00:09:42.457
All was not easy within North Korea, though.

00:09:42.457 --> 00:09:46.169
Different factions of communists threatened Kim's control

00:09:46.169 --> 00:09:49.672
and each tried to push North Korea in their own direction.

00:09:49.672 --> 00:09:54.385
Kim's Kapsin, or gorilla faction, held power for now.

00:09:54.385 --> 00:09:56.971
As the name implies, they were mostly made up

00:09:56.971 --> 00:09:59.474
of former gorilla fighters whose effectiveness

00:09:59.474 --> 00:10:01.267
had earned the faith of Stalin,

00:10:01.267 --> 00:10:04.354
but Stalin's faith was awfully fragile.

00:10:04.354 --> 00:10:08.107
This made the Soviet Korean communists a particular threat.

00:10:08.107 --> 00:10:11.319
Made up of ethnic Koreans with Soviet citizenship,

00:10:11.319 --> 00:10:13.696
they leaned heavily towards Moscow.

00:10:13.696 --> 00:10:15.907
While they hadn't proven their effectiveness enough

00:10:15.907 --> 00:10:18.701
to earn Stalin's favor, the heavy involvement

00:10:18.701 --> 00:10:21.162
of the Soviets made them a risky rival

00:10:21.162 --> 00:10:23.081
for the young Kim regime.

00:10:23.081 --> 00:10:25.291
Then there was the Yan'an Faction.

00:10:25.291 --> 00:10:27.961
This was a Chinese-aligned communist wing,

00:10:27.961 --> 00:10:30.755
most of its members being part of the CCP.

00:10:30.755 --> 00:10:34.717
After Mao's communists took power in China in 1949,

00:10:34.717 --> 00:10:37.136
the Yan'an Faction became a potent threat

00:10:37.136 --> 00:10:39.973
to Kim's Korea-centric approach that threatened

00:10:39.973 --> 00:10:42.600
to pull North Korea towards Beijing.

00:10:42.600 --> 00:10:45.854
Last, there were the South Korean communists.

00:10:45.854 --> 00:10:48.982
Many had fled the south when the American troops arrived

00:10:48.982 --> 00:10:51.776
and made it their main goal to reunify the peninsula

00:10:51.776 --> 00:10:53.319
under communist rule.

00:10:53.319 --> 00:10:56.364
They were less of an immediate threat until reunification

00:10:56.364 --> 00:10:59.200
was achieved, but their leader, Pak Hon-Yong,

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:01.661
was the closest thing Kim had to a rival.

00:11:01.661 --> 00:11:05.623
Pak and Kim had both been invited to Moscow in 1946

00:11:05.623 --> 00:11:09.252
for Stalin to judge which was the suitable leader.

00:11:09.252 --> 00:11:10.962
While Kim had one out,

00:11:10.962 --> 00:11:13.756
Pak remained a force to be reckoned with.

00:11:18.428 --> 00:11:20.179
Foundation of KPA.

00:11:21.472 --> 00:11:24.851
Unsurprisingly, Kim anchored himself in the military.

00:11:24.851 --> 00:11:26.936
He'd been a gorilla fighter for decades

00:11:26.936 --> 00:11:29.230
and made it a huge part of his ideology,

00:11:29.230 --> 00:11:31.608
so much so that the foundation date

00:11:31.608 --> 00:11:35.737
of his anti-Japanese gorilla force, April 25th,

00:11:35.737 --> 00:11:37.864
became an annual holiday.

00:11:37.864 --> 00:11:40.366
This gorilla force was officially transformed

00:11:40.366 --> 00:11:42.160
into the Korean People's Army,

00:11:42.160 --> 00:11:46.164
known as KPA, in February, 1948.

00:11:46.164 --> 00:11:48.499
Conscription was in place from the outset,

00:11:48.499 --> 00:11:52.545
which meant that the KPA has always been a formidable force.

00:11:52.545 --> 00:11:55.340
Arming such a massive army was a tall order,

00:11:55.340 --> 00:11:59.260
but the USSR ensured that it was done by pouring weapons,

00:11:59.260 --> 00:12:02.931
tanks, planes, and artillery into North Korea.

00:12:02.931 --> 00:12:05.391
With a huge numbers and modern equipment,

00:12:05.391 --> 00:12:09.187
the KPA was one of the most powerful military forces

00:12:09.187 --> 00:12:11.064
in the post-war world.

00:12:15.944 --> 00:12:20.531
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea is born, 1948.

00:12:23.368 --> 00:12:26.537
Meanwhile, the newly formed United Nations tried

00:12:26.537 --> 00:12:29.624
and failed to settle the Korean Peninsula problem.

00:12:29.624 --> 00:12:32.710
The USSR opposed free elections

00:12:32.710 --> 00:12:35.171
and refused to cooperate with the UN,

00:12:35.171 --> 00:12:38.424
believing that they were puppets controlled by the US.

00:12:38.424 --> 00:12:41.886
The UN proceeded to hold elections only in the South.

00:12:41.886 --> 00:12:46.307
And on the 15th of August, 1948, the Republic of Korea,

00:12:46.307 --> 00:12:49.894
that being South Korea, was born under the leadership

00:12:49.894 --> 00:12:51.187
of Syngman Rhee.

00:12:51.187 --> 00:12:53.481
As far as the UN was concerned,

00:12:53.481 --> 00:12:56.442
this was the only true Korean government.

00:12:56.442 --> 00:13:00.029
North Korea responded by writing their own constitution.

00:13:00.029 --> 00:13:02.532
On the 9th of September, they declared themselves

00:13:02.532 --> 00:13:05.284
as the Democratic People's Republic of Korea

00:13:05.284 --> 00:13:07.245
with Kim Il-SunG as Premier.

00:13:07.245 --> 00:13:11.207
North Korea, as we know it today, was finally here.

00:13:15.128 --> 00:13:17.380
The Korean War: invasion.

00:13:18.756 --> 00:13:22.343
Almost immediately, Kim started planning the reunification

00:13:22.343 --> 00:13:23.428
of the peninsula.

00:13:23.428 --> 00:13:27.265
With most American troops withdrawing in June, 1949

00:13:27.265 --> 00:13:31.394
and the vastly superior Northern military at his fingertips,

00:13:31.394 --> 00:13:33.187
it looked like an easy win.

00:13:33.187 --> 00:13:36.190
Communism had also seen a string of recent victories

00:13:36.190 --> 00:13:38.401
that boosted Kim's confidence too.

00:13:38.401 --> 00:13:43.406
The USSR detonated their first atomic bomb in August, 1949,

00:13:43.573 --> 00:13:47.493
which ended America's unchallenged nuclear supremacy.

00:13:47.493 --> 00:13:49.704
In China, Mao's communists overthrew

00:13:49.704 --> 00:13:51.164
the Republican government

00:13:51.164 --> 00:13:53.624
and gave them another communist ally,

00:13:53.624 --> 00:13:57.336
both Stalin and Mao threw their support behind an invasion,

00:13:57.336 --> 00:13:59.839
and Mao sent at least 50,000 men

00:13:59.839 --> 00:14:02.592
from the People's Liberation Army to support him,

00:14:02.592 --> 00:14:03.885
although Stalin was clear

00:14:03.885 --> 00:14:06.345
that he would not send in the Red Army.

00:14:06.345 --> 00:14:08.264
The South expected a war.

00:14:08.264 --> 00:14:11.893
There were several clashes in 1950 that proved hostility

00:14:11.893 --> 00:14:13.644
between the two Koreas.

00:14:13.644 --> 00:14:18.441
Then on 25th of June, 1950, North Korean tanks, planes,

00:14:18.441 --> 00:14:22.361
and infantry poured over the border in a massive assault.

00:14:22.361 --> 00:14:24.155
The northern army outnumbered

00:14:24.155 --> 00:14:26.657
the poorly equipped south two to one,

00:14:26.657 --> 00:14:29.118
it's air force by more than 10 to one,

00:14:29.118 --> 00:14:33.289
and North Korea's almost 300 tanks met a grand total

00:14:33.289 --> 00:14:36.584
of zero units of South Korean armor.

00:14:36.584 --> 00:14:39.337
South Korea utterly collapsed.

00:14:39.337 --> 00:14:42.298
Within five days, Kim controlled Seoul.

00:14:42.298 --> 00:14:46.177
Almost 80% of South Korea's army was captured, killed,

00:14:46.177 --> 00:14:49.222
or had deserted, and the tiny handful of US troops

00:14:49.222 --> 00:14:51.641
on the peninsula could do nothing but run

00:14:51.641 --> 00:14:54.769
in the face of the North's overwhelming advance.

00:14:54.769 --> 00:14:55.686
As they went,

00:14:55.686 --> 00:14:58.773
North Korean forces targeted ideological enemies

00:14:58.773 --> 00:15:00.066
in South Korea.

00:15:00.066 --> 00:15:03.152
Politicians, anti-communist intellectuals

00:15:03.152 --> 00:15:06.739
and business leaders were systematically exterminated

00:15:06.739 --> 00:15:08.199
by the KPA.

00:15:08.199 --> 00:15:10.785
Kim Il-Sung was beyond pleased.

00:15:10.785 --> 00:15:13.037
It appeared he'd won a great victory,

00:15:13.037 --> 00:15:15.081
but that euphoria was short-lived.

00:15:19.544 --> 00:15:22.255
The Korean War: US retaliation.

00:15:23.714 --> 00:15:27.051
The United Nation condemned the invasion immediately

00:15:27.051 --> 00:15:30.680
and two days later, it approved a unified military response

00:15:30.680 --> 00:15:31.931
to the crisis.

00:15:31.931 --> 00:15:34.142
Naturally the US took the lead.

00:15:34.142 --> 00:15:37.395
Washington was worried that the fall of Korea to communism

00:15:37.395 --> 00:15:40.064
would threaten Japan and cause a domino effect

00:15:40.064 --> 00:15:41.357
in the rest of Asia.

00:15:41.357 --> 00:15:43.067
General Douglas MacArthur,

00:15:43.067 --> 00:15:46.529
who'd led US forces in the Pacific Theater of World War II

00:15:46.529 --> 00:15:50.199
and currently oversaw US forces in occupied Japan,

00:15:50.199 --> 00:15:51.951
was given overall command

00:15:51.951 --> 00:15:54.412
of the UN Coalition forces.

00:15:54.412 --> 00:15:59.083
UN forces landed at Incheon on the 15th of September, 1950.

00:15:59.083 --> 00:16:02.795
In the largest amphibious assault since World War II,

00:16:02.795 --> 00:16:05.631
the UN attack shattered the KPA.

00:16:05.631 --> 00:16:07.675
The North Korean front collapsed

00:16:07.675 --> 00:16:11.262
and 10s of 1,000s of KPA soldiers were captured.

00:16:11.262 --> 00:16:13.472
The UN quickly retook Seoul

00:16:13.472 --> 00:16:15.099
and by the end of September

00:16:15.099 --> 00:16:17.643
had pushed back to the 38th parallel.

00:16:17.643 --> 00:16:19.937
By that point, most of North Korea's army

00:16:19.937 --> 00:16:22.148
had been killed or captured.

00:16:22.148 --> 00:16:26.068
In October, UN forces pushed into North Korea itself.

00:16:26.068 --> 00:16:28.362
Kim and his government were forced to flee

00:16:28.362 --> 00:16:31.741
and Pyongyang fell to UN forces within weeks.

00:16:31.741 --> 00:16:33.159
What it looked like a victory

00:16:33.159 --> 00:16:36.287
was quickly becoming a total defeat.

00:16:40.041 --> 00:16:42.585
The Korean War: strategic bombing.

00:16:43.920 --> 00:16:46.297
For North Korea, the true story of the war

00:16:46.297 --> 00:16:49.091
was not on the front lines, but at home.

00:16:49.091 --> 00:16:50.635
As its armies collapsed,

00:16:50.635 --> 00:16:53.846
so too did any hope of controlling the air.

00:16:53.846 --> 00:16:56.849
UN-aligned air Forces quickly established dominance

00:16:56.849 --> 00:16:58.809
in the skies above North Korea

00:16:58.809 --> 00:17:01.270
and used it to devastating effect.

00:17:01.270 --> 00:17:04.732
The US Air Force led a colossal bombing campaign

00:17:04.732 --> 00:17:08.778
that devastated North Korea's population and infrastructure.

00:17:08.778 --> 00:17:11.113
Entire cities were flattened,

00:17:11.113 --> 00:17:13.074
villages were wiped off the map.

00:17:13.074 --> 00:17:15.451
Pyongyang was so badly bombed

00:17:15.451 --> 00:17:18.788
that not a single major building was left standing.

00:17:18.788 --> 00:17:21.374
The US general in charge of the Air Forces said

00:17:21.374 --> 00:17:23.793
that by October, 1950,

00:17:23.793 --> 00:17:26.295
the Air Force stopped sending bombers out simply

00:17:26.295 --> 00:17:29.048
because there was nothing left to bomb.

00:17:29.048 --> 00:17:32.468
An estimated 80% or more of North Korea's buildings

00:17:32.468 --> 00:17:33.302
were flattened

00:17:33.302 --> 00:17:36.347
as more explosives were dropped on North Korea

00:17:36.347 --> 00:17:38.641
than were dropped in the entire Pacific Theater

00:17:38.641 --> 00:17:39.976
in World War II.

00:17:39.976 --> 00:17:43.688
Maybe 10% of the North Korean population was killed

00:17:43.688 --> 00:17:44.730
by the bombing.

00:17:44.730 --> 00:17:47.566
It is this experience, more than anything else,

00:17:47.566 --> 00:17:51.404
that shaped North Korean attitudes to the US after the war.

00:17:51.404 --> 00:17:54.407
Whatever ideological disagreements they might have

00:17:54.407 --> 00:17:57.618
and whatever nonsense propaganda the regime puts out,

00:17:57.618 --> 00:18:01.747
it is the near total leveling of North Korea by US bombing

00:18:01.747 --> 00:18:04.834
that explains the sheer hatred for the USA

00:18:04.834 --> 00:18:08.671
that pervades the North Korean state and society.

00:18:11.924 --> 00:18:14.719
The Korean War: Chinese intervention.

00:18:16.178 --> 00:18:19.557
Things improved for North Korea when China stepped in.

00:18:19.557 --> 00:18:22.476
China had warned the UN forces not to get too close

00:18:22.476 --> 00:18:26.772
to its territory, and on the 25th of October, 1950,

00:18:26.772 --> 00:18:28.899
they decided that enough was enough.

00:18:28.899 --> 00:18:32.862
10s of 1,000s of Chinese troops burst across the border

00:18:32.862 --> 00:18:35.531
and surprise attacked the UN forces.

00:18:35.531 --> 00:18:37.366
The UN was caught unaware

00:18:37.366 --> 00:18:39.910
and retreated in the face of the sudden attack.

00:18:39.910 --> 00:18:41.787
Chinese and North Korean forces

00:18:41.787 --> 00:18:43.706
quickly recaptured Pyongyang,

00:18:43.706 --> 00:18:46.542
pushed the UN back over the 38th parallel

00:18:46.542 --> 00:18:49.420
and even retook Seoul for a short period.

00:18:49.420 --> 00:18:51.589
Kim Il-Sung's feelings were mixed.

00:18:51.589 --> 00:18:53.174
On the one hand, North Korea

00:18:53.174 --> 00:18:55.551
was back under his control, but the strength

00:18:55.551 --> 00:18:59.138
of the UN forces made reunification unlikely.

00:18:59.138 --> 00:19:02.516
Kim resented the loss of so many of his troops

00:19:02.516 --> 00:19:05.436
and the fact that China was doing most of the fighting.

00:19:05.436 --> 00:19:08.898
Furthermore, both Stalin and Mao blamed the KPA

00:19:08.898 --> 00:19:11.150
for being too incompetent to win

00:19:11.150 --> 00:19:14.111
and causing the war to spiral out of control.

00:19:14.111 --> 00:19:16.572
Un forces soon regrouped and pushed back.

00:19:16.572 --> 00:19:18.366
Soul was retaken in March,

00:19:18.366 --> 00:19:20.951
its fourth and final conquest in less than a year,

00:19:20.951 --> 00:19:23.537
and once again it was the communist's turn

00:19:23.537 --> 00:19:26.791
to retreat north with 1,000s of their soldiers killed,

00:19:26.791 --> 00:19:28.709
wounded, or captured.

00:19:28.709 --> 00:19:33.339
The UN reached the 38th parallel again in July, 1951,

00:19:33.339 --> 00:19:37.635
and there the war would stall for two brutal years.

00:19:42.556 --> 00:19:45.851
The Korean War: stalemate and armistice.

00:19:47.561 --> 00:19:51.399
From July, 1951 to July, 1953,

00:19:51.399 --> 00:19:54.944
the Korean War was a stubborn stalemate that was as grueling

00:19:54.944 --> 00:19:58.656
and frustrating as the trenches of the First World War.

00:19:58.656 --> 00:20:00.950
Casualties continued on both sides,

00:20:00.950 --> 00:20:04.036
but no significant territory changed hands.

00:20:04.036 --> 00:20:06.497
After several failed attempts to negotiate,

00:20:06.497 --> 00:20:08.624
both sides finally came to an agreement

00:20:08.624 --> 00:20:11.919
on the 27th of July, 1953.

00:20:11.919 --> 00:20:15.047
It was not a peace treaty but an armistice.

00:20:15.047 --> 00:20:17.883
Both sides agreed to halt military operations,

00:20:17.883 --> 00:20:21.554
release prisoners, and returned the remains of the deceased.

00:20:21.554 --> 00:20:24.557
The armistice set up an internationally monitored

00:20:24.557 --> 00:20:28.102
demilitarized zone, the Korean DMZ,

00:20:28.102 --> 00:20:29.979
along the border to mark the boundary

00:20:29.979 --> 00:20:31.814
between the two nations.

00:20:31.814 --> 00:20:34.525
The war has been left unfinished ever since.

00:20:34.525 --> 00:20:37.778
Skirmishes and episodes of violence have broken out,

00:20:37.778 --> 00:20:38.863
but for the most part,

00:20:38.863 --> 00:20:42.616
North and South Korea have been locked in a tense standoff

00:20:42.616 --> 00:20:45.786
that has threatened to spill over into a devastating war

00:20:45.786 --> 00:20:49.415
at any moment for the last 70 years.

00:20:56.839 --> 00:21:01.343
The rebirth of North Korea, 1953 to 1970.

00:21:01.343 --> 00:21:04.138
North Korea emerged from the war a broken

00:21:04.138 --> 00:21:05.556
and battered nation.

00:21:05.556 --> 00:21:07.516
Its army was almost destroyed.

00:21:07.516 --> 00:21:09.310
Its cities were in ruins.

00:21:09.310 --> 00:21:12.521
Its population was exhausted and demoralized.

00:21:12.521 --> 00:21:16.025
Kim Il-Sung and his regime now faced the monumental task

00:21:16.025 --> 00:21:17.568
of rebuilding their country

00:21:17.568 --> 00:21:20.988
and navigating the perilous Cold War world.

00:21:20.988 --> 00:21:23.991
It was a task that required a fresh start,

00:21:23.991 --> 00:21:27.161
a rebirth of North Korea for a brand new age.

00:21:29.580 --> 00:21:31.165
Rebuilding a nation.

00:21:32.416 --> 00:21:36.879
The war devastated North Korea socially and economically.

00:21:36.879 --> 00:21:40.299
Overall economic output fell by 75%

00:21:40.299 --> 00:21:43.260
from 1949 to 1953.

00:21:43.260 --> 00:21:46.805
Output of energy, fuel, chemicals, metallurgy,

00:21:46.805 --> 00:21:50.351
and agriculture was a fraction of what it had been

00:21:50.351 --> 00:21:51.477
before the war.

00:21:51.477 --> 00:21:53.479
North Korea needed a rebirth

00:21:53.479 --> 00:21:56.899
and Kim Il-Sung set out the ways in which they'd achieve it.

00:21:56.899 --> 00:22:00.027
In 1953, he clarified four goals

00:22:00.027 --> 00:22:02.530
that would guide the nation in the coming years.

00:22:02.530 --> 00:22:04.156
First, he would consolidate

00:22:04.156 --> 00:22:07.201
what he called the People's Democratic System.

00:22:07.201 --> 00:22:08.494
In simpler terms,

00:22:08.494 --> 00:22:11.288
this meant doubling down on communist ideology

00:22:11.288 --> 00:22:13.123
and ramping up the propaganda

00:22:13.123 --> 00:22:16.210
to ensure that everyone was a loyal citizen.

00:22:16.210 --> 00:22:18.462
Second was to rebuild the economy

00:22:18.462 --> 00:22:20.714
and improve people's living standards.

00:22:20.714 --> 00:22:22.716
With much of the country in ruins,

00:22:22.716 --> 00:22:26.887
this was an obvious goal, but it would be a monumental task.

00:22:26.887 --> 00:22:29.473
Still, with total control over the economy

00:22:29.473 --> 00:22:31.600
and the support of their foreign allies,

00:22:31.600 --> 00:22:34.937
Pyongyang was confident it could be achieved.

00:22:34.937 --> 00:22:37.648
Third was to improve national defense.

00:22:37.648 --> 00:22:39.942
The army had to be rebuilt.

00:22:39.942 --> 00:22:42.278
The border had to be properly fortified,

00:22:42.278 --> 00:22:44.655
and they needed to secure modern equipment

00:22:44.655 --> 00:22:47.408
to stay competitive in a changing world.

00:22:47.408 --> 00:22:49.994
Last but not least, the unending goal

00:22:49.994 --> 00:22:52.079
of reunification remained.

00:22:52.079 --> 00:22:54.790
Kim's hopes had been shattered during the war,

00:22:54.790 --> 00:22:57.418
but he and other North Koreans remained convinced

00:22:57.418 --> 00:22:58.919
that it was possible.

00:22:58.919 --> 00:23:01.630
North Korea had its work cut out for it.

00:23:05.718 --> 00:23:07.386
Post-war purges.

00:23:08.387 --> 00:23:10.180
One of Kim's first priorities

00:23:10.180 --> 00:23:13.601
was repairing the damage his ideology took from the war.

00:23:13.601 --> 00:23:15.227
The North Korean Workers' Party

00:23:15.227 --> 00:23:17.521
had lost many members during the conflict,

00:23:17.521 --> 00:23:20.524
so he funded massive reeducation programs

00:23:20.524 --> 00:23:22.276
to bolster the party's ranks

00:23:22.276 --> 00:23:24.194
and reaffirm their ideology,

00:23:24.194 --> 00:23:26.864
ensuring the party's long-term survival.

00:23:26.864 --> 00:23:28.991
However, the more serious damage

00:23:28.991 --> 00:23:32.161
was to the North Korean Worker Party's prestige.

00:23:32.161 --> 00:23:34.788
The communists had presided over a failed war

00:23:34.788 --> 00:23:37.750
that had not reunified the country as promised,

00:23:37.750 --> 00:23:40.085
and communism itself had been rejected

00:23:40.085 --> 00:23:43.005
by the South Korean masses who failed to rise up

00:23:43.005 --> 00:23:45.174
to support their Northern invaders.

00:23:45.174 --> 00:23:46.967
Kim decided to redirect blame

00:23:46.967 --> 00:23:50.471
for those failures towards his internal rivals.

00:23:50.471 --> 00:23:52.181
By scapegoating his enemies,

00:23:52.181 --> 00:23:55.184
Kim redirected popular resentment away from himself

00:23:55.184 --> 00:23:58.187
and towards the rival communist factions.

00:23:58.187 --> 00:24:00.272
By removing these people from power,

00:24:00.272 --> 00:24:02.483
he crippled his internal enemies

00:24:02.483 --> 00:24:04.318
and could fill government positions

00:24:04.318 --> 00:24:06.195
with his own allies instead.

00:24:06.195 --> 00:24:08.489
It was transparent and predictable,

00:24:08.489 --> 00:24:10.741
but it was awfully effective.

00:24:10.741 --> 00:24:13.661
The Soviet Korean communist leader Ho Ka-I

00:24:13.661 --> 00:24:16.330
faced Kim's wrath towards the war's end.

00:24:16.330 --> 00:24:18.499
When he was purged of his posts and blamed

00:24:18.499 --> 00:24:21.168
for a series of failures in the country's response

00:24:21.168 --> 00:24:24.171
to the war, especially the slow repairs of dams

00:24:24.171 --> 00:24:27.049
and infrastructure bombed by the Americans,

00:24:27.049 --> 00:24:30.010
the accusations drove Ho Ka-I to suicide,

00:24:30.010 --> 00:24:32.012
or so the regime claimed.

00:24:32.012 --> 00:24:35.307
Another victim was Kim's old rival, Pak Hon-Yong.

00:24:35.307 --> 00:24:37.643
The leader of the South Korean communist faction

00:24:37.643 --> 00:24:40.813
had been appointed foreign minister and had promised Kim

00:24:40.813 --> 00:24:43.399
that the Southerners would rise up and join the North

00:24:43.399 --> 00:24:45.567
when their communist forces rolled in.

00:24:45.567 --> 00:24:47.736
This obviously did not happen.

00:24:47.736 --> 00:24:50.864
Kim dismissed him from his post in 1953

00:24:50.864 --> 00:24:53.158
and then had him arrested on accusations

00:24:53.158 --> 00:24:55.119
of being an American spy.

00:24:55.119 --> 00:24:57.579
Only disloyalty, the regime argued,

00:24:57.579 --> 00:25:00.249
could explain such a complete failure.

00:25:00.249 --> 00:25:05.254
He was given a show trial and executed in December, 1955.

00:25:05.295 --> 00:25:08.298
100s of communist figures found themselves fired,

00:25:08.298 --> 00:25:11.677
imprisoned, or executed in the months after the war

00:25:11.677 --> 00:25:13.178
in a similar fashion,

00:25:13.178 --> 00:25:16.515
and Kim's grip on power became ever tighter.

00:25:19.518 --> 00:25:21.186
Juche ideology.

00:25:22.771 --> 00:25:25.232
With Kim's power almost unchallenged,

00:25:25.232 --> 00:25:28.527
it fell to him to decide how North Korea would proceed.

00:25:28.527 --> 00:25:30.237
He formulated an ideology

00:25:30.237 --> 00:25:32.656
that would guide his country into the future.

00:25:32.656 --> 00:25:35.200
An ideology called Juche.

00:25:35.200 --> 00:25:38.412
Juche was and remains the guiding principle

00:25:38.412 --> 00:25:40.038
of the entire country.

00:25:40.038 --> 00:25:43.542
Its elements were first expressed in a 1955 speech

00:25:43.542 --> 00:25:47.796
by Kim Il-Sung, and it essentially means self-reliance.

00:25:47.796 --> 00:25:50.924
North Korea strives to be militarily, socially,

00:25:50.924 --> 00:25:54.636
and economically capable of standing on its own two feet.

00:25:54.636 --> 00:25:57.765
Cooperation with fellow socialist states was welcome,

00:25:57.765 --> 00:26:00.726
but dependence undermined the country's power.

00:26:00.726 --> 00:26:04.104
Economically this meant a rejection of international trade

00:26:04.104 --> 00:26:08.317
as the path to prosperity and a focus on self-sufficiency.

00:26:08.317 --> 00:26:10.652
The Democratic people's Republic of Korea

00:26:10.652 --> 00:26:13.322
would strive to grow all of its own food,

00:26:13.322 --> 00:26:15.407
develop all of its own technology,

00:26:15.407 --> 00:26:18.368
and extract all of its own raw materials.

00:26:18.368 --> 00:26:22.289
Socially it meant a thorough education in Juche ideology

00:26:22.289 --> 00:26:26.084
for all citizens and an insulation from outside ideas

00:26:26.084 --> 00:26:30.005
that might compromise the ideological unity of the nation.

00:26:30.005 --> 00:26:33.842
All of this, of course, was in a Marxist-Leninist framework,

00:26:33.842 --> 00:26:36.845
but Kim stressed that Korean thought and experiences

00:26:36.845 --> 00:26:39.765
should determine how those Marxist-Leninist ideas

00:26:39.765 --> 00:26:41.767
would be applied in practice.

00:26:41.767 --> 00:26:45.187
Juche also defined the North against the South.

00:26:45.187 --> 00:26:48.732
For Kim, the North was a fiercely independent nation

00:26:48.732 --> 00:26:49.983
that stood on its own,

00:26:49.983 --> 00:26:52.986
while the South was an American puppet shackled

00:26:52.986 --> 00:26:56.365
to its trading partners and military alliances.

00:26:56.365 --> 00:27:00.118
However, Juche is more than a practical philosophy.

00:27:00.118 --> 00:27:03.247
It's also an intense love of North Korea.

00:27:03.247 --> 00:27:05.916
One historian of North Korea described Juche

00:27:05.916 --> 00:27:10.170
as an assumption that Korea is at the center of the world.

00:27:10.170 --> 00:27:12.673
All citizens of the Democratic People's Republic

00:27:12.673 --> 00:27:16.093
of Korea must passionately love their country

00:27:16.093 --> 00:27:18.679
and by extension, its leader.

00:27:18.679 --> 00:27:20.931
Understanding Juche is the key

00:27:20.931 --> 00:27:23.475
to understanding modern North Korea.

00:27:27.688 --> 00:27:29.690
Kim's cult of personality.

00:27:31.024 --> 00:27:34.236
North Korea had a goal and a means of attaining it,

00:27:34.236 --> 00:27:37.656
but it also needed a center to anchor the whole system,

00:27:37.656 --> 00:27:40.367
and Kim made himself that center.

00:27:40.367 --> 00:27:43.996
The 20th century was already no stranger to dictators

00:27:43.996 --> 00:27:47.082
whose personality cults consumed their nations,

00:27:47.082 --> 00:27:50.919
but Kim Il-Sung's cult would put all of them to shame.

00:27:50.919 --> 00:27:53.630
The level of worship Kim and his descendants receive

00:27:53.630 --> 00:27:57.342
in North Korea to this day is one of the most striking

00:27:57.342 --> 00:27:59.845
and disturbing aspects of the regime.

00:27:59.845 --> 00:28:02.347
At first, Kim was following in the footsteps

00:28:02.347 --> 00:28:05.309
of his contemporaries like Mao and Stalin.

00:28:05.309 --> 00:28:10.314
In 1953, he declared himself Suryong, or great leader,

00:28:10.355 --> 00:28:13.400
and became a sort of embodiment of the nation.

00:28:13.400 --> 00:28:15.819
However, that amount of power and prestige

00:28:15.819 --> 00:28:18.447
could make anyone unhinged.

00:28:18.447 --> 00:28:21.783
Furthermore, by becoming the representative of the nation,

00:28:21.783 --> 00:28:25.495
any attack on Kim became an attack on North Korea.

00:28:25.495 --> 00:28:28.874
And in a country that emphasized loyalty to the nation,

00:28:28.874 --> 00:28:32.878
loyalty to the dictators was an inevitable consequence.

00:28:32.878 --> 00:28:35.255
This cult quickly grew out of control.

00:28:35.255 --> 00:28:38.467
It became illegal to write over a photo of Kim Il-Sung

00:28:38.467 --> 00:28:42.012
or to wrap things in newspapers that mentioned his name.

00:28:42.012 --> 00:28:44.514
It was even an offense to print his photo

00:28:44.514 --> 00:28:46.600
on poor-quality paper.

00:28:51.355 --> 00:28:53.440
The August faction incident.

00:28:55.609 --> 00:28:58.737
However, the ruler cult almost brought Kim down

00:28:58.737 --> 00:29:00.280
before he really began.

00:29:00.280 --> 00:29:01.823
After the death of Stalin,

00:29:01.823 --> 00:29:05.827
the USSR took a hard pivot against leader cults.

00:29:05.827 --> 00:29:08.038
In February, 1956,

00:29:08.038 --> 00:29:11.291
the new Soviet leader Khruschev openly denounced Stalin

00:29:11.291 --> 00:29:13.335
and his personality cult,

00:29:13.335 --> 00:29:16.588
along with any other leaders who tried to emulate it.

00:29:16.588 --> 00:29:19.424
Still dependent on Soviet aid and support,

00:29:19.424 --> 00:29:22.177
Kim was forced to obey when Khruschev summoned him

00:29:22.177 --> 00:29:26.348
to Moscow to be privately scolded for his own ruler cult

00:29:26.348 --> 00:29:27.933
in the summer of that year.

00:29:27.933 --> 00:29:29.643
In his absence, Soviet

00:29:29.643 --> 00:29:32.854
and Yan'an non-communist factions hatched a conspiracy.

00:29:32.854 --> 00:29:35.565
They shared Khruschev's disgusted with the ruler cult

00:29:35.565 --> 00:29:38.318
and called Sung out for his arbitrary punishment

00:29:38.318 --> 00:29:39.528
of dissenters.

00:29:39.528 --> 00:29:43.031
They also criticized his regime's economic policies

00:29:43.031 --> 00:29:46.576
and his bias towards his own gorilla faction of communists.

00:29:46.576 --> 00:29:48.912
When Kim returned for the annual party meeting

00:29:48.912 --> 00:29:52.040
in late August, he was met with condemnation by the leaders

00:29:52.040 --> 00:29:53.750
of the other factions.

00:29:53.750 --> 00:29:56.420
Pak Chang-Ok, leader of the Soviet faction,

00:29:56.420 --> 00:29:59.172
and Choe Chang-Ik, leader of the Yan'an Faction,

00:29:59.172 --> 00:30:01.174
along with several of their allies,

00:30:01.174 --> 00:30:03.552
took to the stage at the party conference

00:30:03.552 --> 00:30:06.763
and tore into Kim as a tyrant and egomaniac

00:30:06.763 --> 00:30:10.225
whose actions were undermining socialist principles,

00:30:10.225 --> 00:30:12.769
but Kim's enemies had miscalculated.

00:30:12.769 --> 00:30:16.815
The Soviet and Yan'an factions were too anchored in the USSR

00:30:16.815 --> 00:30:18.608
and China for their support.

00:30:18.608 --> 00:30:22.988
Meanwhile, Kim was a nationalist hero, a true Korean

00:30:22.988 --> 00:30:25.824
who had fought the gorilla fight to free his nation.

00:30:25.824 --> 00:30:30.162
For many, Kim represented Juche, self-reliance,

00:30:30.162 --> 00:30:32.330
while his enemies would submit North Korea

00:30:32.330 --> 00:30:34.750
to the powers of foreign nations.

00:30:34.750 --> 00:30:38.378
At the party conference, Kim's critics were shouted down.

00:30:38.378 --> 00:30:40.422
They overestimated their support

00:30:40.422 --> 00:30:42.883
and the party voted to expel Choe Chang-Ik

00:30:42.883 --> 00:30:44.092
and Pak Chang-Ok.

00:30:44.092 --> 00:30:45.635
Over the following months,

00:30:45.635 --> 00:30:48.346
dozens of leaders from both factions disappeared

00:30:48.346 --> 00:30:51.391
as Kim purged everyone he could lay his hands on.

00:30:51.391 --> 00:30:53.643
It is unknown how many people died,

00:30:53.643 --> 00:30:55.812
but it was so bad that Beijing

00:30:55.812 --> 00:30:59.232
and Moscow sent a joint delegation pleading with Kim

00:30:59.232 --> 00:31:00.984
to stop the purges.

00:31:00.984 --> 00:31:02.778
Kim simply ignored them.

00:31:02.778 --> 00:31:04.654
Most just disappeared.

00:31:04.654 --> 00:31:07.324
They were forgotten in hard labor camps

00:31:07.324 --> 00:31:09.951
or shot and buried in an unmarked grave.

00:31:09.951 --> 00:31:12.829
About 11 people were convicted in show trials

00:31:12.829 --> 00:31:15.415
and executed as enemies of the state.

00:31:15.415 --> 00:31:18.502
By 1960, Pak and Choe were dead.

00:31:18.502 --> 00:31:22.297
The Soviet and Yan'an factions had been completely destroyed

00:31:22.297 --> 00:31:24.758
and there was no one left in North Korea

00:31:24.758 --> 00:31:28.303
who would dare challenge Kim Il-Sung's power.

00:31:32.557 --> 00:31:37.270
The three year plan, 1954 to 1957.

00:31:37.270 --> 00:31:38.897
With politics dealt with,

00:31:38.897 --> 00:31:41.441
Kim turned towards economic issues.

00:31:41.441 --> 00:31:44.444
In August, 1953, he set out his vision

00:31:44.444 --> 00:31:47.739
for a three year plan to run from 1954 to 1956.

00:31:49.699 --> 00:31:53.120
Kim laid out investment plans to boost the nation's economy.

00:31:53.120 --> 00:31:55.372
Heavy industry was the main priority,

00:31:55.372 --> 00:31:58.542
with over 80% of all industrial investment going

00:31:58.542 --> 00:32:01.336
to sectors such as mining and construction.

00:32:01.336 --> 00:32:05.257
The plan also set out extensive quotas for every industry

00:32:05.257 --> 00:32:07.467
and directed workers to devote themselves

00:32:07.467 --> 00:32:09.094
to laboring for the state.

00:32:09.094 --> 00:32:12.013
According to Pyongyang, it was a success.

00:32:12.013 --> 00:32:14.307
Industrial and agricultural production

00:32:14.307 --> 00:32:18.270
had returned to their pre-war levels by early 1957.

00:32:18.270 --> 00:32:21.273
However, external observers noted that the numbers

00:32:21.273 --> 00:32:23.233
were probably skewed.

00:32:23.233 --> 00:32:24.943
Thanks to all of that investment,

00:32:24.943 --> 00:32:28.947
heavy industry had probably improved beyond pre-war levels,

00:32:28.947 --> 00:32:33.160
but vital industries like agriculture and fishing had not.

00:32:33.160 --> 00:32:35.996
In reality, the focus on quotas and output

00:32:35.996 --> 00:32:38.540
had devastating consequences.

00:32:38.540 --> 00:32:40.667
Like China, during the great famine,

00:32:40.667 --> 00:32:43.086
the regime exacerbated its own problems

00:32:43.086 --> 00:32:45.714
with its focus on quotas and numbers.

00:32:45.714 --> 00:32:48.758
Regional officials who failed to meet agricultural quotas

00:32:48.758 --> 00:32:49.634
were punished.

00:32:49.634 --> 00:32:52.721
So officials were incentivized to lie.

00:32:52.721 --> 00:32:54.472
This continued at each level.

00:32:54.472 --> 00:32:56.308
Lie piling upon lie,

00:32:56.308 --> 00:32:59.144
leaving Pyongyang with a completely warped view

00:32:59.144 --> 00:33:01.188
of the country's actual state.

00:33:01.188 --> 00:33:03.356
This was especially bad for farmers

00:33:03.356 --> 00:33:05.567
who would have food seized by the state based

00:33:05.567 --> 00:33:08.278
on exaggerated reports of food output,

00:33:08.278 --> 00:33:10.906
which produced a famine in 1955

00:33:10.906 --> 00:33:12.908
that killed 1,000s of people.

00:33:12.908 --> 00:33:16.244
This disaster was hidden from the non-communist world,

00:33:16.244 --> 00:33:19.039
but Pyongyang's allies in Beijing and Moscow

00:33:19.039 --> 00:33:20.624
were deeply concerned.

00:33:20.624 --> 00:33:22.125
The truth about the famine

00:33:22.125 --> 00:33:24.669
could harm Communism's image abroad.

00:33:24.669 --> 00:33:26.421
Both countries sent food aid,

00:33:26.421 --> 00:33:28.840
but not enough to make up for the deficit.

00:33:28.840 --> 00:33:32.344
The regime worked hard to bury all evidence of this famine,

00:33:32.344 --> 00:33:34.095
and it was only in the 2000s

00:33:34.095 --> 00:33:37.474
when historians began combing through the Soviet archives

00:33:37.474 --> 00:33:39.976
that its existence was rediscovered.

00:33:39.976 --> 00:33:44.940
Data is incomplete, but an estimated 800,000 people died

00:33:44.981 --> 00:33:46.816
between 1954 and 1955.

00:33:48.860 --> 00:33:51.154
The East German government at the time believed

00:33:51.154 --> 00:33:54.908
that as many as 25% of North Korea's children

00:33:54.908 --> 00:33:56.534
had starved to death.

00:34:00.288 --> 00:34:01.706
The five year plan.

00:34:03.458 --> 00:34:05.377
Declaring the plan of success,

00:34:05.377 --> 00:34:07.545
Kim followed it up with a five year plan

00:34:07.545 --> 00:34:10.924
from 1957 to 1961.

00:34:10.924 --> 00:34:13.718
While the farmer was for reconstruction,

00:34:13.718 --> 00:34:17.305
this new plan focused on developing in a new direction

00:34:17.305 --> 00:34:20.100
and bringing North Korea into modernity.

00:34:20.100 --> 00:34:22.852
The first plan had been great for industry,

00:34:22.852 --> 00:34:25.063
but the common people still lacked food,

00:34:25.063 --> 00:34:26.356
housing, and clothing.

00:34:26.356 --> 00:34:28.149
Pyongyang was still too obsessed

00:34:28.149 --> 00:34:31.528
with heavy industry quotas over agricultural output.

00:34:31.528 --> 00:34:35.323
Both China and the USSR criticized Kim's plan

00:34:35.323 --> 00:34:38.743
and urged him to change it, but Kim stayed his course.

00:34:38.743 --> 00:34:42.622
The Chollima Undong, or Flying Horses campaign,

00:34:42.622 --> 00:34:45.041
was Kim's way of ramping up production.

00:34:45.041 --> 00:34:47.544
It was a massive propaganda campaign

00:34:47.544 --> 00:34:49.170
to encourage productivity

00:34:49.170 --> 00:34:52.424
and gave out rewards such as medals for factories

00:34:52.424 --> 00:34:55.468
and workers who exceeded their monthly quotas.

00:34:55.468 --> 00:34:58.138
Workers could also be organized into teams

00:34:58.138 --> 00:35:01.057
and compete with other teams for maximum output.

00:35:01.057 --> 00:35:04.352
They may be communists, but even North Korea realized

00:35:04.352 --> 00:35:07.022
that competition could be good for the economy.

00:35:07.022 --> 00:35:10.442
The press was filled with these Chollima Riders,

00:35:10.442 --> 00:35:14.404
whose hard work was held up as a symbol of true patriotism.

00:35:14.404 --> 00:35:16.698
Kim also took to visiting production sites

00:35:16.698 --> 00:35:18.992
to encourage and inspire the workers,

00:35:18.992 --> 00:35:22.495
which became huge propaganda features for the regime.

00:35:22.495 --> 00:35:25.749
Another key part of Kim's motivation campaign

00:35:25.749 --> 00:35:28.543
were on the spot guidance visits,

00:35:28.543 --> 00:35:31.463
where Kim would visit farms, factories,

00:35:31.463 --> 00:35:34.090
or other facilities to motivate workers.

00:35:34.090 --> 00:35:37.761
According to the propaganda, he would use his immense wisdom

00:35:37.761 --> 00:35:41.056
to instruct the workers how to be better at their jobs

00:35:41.056 --> 00:35:42.640
and achieve their quotas.

00:35:42.640 --> 00:35:46.811
On the spot guidance has become one of the most iconic parts

00:35:46.811 --> 00:35:48.521
of regime propaganda

00:35:48.521 --> 00:35:52.567
and has been kept up by all of Kim Il-Sung's successors.

00:35:52.567 --> 00:35:54.819
Their motivation campaigns were combined

00:35:54.819 --> 00:35:58.239
with nationalization and reorganization that tightened state

00:35:58.239 --> 00:36:00.283
and party control of the economy.

00:36:00.283 --> 00:36:04.913
By 1958, North Korea had collectivized every farm,

00:36:04.913 --> 00:36:06.581
and by the following year,

00:36:06.581 --> 00:36:08.666
it had reached full nationalization

00:36:08.666 --> 00:36:10.752
of all industry and trade.

00:36:10.752 --> 00:36:12.128
The obsession with quotas

00:36:12.128 --> 00:36:15.006
and productivity also had its dark sides.

00:36:15.006 --> 00:36:18.259
The pressure to exceed and expand led to punishment

00:36:18.259 --> 00:36:20.887
and social consequences for workers or teams

00:36:20.887 --> 00:36:22.055
who fell behind.

00:36:22.055 --> 00:36:25.725
The government even started a "drink no soup" campaign,

00:36:25.725 --> 00:36:28.812
encouraging workers to not eat or drink as much

00:36:28.812 --> 00:36:30.814
so they wouldn't have to go to the bathroom

00:36:30.814 --> 00:36:32.357
during work hours.

00:36:35.985 --> 00:36:39.280
The five year plan, success or failure?

00:36:40.865 --> 00:36:43.326
So was it all a success?

00:36:43.326 --> 00:36:44.869
It's not so simple.

00:36:44.869 --> 00:36:48.706
The more Kim pushed, the more the workers were exhausted.

00:36:48.706 --> 00:36:51.084
The quality of work started to decline,

00:36:51.084 --> 00:36:53.420
even as the quantity increased.

00:36:53.420 --> 00:36:55.839
Kim complained that companies were being lazy

00:36:55.839 --> 00:36:57.841
and would rush to meet their monthly quotas

00:36:57.841 --> 00:37:00.760
with shoddy worksmanship of goods and materials.

00:37:00.760 --> 00:37:04.514
And by the late 1950s and early 1960s,

00:37:04.514 --> 00:37:06.766
production growth had stalled again.

00:37:06.766 --> 00:37:09.102
In theory, by 1959,

00:37:09.102 --> 00:37:11.521
North Korea had met its production quotas

00:37:11.521 --> 00:37:13.982
and the government declared the plan completed ahead

00:37:13.982 --> 00:37:14.858
of schedule.

00:37:14.858 --> 00:37:18.111
The big picture numbers definitely looked great.

00:37:18.111 --> 00:37:22.031
The North's per capita GDP was $140,

00:37:22.031 --> 00:37:24.701
well above the South's $81,

00:37:24.701 --> 00:37:27.328
and many industries had seen increases in production

00:37:27.328 --> 00:37:29.289
by 50% or more.

00:37:29.289 --> 00:37:32.876
However, the GDP was inflated by industrial output

00:37:32.876 --> 00:37:35.086
at the expense of the food, clothing,

00:37:35.086 --> 00:37:38.131
and housing that Kim claimed to prioritize.

00:37:38.131 --> 00:37:41.259
The average North Korean remained wretchedly poor,

00:37:41.259 --> 00:37:43.678
living in temporary shanty towns

00:37:43.678 --> 00:37:46.347
and many of them suffered from malnutrition.

00:37:46.347 --> 00:37:49.184
Industrial development came before the wellbeing

00:37:49.184 --> 00:37:50.143
of the people.

00:37:50.143 --> 00:37:52.061
The state also altered the numbers

00:37:52.061 --> 00:37:55.482
to not count industries such as coal, steel, copper,

00:37:55.482 --> 00:37:57.942
and fertilizer, which had all failed

00:37:57.942 --> 00:37:59.527
to meet their plan targets.

00:37:59.527 --> 00:38:02.322
Grain output was also curiously absent

00:38:02.322 --> 00:38:05.492
from the official 1959 statistics.

00:38:05.492 --> 00:38:08.745
It's telling that the government immediately planned a year

00:38:08.745 --> 00:38:12.999
of adjustment in 1960 to try and rebalance the numbers

00:38:12.999 --> 00:38:16.127
in preparation for a new phase of economic planning

00:38:16.127 --> 00:38:18.046
into the 1960s,

00:38:18.046 --> 00:38:21.508
and never again would North Korea publish thorough data

00:38:21.508 --> 00:38:23.718
about its economic situation.

00:38:27.514 --> 00:38:29.599
Songbun - class system.

00:38:31.476 --> 00:38:34.062
Alongside economic reorganization,

00:38:34.062 --> 00:38:37.607
the 1950 saw a social reorganization

00:38:37.607 --> 00:38:40.318
with the introduction of the songbun system.

00:38:40.318 --> 00:38:44.531
Songbun is essentially a caste system that is still upheld

00:38:44.531 --> 00:38:47.116
in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.

00:38:47.116 --> 00:38:50.203
It was launched in 1957 to distinguish

00:38:50.203 --> 00:38:53.831
between those families who were always loyal to the regime

00:38:53.831 --> 00:38:56.292
and those who were not to be trusted.

00:38:56.292 --> 00:39:00.213
There are three overarching classes in the songbun system.

00:39:00.213 --> 00:39:03.841
The core comprise about 28% of the population,

00:39:03.841 --> 00:39:06.970
made up of those people descended from the original gorillas

00:39:06.970 --> 00:39:10.557
and revolutionaries, the soldiers who died in the war,

00:39:10.557 --> 00:39:13.518
and those from traditional peasant families.

00:39:13.518 --> 00:39:16.646
This group is seen as the most loyal and trustworthy.

00:39:16.646 --> 00:39:18.940
They will be allies to the end.

00:39:18.940 --> 00:39:22.777
The largest group at 45% are the wavering.

00:39:22.777 --> 00:39:25.446
This includes the foreign born population,

00:39:25.446 --> 00:39:27.156
families of defectors,

00:39:27.156 --> 00:39:29.993
members of the middle classes and their families,

00:39:29.993 --> 00:39:33.037
and a number of regular occupations like small traders

00:39:33.037 --> 00:39:34.122
and teachers.

00:39:34.122 --> 00:39:36.666
This group is not necessarily disloyal,

00:39:36.666 --> 00:39:38.167
but they cannot be trusted

00:39:38.167 --> 00:39:40.545
to be completely devoted to the regime.

00:39:40.545 --> 00:39:44.173
If things take a bad turn economically or politically,

00:39:44.173 --> 00:39:47.427
the regime knows that these people might turn against them.

00:39:47.427 --> 00:39:51.180
Lastly, roughly 27% of the population belong

00:39:51.180 --> 00:39:53.141
to the hostile class.

00:39:53.141 --> 00:39:55.602
Political prisoners, religious people,

00:39:55.602 --> 00:39:58.938
supporters of the South or the descendants of businessmen

00:39:58.938 --> 00:40:01.983
and landlords all belong to this group.

00:40:01.983 --> 00:40:04.319
These people are not to be trusted

00:40:04.319 --> 00:40:08.281
and must be closely monitored for any hint of disloyalty

00:40:08.281 --> 00:40:10.575
or anti-communist action.

00:40:10.575 --> 00:40:13.870
Every North Korean is sorted into one of these classes

00:40:13.870 --> 00:40:17.248
and then sorted into one of 50 subcategories within it.

00:40:17.248 --> 00:40:20.835
Those higher up the songbun scale can expect privileges,

00:40:20.835 --> 00:40:23.212
and having good songbun is the key

00:40:23.212 --> 00:40:25.298
to a good life in North Korea.

00:40:25.298 --> 00:40:28.051
On the other hand, those with bad songbun

00:40:28.051 --> 00:40:30.553
can expect to be discriminated against.

00:40:30.553 --> 00:40:32.597
Songbun affects everything,

00:40:32.597 --> 00:40:35.350
what jobs one can have, who they can marry,

00:40:35.350 --> 00:40:38.478
what healthcare they have, what schools they can get into,

00:40:38.478 --> 00:40:41.814
and even how much food is distributed to them.

00:40:41.814 --> 00:40:44.859
The regime maintains a file on every North Korean

00:40:44.859 --> 00:40:48.196
above the age of 17 to keep track of their songbun.

00:40:48.196 --> 00:40:50.823
Good deeds might move one up the songbun scale,

00:40:50.823 --> 00:40:53.951
but moving up is much harder than moving down.

00:40:53.951 --> 00:40:56.204
Missing work quotas, committing a crime

00:40:56.204 --> 00:40:58.665
or showing any disloyalty to the regime

00:40:58.665 --> 00:41:01.042
are always bad for your songbun.

00:41:06.255 --> 00:41:08.341
Propaganda overdrive.

00:41:09.676 --> 00:41:12.345
Amidst this social and economic reform,

00:41:12.345 --> 00:41:15.640
the regime kept pumping out propaganda to tell citizens

00:41:15.640 --> 00:41:17.266
that they were fortunate to live

00:41:17.266 --> 00:41:19.811
in the greatest nation on earth.

00:41:19.811 --> 00:41:22.897
The regime claimed that North Korea was a paradise,

00:41:22.897 --> 00:41:26.901
free from the miseries that affected other lesser nations.

00:41:26.901 --> 00:41:29.195
According to one kindergarten teacher,

00:41:29.195 --> 00:41:31.239
there was no such thing as blindness

00:41:31.239 --> 00:41:33.658
or deafness in North Korean children

00:41:33.658 --> 00:41:37.453
because those were failures of the pre-revolutionary world.

00:41:37.453 --> 00:41:40.957
According to school teachers, students never missed a lesson

00:41:40.957 --> 00:41:42.583
and never misbehaved.

00:41:42.583 --> 00:41:45.002
There was no such thing as alcoholism

00:41:45.002 --> 00:41:47.213
or prostitution in North Korea

00:41:47.213 --> 00:41:49.382
because everyone had what they needed

00:41:49.382 --> 00:41:52.009
and never had to stoop to such lows.

00:41:52.009 --> 00:41:56.389
Divorce, that never happened, neither did premarital sex.

00:41:56.389 --> 00:41:59.517
And of course it wouldn't be a communist utopia

00:41:59.517 --> 00:42:02.770
without a complete absence of homosexuality,

00:42:02.770 --> 00:42:06.607
which the regime saw as an anti-socialist perversion.

00:42:06.607 --> 00:42:08.943
The truth was quite different.

00:42:08.943 --> 00:42:10.987
The regime took care to hide its flaws

00:42:10.987 --> 00:42:13.781
from the eyes of the world, even its own people,

00:42:13.781 --> 00:42:17.285
while trumpeting its supposed success to the stars,

00:42:17.285 --> 00:42:19.162
but there was something sinister

00:42:19.162 --> 00:42:21.372
behind this image of perfection.

00:42:21.372 --> 00:42:23.207
One visitor to North Korea noted

00:42:23.207 --> 00:42:25.251
that despite the war being recent

00:42:25.251 --> 00:42:27.628
and causing 1,000s of injuries,

00:42:27.628 --> 00:42:30.548
he never saw a single person who was scarred,

00:42:30.548 --> 00:42:32.592
mutilated or disabled.

00:42:32.592 --> 00:42:34.093
The question was obvious.

00:42:34.093 --> 00:42:36.345
He said, what have they done with them all?

00:42:36.345 --> 00:42:39.348
The truth was that anything or anyone

00:42:39.348 --> 00:42:42.435
that made the regime look bad or question its image

00:42:42.435 --> 00:42:44.187
was taken out of the public eye.

00:42:44.187 --> 00:42:46.063
Some were merely hidden,

00:42:46.063 --> 00:42:49.901
but others would see the dark underside of the Kim regime.

00:42:54.530 --> 00:42:56.240
Punishment in North Korea.

00:42:57.909 --> 00:43:01.621
A regime like North Korea needed ways to punish dissenters

00:43:01.621 --> 00:43:03.623
and the elaborate system of prison

00:43:03.623 --> 00:43:07.001
and labor camps first set up by Kim Il-Sung's government

00:43:07.001 --> 00:43:08.878
are some of the most effective

00:43:08.878 --> 00:43:11.923
and terrifying examples in the world.

00:43:11.923 --> 00:43:15.259
It is easy to end up in a North Korean prison,

00:43:15.259 --> 00:43:18.346
the slightest accusation of disloyalty

00:43:18.346 --> 00:43:21.557
or anti-socialist activity from a party official

00:43:21.557 --> 00:43:24.185
or someone higher up the songbun scale

00:43:24.185 --> 00:43:27.146
could be enough for someone to be swept away by the police.

00:43:27.146 --> 00:43:31.067
Trials are a little more than ideological performances

00:43:31.067 --> 00:43:32.985
where the judge can berate the accused

00:43:32.985 --> 00:43:35.947
for being a traitor and enemy to North Korea

00:43:35.947 --> 00:43:37.990
before being inevitably sentenced

00:43:37.990 --> 00:43:40.243
to several years in prison.

00:43:40.243 --> 00:43:43.037
The North Korean prison system borrowed heavily

00:43:43.037 --> 00:43:45.790
from Stalin's infamous gulags.

00:43:45.790 --> 00:43:49.085
They were designed to handle not only regular criminals

00:43:49.085 --> 00:43:51.045
but political dissidents,

00:43:51.045 --> 00:43:54.257
whose only crimes were against the ideas of the regime.

00:43:54.257 --> 00:43:59.136
Virtually all North Korean prisons were and are labor camps.

00:43:59.136 --> 00:44:02.682
Inmates are subjected to forced labor to produce goods

00:44:02.682 --> 00:44:05.351
or extract raw materials for the regime.

00:44:05.351 --> 00:44:09.021
This ensures that the inmates labor isn't wasted in idleness

00:44:09.021 --> 00:44:13.025
and in theory, gives them labor skills and work ethic

00:44:13.025 --> 00:44:14.318
that those who are lucky enough

00:44:14.318 --> 00:44:17.822
to be released might remember when they return to society.

00:44:17.822 --> 00:44:21.367
Many prisons also serve as reeducation camps.

00:44:21.367 --> 00:44:23.953
These places are known as Kyohwaso.

00:44:23.953 --> 00:44:26.289
Then there are concentration camps

00:44:26.289 --> 00:44:29.166
for political prisoners known as Kwanliso.

00:44:29.166 --> 00:44:33.129
These are for the prisoners for whom reeducation won't work

00:44:33.129 --> 00:44:36.132
and only hard labor or total isolation

00:44:36.132 --> 00:44:37.884
are suitable punishments.

00:44:37.884 --> 00:44:40.386
Political rivals such as those purged

00:44:40.386 --> 00:44:42.555
after the August faction incident,

00:44:42.555 --> 00:44:45.308
dissidents, critics attempted defectors,

00:44:45.308 --> 00:44:48.477
and sometimes the more serious violent criminals

00:44:48.477 --> 00:44:50.897
are likely to end up in these camps.

00:44:50.897 --> 00:44:54.609
Prisoners in all camps are subject to poor living conditions

00:44:54.609 --> 00:44:56.903
and barely enough food to survive.

00:44:56.903 --> 00:44:58.738
Beatings are a common punishment.

00:44:58.738 --> 00:45:00.823
And one former camp guard estimated

00:45:00.823 --> 00:45:03.701
that at least a third of inmates were mutilated,

00:45:03.701 --> 00:45:07.747
losing fingers, ears, or eyes to guard beatings.

00:45:07.747 --> 00:45:10.833
That same guard recalled that as far as the regime

00:45:10.833 --> 00:45:14.086
was concerned, inmates are not humans

00:45:14.086 --> 00:45:16.213
and there are no human rights protections

00:45:16.213 --> 00:45:19.050
for anyone in North Korean captivity.

00:45:19.050 --> 00:45:22.219
With Kim's power secure, the economy recovering,

00:45:22.219 --> 00:45:25.306
society realigning along socialist lines,

00:45:25.306 --> 00:45:28.476
and all of the opponents rapidly ending up in camps

00:45:28.476 --> 00:45:31.771
or graves, North Korea entered the 1960s

00:45:31.771 --> 00:45:34.148
with everything to play for.

00:45:39.278 --> 00:45:42.448
Challenges and triumphs.

00:45:42.448 --> 00:45:44.408
The great leap onward.

00:45:45.993 --> 00:45:48.996
As the new decade dawned, North Korea continued

00:45:48.996 --> 00:45:52.124
to strive for economic and military progress.

00:45:52.124 --> 00:45:54.752
Kim still wanted to improve heavy industry

00:45:54.752 --> 00:45:58.381
and compromised on the policy of Juche to import equipment

00:45:58.381 --> 00:46:00.925
to support these economic sectors.

00:46:00.925 --> 00:46:03.970
The USSR was initially their main supplier,

00:46:03.970 --> 00:46:07.306
but friction over pricing and other issues led North Korea

00:46:07.306 --> 00:46:10.851
to do the unthinkable, turn to the West.

00:46:10.851 --> 00:46:12.979
Pyongyang realized that it was cheaper

00:46:12.979 --> 00:46:14.814
for them to buy industrial plants

00:46:14.814 --> 00:46:17.984
and machinery equipment from the West or Japan.

00:46:17.984 --> 00:46:20.444
Often these goods were of much higher quality

00:46:20.444 --> 00:46:22.154
than the Soviet models.

00:46:22.154 --> 00:46:25.449
Kim declared the Great Leap Onward policy,

00:46:25.449 --> 00:46:27.284
a way to use Western technology

00:46:27.284 --> 00:46:29.328
to jumpstart Korean development.

00:46:29.328 --> 00:46:31.539
They imported billions of dollars worth

00:46:31.539 --> 00:46:33.124
of equipment on credit,

00:46:33.124 --> 00:46:36.794
including $1 billion from Japan alone.

00:46:36.794 --> 00:46:39.797
Western businesses were happy to embrace a new market

00:46:39.797 --> 00:46:40.715
for the goods

00:46:40.715 --> 00:46:42.967
and the fact that they were snubbing the Soviets

00:46:42.967 --> 00:46:44.176
didn't hurt either.

00:46:44.176 --> 00:46:46.470
In turn, North Korea used the equipment

00:46:46.470 --> 00:46:49.765
to establish the world's largest cement factory

00:46:49.765 --> 00:46:52.852
as well as production facilities for steel, paper,

00:46:52.852 --> 00:46:54.979
fertilizer, and chemicals.

00:46:54.979 --> 00:46:57.857
Overall, the West went from almost nothing

00:46:57.857 --> 00:47:01.694
to being over 40% of total North Korea trade.

00:47:01.694 --> 00:47:04.155
These brief years of interaction in the '60s

00:47:04.155 --> 00:47:06.574
and '70s soon faded, however,

00:47:06.574 --> 00:47:09.076
when it became clear that the North Koreans

00:47:09.076 --> 00:47:11.370
who had been buying everything on credit

00:47:11.370 --> 00:47:13.205
were never going to pay it back.

00:47:16.917 --> 00:47:19.420
Defection of James Joseph Dresnok.

00:47:20.921 --> 00:47:23.507
This interaction did generate Western interest

00:47:23.507 --> 00:47:24.842
in the hermit kingdom

00:47:24.842 --> 00:47:27.762
and a special temptation for a handful of men,

00:47:27.762 --> 00:47:30.347
men like James Joseph Dresnok.

00:47:30.347 --> 00:47:33.768
Dresnok was a US soldier and he'd had a rough life.

00:47:33.768 --> 00:47:35.853
His parents divorced when he was young.

00:47:35.853 --> 00:47:37.480
He'd never finished high school

00:47:37.480 --> 00:47:40.858
and he had a run-ins with the law before he enlisted at 17.

00:47:40.858 --> 00:47:43.652
He married young, but returned from a deployment in Germany

00:47:43.652 --> 00:47:46.322
to find his wife had left him for another man.

00:47:46.322 --> 00:47:50.701
When Dresnok was redeployed to South Korea in 1962,

00:47:50.701 --> 00:47:52.119
he had lost all hope

00:47:52.119 --> 00:47:54.789
and was treating his depression with alcohol.

00:47:54.789 --> 00:47:55.623
It didn't help

00:47:55.623 --> 00:47:58.375
that his behavior earned him a court marshal either.

00:47:58.375 --> 00:48:01.170
With no wife, no career, and no future,

00:48:01.170 --> 00:48:03.881
Dresnok decided that life in the DPRK

00:48:03.881 --> 00:48:06.926
couldn't possibly be worse than his current one.

00:48:06.926 --> 00:48:10.179
So on August 15th, 1962,

00:48:10.179 --> 00:48:14.141
Dresnok ran across a minefield in the demilitarized zone

00:48:14.141 --> 00:48:15.643
and straight into the arms

00:48:15.643 --> 00:48:19.063
of some rather shocked North Korean soldiers.

00:48:19.063 --> 00:48:21.857
Dresnok was interrogated, but they soon realized

00:48:21.857 --> 00:48:24.860
that he genuinely wished to live in North Korea.

00:48:24.860 --> 00:48:28.114
After initial hesitation, the regime accepted him.

00:48:28.114 --> 00:48:29.740
Dresnok was given a home

00:48:29.740 --> 00:48:32.076
and became a North Korean citizen.

00:48:32.076 --> 00:48:35.496
He was one of at least seven known US defectors

00:48:35.496 --> 00:48:36.580
to the country.

00:48:36.580 --> 00:48:38.499
In his new life in North Korea,

00:48:38.499 --> 00:48:40.543
Dresnok became an English teacher

00:48:40.543 --> 00:48:43.796
and sometimes acted in state propaganda films.

00:48:43.796 --> 00:48:44.713
He and the handful

00:48:44.713 --> 00:48:47.883
of other American defectors often played American soldiers

00:48:47.883 --> 00:48:51.387
in war films, and he became something of a celebrity

00:48:51.387 --> 00:48:52.513
in the country.

00:48:52.513 --> 00:48:55.516
Another defector who later returned to the West claimed

00:48:55.516 --> 00:48:59.019
that they were closely monitored by state security services

00:48:59.019 --> 00:49:01.480
and were sometimes beaten or interrogated

00:49:01.480 --> 00:49:03.524
on suspicion of being spies,

00:49:03.524 --> 00:49:07.611
but if this is true, it did not seem to deter Dresnok.

00:49:07.611 --> 00:49:10.406
Dresnok lived the rest of his life in North Korea.

00:49:10.406 --> 00:49:12.616
He married twice and had several children

00:49:12.616 --> 00:49:15.286
before dying in November, 2016.

00:49:15.286 --> 00:49:17.413
His children remain in North Korea

00:49:17.413 --> 00:49:18.873
where they hold important jobs

00:49:18.873 --> 00:49:21.709
and plan to remain there for the rest of their lives.

00:49:24.795 --> 00:49:26.755
Military of Kim Il-Sung.

00:49:27.840 --> 00:49:29.592
A few defections like Dresnok

00:49:29.592 --> 00:49:32.386
were not going to redress the military imbalance

00:49:32.386 --> 00:49:35.055
between North Korea and the US, though.

00:49:35.055 --> 00:49:37.266
In the 1960s, Kim focused

00:49:37.266 --> 00:49:40.144
on rebuilding his decimated military,

00:49:40.144 --> 00:49:43.105
using the rebuilt economic strength of his nation

00:49:43.105 --> 00:49:45.691
to re-arm and upgrade his massive army.

00:49:45.691 --> 00:49:48.944
The government coined the slogan "arms in one hand,

00:49:48.944 --> 00:49:50.905
hammer and sickle in the other"

00:49:50.905 --> 00:49:53.657
to emphasize the importance of the military

00:49:53.657 --> 00:49:55.409
to their vision of the country.

00:49:55.409 --> 00:49:58.829
North Korea continued to recruit soldiers into its military.

00:49:58.829 --> 00:50:00.206
All eligible citizens

00:50:00.206 --> 00:50:03.125
had to serve eight years in one branch or another.

00:50:03.125 --> 00:50:05.544
Most of its equipment was still being given to them

00:50:05.544 --> 00:50:09.798
by the USSR and China well into the 1950s.

00:50:09.798 --> 00:50:13.928
Maybe 5% of its annual expenditure went to the military,

00:50:13.928 --> 00:50:15.221
most in most nations,

00:50:15.221 --> 00:50:18.098
but not as high as it would be in later years.

00:50:18.098 --> 00:50:21.310
With no wars to fight, the soldiers were regularly assigned

00:50:21.310 --> 00:50:23.270
to work projects around the country,

00:50:23.270 --> 00:50:25.272
providing an easy labor force

00:50:25.272 --> 00:50:27.983
that could be deployed wherever the state needed them.

00:50:27.983 --> 00:50:30.861
On top of its obvious use, if war broke out,

00:50:30.861 --> 00:50:33.113
a strong military was a useful way

00:50:33.113 --> 00:50:36.367
to indoctrinate young people with state ideology.

00:50:36.367 --> 00:50:39.286
Kim wanted to inculcate military discipline

00:50:39.286 --> 00:50:43.123
in the next generation and required all children to practice

00:50:43.123 --> 00:50:46.877
with firearms, starting when they were seven years old.

00:50:46.877 --> 00:50:50.297
This military resurgence had economic benefits too.

00:50:50.297 --> 00:50:53.926
Kim envisioned a militarily self-sufficient North Korea

00:50:53.926 --> 00:50:56.512
that could boost its economy by churning out a rifle

00:50:56.512 --> 00:51:00.099
for every citizen and enough tanks, planes, and artillery

00:51:00.099 --> 00:51:03.060
to match the South and its American allies.

00:51:03.060 --> 00:51:05.437
This concept was called Byungjin,

00:51:05.437 --> 00:51:08.565
and argued that military development was deeply tied

00:51:08.565 --> 00:51:10.401
to economic development.

00:51:10.401 --> 00:51:11.777
And it has remained relevant

00:51:11.777 --> 00:51:14.238
in North Korean thought ever since.

00:51:14.238 --> 00:51:16.115
As the military grew in power,

00:51:16.115 --> 00:51:18.742
Kim purged unreliable officials.

00:51:18.742 --> 00:51:21.662
In the late 1960s, top military men

00:51:21.662 --> 00:51:23.998
like the Minister of National Security,

00:51:23.998 --> 00:51:26.125
the Chief of Southern Intelligence,

00:51:26.125 --> 00:51:28.460
and the Commander in Chief of the Navy,

00:51:28.460 --> 00:51:31.046
along with at least 10 top generals,

00:51:31.046 --> 00:51:32.631
were removed from power.

00:51:32.631 --> 00:51:35.050
This was less a case of them being a threat

00:51:35.050 --> 00:51:38.470
and more a case of Kim simply tightening his control

00:51:38.470 --> 00:51:42.349
to replace these men with even more dependable allies.

00:51:47.104 --> 00:51:49.148
Communist power politics.

00:51:50.482 --> 00:51:53.360
While still providing economic aid to Pyongyang,

00:51:53.360 --> 00:51:55.237
Moscow and Beijing's relationship

00:51:55.237 --> 00:51:58.991
with the strange little regime was not smooth sailing.

00:51:58.991 --> 00:52:02.619
Moscow was still uncomfortable with Kim's personality cult,

00:52:02.619 --> 00:52:05.497
but it was China who was most unhappy with Kim.

00:52:05.497 --> 00:52:08.334
North Korea's poor performance in the Korean War

00:52:08.334 --> 00:52:11.086
had earned them a low opinion in China's political

00:52:11.086 --> 00:52:12.671
and military leadership

00:52:12.671 --> 00:52:15.049
and the fact that China had to take up most

00:52:15.049 --> 00:52:16.258
of the manpower burden

00:52:16.258 --> 00:52:20.054
of the conflict created resentment against the Kim regime.

00:52:20.054 --> 00:52:23.265
Kim's tied control over the state also conflicted

00:52:23.265 --> 00:52:26.560
with Mao's enthusiasm for popular revolution.

00:52:26.560 --> 00:52:29.855
When Mao's Legion of Red Guard's student activist launched

00:52:29.855 --> 00:52:34.693
the Cultural Revolution in 1966, waging a campaign of terror

00:52:34.693 --> 00:52:37.780
and vandalism against rival communist factions

00:52:37.780 --> 00:52:40.824
and symbols of Chinese tradition across the country,

00:52:40.824 --> 00:52:42.493
Kim Il-Sung condemned them.

00:52:42.493 --> 00:52:46.080
To him, it was a dangerous act of popular unrest

00:52:46.080 --> 00:52:49.083
that risked undermining the stability of the country.

00:52:49.083 --> 00:52:51.335
The Red Guards had no love for him either

00:52:51.335 --> 00:52:54.546
and dubbed him "a fat revisionist"

00:52:54.546 --> 00:52:57.716
who was not worthy of being called a communist

00:53:03.639 --> 00:53:05.766
Korean DMZ conflict.

00:53:07.017 --> 00:53:09.436
Perhaps it was these wounds to his pride

00:53:09.436 --> 00:53:11.355
and questions about his credentials

00:53:11.355 --> 00:53:16.360
that made Kim Il-Sung lash out at his enemies in 1966.

00:53:16.360 --> 00:53:18.654
Inspired by the work of the Viet Cong,

00:53:18.654 --> 00:53:21.907
Kim Ong devised plans for gorilla infiltrators

00:53:21.907 --> 00:53:25.994
to slip across the DMZ and wreak havoc on the South.

00:53:25.994 --> 00:53:28.330
After over a decade of stalemate,

00:53:28.330 --> 00:53:31.625
it seemed he wanted to roll the dice on conflict once more.

00:53:31.625 --> 00:53:35.087
Incursions and even firefights along the DMZ

00:53:35.087 --> 00:53:36.338
were not unheard of,

00:53:36.338 --> 00:53:39.675
and there were usually a few dozen encounters a year.

00:53:39.675 --> 00:53:44.054
However, in 1966, these increased tenfold.

00:53:44.054 --> 00:53:46.140
There were almost daily skirmishes

00:53:46.140 --> 00:53:47.558
as North Korean gorillas

00:53:47.558 --> 00:53:49.893
were caught in South Korean territory.

00:53:49.893 --> 00:53:53.522
As tensions rose, border guards became more on edge

00:53:53.522 --> 00:53:57.317
and started to resolve disputes with aggression and gunfire.

00:53:57.317 --> 00:54:00.904
This period is sometimes called the second Korean War,

00:54:00.904 --> 00:54:02.865
but there were no major battles.

00:54:02.865 --> 00:54:05.033
Rather than a concerted campaign,

00:54:05.033 --> 00:54:08.954
it was 100s of tiny skirmishes and gorilla attacks.

00:54:08.954 --> 00:54:11.039
There were casualties on both sides,

00:54:11.039 --> 00:54:14.710
and the US declared the area around the demilitarized zone

00:54:14.710 --> 00:54:16.628
a hostile fire zone.

00:54:21.133 --> 00:54:22.301
Blue House raid.

00:54:23.552 --> 00:54:27.681
By far the most dire episode of the conflict was a daring

00:54:27.681 --> 00:54:31.185
and disastrous North Korean assassination attempt

00:54:31.185 --> 00:54:33.187
on the South Korean president.

00:54:33.187 --> 00:54:34.062
They were convinced

00:54:34.062 --> 00:54:36.106
that eliminating President Park Chung Hee,

00:54:36.106 --> 00:54:37.941
he wouldn't just weaken the South,

00:54:37.941 --> 00:54:41.069
but cause chaos from which the people would rise up,

00:54:41.069 --> 00:54:44.907
throw out the American occupiers, and embrace communism.

00:54:44.907 --> 00:54:48.327
On the night of January 17th, 1968,

00:54:48.327 --> 00:54:52.539
31 elite North Korean commandos slipped across the DMZ

00:54:52.539 --> 00:54:53.707
into the South.

00:54:53.707 --> 00:54:56.668
Their goal, infiltrate President Park's residence

00:54:56.668 --> 00:54:59.671
at the Blue House in Seoul and eliminate him.

00:54:59.671 --> 00:55:01.965
Each man and the team had been handpicked

00:55:01.965 --> 00:55:03.967
and trained in infiltration.

00:55:03.967 --> 00:55:06.970
They'd rehearsed this mission dozens of times,

00:55:06.970 --> 00:55:09.264
and most of all, they'd been pumped full

00:55:09.264 --> 00:55:11.475
of North Korean propaganda.

00:55:11.475 --> 00:55:13.894
They avoided detection for several days,

00:55:13.894 --> 00:55:16.939
until they encountered four civilian wood cutters.

00:55:16.939 --> 00:55:19.107
These civilians might have feared death,

00:55:19.107 --> 00:55:21.860
but they were saved by the delusional propaganda

00:55:21.860 --> 00:55:22.903
of the North.

00:55:22.903 --> 00:55:25.155
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea

00:55:25.155 --> 00:55:27.616
had assured its people that these Southern masses

00:55:27.616 --> 00:55:31.245
were oppressed and eager to embrace communism.

00:55:31.245 --> 00:55:33.455
The soldiers simply explained the virtues

00:55:33.455 --> 00:55:34.915
of communism to the men,

00:55:34.915 --> 00:55:36.792
promised that they'd all soon be joined

00:55:36.792 --> 00:55:40.504
in wonderful communist bliss and let them go.

00:55:40.504 --> 00:55:44.049
Naturally, the men immediately reported them to the police.

00:55:44.049 --> 00:55:45.926
Within hours, the warning

00:55:45.926 --> 00:55:48.262
was relayed up the chain of command.

00:55:48.262 --> 00:55:51.098
South Korea didn't know what the commandos wanted,

00:55:51.098 --> 00:55:54.726
but they mobilized everything in the area to find them

00:55:54.726 --> 00:55:57.729
and put the whole country on high alert.

00:55:57.729 --> 00:56:01.358
The North Koreans managed to arrive in Seoul undetected,

00:56:01.358 --> 00:56:03.902
but they had to scuttle their original plan.

00:56:03.902 --> 00:56:05.195
They'd been trained well, though,

00:56:05.195 --> 00:56:06.905
and adapted to the high alert.

00:56:06.905 --> 00:56:10.784
With soldiers everywhere, the commandos simply blended in.

00:56:10.784 --> 00:56:13.829
They dawned stolen South Korean uniforms.

00:56:13.829 --> 00:56:15.747
And on the 20th of January,

00:56:15.747 --> 00:56:19.167
the full group of 31 armed men walked down the street

00:56:19.167 --> 00:56:22.212
in open daylight towards the President's residence

00:56:22.212 --> 00:56:23.589
at the Blue House.

00:56:23.589 --> 00:56:27.092
The commandos got within 800 meters of the President's house

00:56:27.092 --> 00:56:29.803
before some curious policemen stopped them.

00:56:29.803 --> 00:56:31.597
It didn't take long for the police

00:56:31.597 --> 00:56:33.849
to see right through their disguises.

00:56:33.849 --> 00:56:36.977
Their cover blown, the commandos opened fire.

00:56:36.977 --> 00:56:39.855
One policeman died and two North Koreans fell

00:56:39.855 --> 00:56:41.648
before the commandos scattered.

00:56:41.648 --> 00:56:45.277
A massive manhunt was launched in the following days.

00:56:45.277 --> 00:56:48.155
South Korean and American forces swept the city

00:56:48.155 --> 00:56:51.742
and countryside hunting down the scattered commandos.

00:56:51.742 --> 00:56:53.660
Of the 31 Commandos,

00:56:53.660 --> 00:56:56.538
just one escaped back across the border.

00:56:56.538 --> 00:57:00.042
One more was captured, but all of the rest were killed.

00:57:00.042 --> 00:57:03.587
The Blue House raid was an embarrassment for both sides.

00:57:03.587 --> 00:57:04.921
The North Korean soldiers

00:57:04.921 --> 00:57:06.798
had foolishly blown their own cover

00:57:06.798 --> 00:57:08.050
and failed their mission.

00:57:08.050 --> 00:57:11.595
However, had the four civilians not warned the authorities,

00:57:11.595 --> 00:57:15.015
it is possible the commandos would have succeeded.

00:57:15.015 --> 00:57:17.434
Even then, with Seoul on high alert,

00:57:17.434 --> 00:57:20.979
the commandos had gotten within 800 meters of their target

00:57:20.979 --> 00:57:22.314
before being caught.

00:57:22.314 --> 00:57:24.608
The Blue House raid could have been the spark

00:57:24.608 --> 00:57:29.446
of a major war, but by sheer luck, it happened to occur just

00:57:29.446 --> 00:57:32.240
as the Tet Offensive exploded in Vietnam,

00:57:32.240 --> 00:57:35.118
dragging away us attention and guaranteeing

00:57:35.118 --> 00:57:38.538
that America would not commit to another war in Asia.

00:57:38.538 --> 00:57:41.416
For his part, Kim Il-Sung denied involvement

00:57:41.416 --> 00:57:44.378
and blamed rogue elements in the government for the plan,

00:57:44.378 --> 00:57:46.338
but other actions by North Korea

00:57:46.338 --> 00:57:49.383
at the same time paint a different picture.

00:57:54.221 --> 00:57:55.847
The conflict peaks.

00:57:57.307 --> 00:57:59.976
A mere three days after the Blue House raid,

00:57:59.976 --> 00:58:03.230
North Korea captured a US recon ship off the coast

00:58:03.230 --> 00:58:04.314
of the peninsula.

00:58:04.314 --> 00:58:07.859
The USS Pueblo was performing intelligence gathering

00:58:07.859 --> 00:58:09.861
several miles off the coast

00:58:09.861 --> 00:58:12.698
when it was intercepted by the North Korean Navy

00:58:12.698 --> 00:58:14.116
and Air Force.

00:58:14.116 --> 00:58:17.619
Officially, the Pueblo was in international waters,

00:58:17.619 --> 00:58:21.832
but North Korea has always asserted a much larger sea border

00:58:21.832 --> 00:58:23.834
than other countries accept.

00:58:23.834 --> 00:58:26.837
The North Koreans pursued the ship when it tried to flee

00:58:26.837 --> 00:58:29.131
and fired several warning shots,

00:58:29.131 --> 00:58:31.883
killing one sailor before the Pueblo surrendered

00:58:31.883 --> 00:58:33.885
and its crew was taken prisoner.

00:58:33.885 --> 00:58:36.596
It took several days to confirm the ship's fate.

00:58:36.596 --> 00:58:39.349
And Washington scrambled for a response.

00:58:39.349 --> 00:58:42.811
They desperately wanted to avoid making things worse.

00:58:42.811 --> 00:58:45.230
Not only might the hostages be killed,

00:58:45.230 --> 00:58:47.649
but US resources were consumed dealing

00:58:47.649 --> 00:58:49.735
with Tet Offensive in Vietnam.

00:58:49.735 --> 00:58:51.903
All the while, the crew suffered the misery

00:58:51.903 --> 00:58:54.656
and torture of North Korean captivity.

00:58:54.656 --> 00:58:57.284
The North began stockpiling rations.

00:58:57.284 --> 00:59:00.871
And in early 1968, Pyongyang closed its schools

00:59:00.871 --> 00:59:03.457
and evacuated citizens to the countryside

00:59:03.457 --> 00:59:06.126
in anticipation of a nuclear attack.

00:59:06.126 --> 00:59:09.212
Over 100 infiltrators were sent to the South again

00:59:09.212 --> 00:59:12.007
in late October, but almost all of them were caught

00:59:12.007 --> 00:59:15.969
within weeks of an that left about 150 people

00:59:15.969 --> 00:59:17.471
on both sides dead.

00:59:17.471 --> 00:59:20.265
The murder of an entire family at Gebang Mountain

00:59:20.265 --> 00:59:23.518
by the infiltrators, including a 10-year-old boy,

00:59:23.518 --> 00:59:26.646
intensified the South Korean response and made hope

00:59:26.646 --> 00:59:30.942
of a South Korean pro-communist uprising even more absurd.

00:59:30.942 --> 00:59:32.944
The global community feared war.

00:59:32.944 --> 00:59:35.238
Diplomats from communist, capitalist,

00:59:35.238 --> 00:59:38.742
and non-aligned nations urged deescalation.

00:59:38.742 --> 00:59:40.827
Even Moscow was unhappy.

00:59:40.827 --> 00:59:44.080
During a party conference in April, 1968,

00:59:44.080 --> 00:59:46.666
Premier Brezhnev condemned North Korea

00:59:46.666 --> 00:59:50.086
for trying to drag the world into another conflict.

00:59:50.086 --> 00:59:53.256
We do not know what exactly led Kim Il-Sung

00:59:53.256 --> 00:59:56.760
to wind down the provocations in 1969.

00:59:56.760 --> 00:59:59.262
The anger of the USSR in China,

00:59:59.262 --> 01:00:03.433
fear of actual conflict or a changing domestic political

01:00:03.433 --> 01:00:06.645
and economic situation might all explain it.

01:00:06.645 --> 01:00:10.273
We only know that for whatever reason, Pyongyang eased off

01:00:10.273 --> 01:00:12.859
on the provocations over the following months,

01:00:12.859 --> 01:00:17.280
and by late 1969, the crew of the Pueblo were released

01:00:17.280 --> 01:00:20.742
and hostile encounters along the demilitarized zone

01:00:20.742 --> 01:00:24.371
had returned to their pre-1966 levels.

01:00:24.371 --> 01:00:27.833
It is possible that Kim's massive military buildup

01:00:27.833 --> 01:00:31.545
in the 1960s created the appetite for war.

01:00:31.545 --> 01:00:33.547
It is also likely that the purge

01:00:33.547 --> 01:00:36.716
of North Korean generals in the late 1960s

01:00:36.716 --> 01:00:40.846
was a direct result of the failures of this whole conflict.

01:00:40.846 --> 01:00:43.890
Overall, though, it was a pointless conflict

01:00:43.890 --> 01:00:46.893
that claimed an estimated 400 South Korean

01:00:46.893 --> 01:00:51.106
and American lives, along with 100s of North Koreans.

01:00:55.610 --> 01:00:58.405
Prosperity in the '60s and '70s.

01:00:59.823 --> 01:01:02.617
North Korea's military fortunes were poor,

01:01:02.617 --> 01:01:06.705
but its economic prosperity at this point was not so dire.

01:01:06.705 --> 01:01:09.583
Per capita GDP in the North was comparable

01:01:09.583 --> 01:01:13.628
or even higher than that of the South well into the 1960s

01:01:13.628 --> 01:01:14.754
and '70s.

01:01:14.754 --> 01:01:16.298
More than just rebuilding,

01:01:16.298 --> 01:01:18.675
North Korea had upgraded too.

01:01:18.675 --> 01:01:22.637
Almost all homes had electricity by the mid 1970s

01:01:22.637 --> 01:01:26.266
and almost 70% of the population had urbanized

01:01:26.266 --> 01:01:29.019
as agricultural improvements reduced the need

01:01:29.019 --> 01:01:31.271
for people to be rural farmers.

01:01:31.271 --> 01:01:33.189
Education also improved

01:01:33.189 --> 01:01:36.067
with virtually all children enrolled in school

01:01:36.067 --> 01:01:39.946
and over 200 universities established across the country,

01:01:39.946 --> 01:01:42.198
all with free tuition, of course.

01:01:42.198 --> 01:01:45.493
One of the biggest success stories in North Korea was

01:01:45.493 --> 01:01:47.996
and remains national health.

01:01:47.996 --> 01:01:50.332
The hospitals remain underfunded.

01:01:50.332 --> 01:01:52.751
However, mandatory health checkups

01:01:52.751 --> 01:01:56.504
and vaccination programs instituted under Kim Il-Sung

01:01:56.504 --> 01:02:00.717
have left North Korea with an unusually high life expectancy

01:02:00.717 --> 01:02:03.428
and a low infant mortality rate despite

01:02:03.428 --> 01:02:04.971
its relative poverty.

01:02:04.971 --> 01:02:08.600
To this day, North Korea enjoys an average life expectancy

01:02:08.600 --> 01:02:10.727
of about 73 years,

01:02:10.727 --> 01:02:13.563
lower than the US or other developed countries,

01:02:13.563 --> 01:02:16.608
but considerably higher than other nations

01:02:16.608 --> 01:02:19.069
of comparable economic status.

01:02:19.069 --> 01:02:22.948
Still, Kim's promises far exceeded reality.

01:02:22.948 --> 01:02:25.033
He'd once claimed he would see North Korea

01:02:25.033 --> 01:02:26.952
where everyone wore silk,

01:02:26.952 --> 01:02:29.245
lived in a house with a tiled roof,

01:02:29.245 --> 01:02:31.790
and ate three full meals a day.

01:02:31.790 --> 01:02:36.086
North Korea had made progress, but this dream of luxury,

01:02:36.086 --> 01:02:39.881
a dream that was already reality for millions in the West,

01:02:39.881 --> 01:02:41.591
was still a distant hope.

01:02:41.591 --> 01:02:44.177
What's more, North Korea's progress towards

01:02:44.177 --> 01:02:48.139
that distant hope was about to come to a grinding halt.

01:02:50.600 --> 01:02:51.893
A desperate nation.

01:02:53.019 --> 01:02:54.646
Economic issues.

01:02:55.480 --> 01:02:58.358
By the mid 1970s, North Korea's economy

01:02:58.358 --> 01:03:00.193
was showing signs of struggle.

01:03:00.193 --> 01:03:02.737
The Chollima Movement had exhausted its workforce

01:03:02.737 --> 01:03:04.823
and production was steadily declining.

01:03:04.823 --> 01:03:07.826
Imports of advanced Western machinery had stalled

01:03:07.826 --> 01:03:09.995
when it became obvious that Pyongyang

01:03:09.995 --> 01:03:12.080
would not be able to pay its debts.

01:03:12.080 --> 01:03:15.041
Global economic challenges throughout the decade,

01:03:15.041 --> 01:03:18.336
including the 1973 oil crisis,

01:03:18.336 --> 01:03:22.173
had knock-on effects that shook the already fragile nation.

01:03:22.173 --> 01:03:26.636
In 1976, North Korea was forced to stop all dead repayments

01:03:26.636 --> 01:03:28.555
to the West, a dire sign

01:03:28.555 --> 01:03:30.849
of the state of the nation's finances.

01:03:30.849 --> 01:03:34.769
Manipulation of statistics also continued to be a problem.

01:03:34.769 --> 01:03:38.023
Success varied wildly in different parts of the economy,

01:03:38.023 --> 01:03:40.400
and already by 1968,

01:03:40.400 --> 01:03:42.944
the government had stopped publishing specific data

01:03:42.944 --> 01:03:45.780
on economic output to avoid scrutiny.

01:03:45.780 --> 01:03:48.116
Some industries like ceramic soared,

01:03:48.116 --> 01:03:50.243
and the government smashed these numbers together

01:03:50.243 --> 01:03:53.496
with massive underperformance in other industries

01:03:53.496 --> 01:03:57.667
to create the illusion of success for propaganda purposes.

01:03:57.667 --> 01:04:00.128
By not recognizing their failures, though,

01:04:00.128 --> 01:04:02.172
the government only made it worse,

01:04:02.172 --> 01:04:06.092
continuing to pour resources into overperforming industries

01:04:06.092 --> 01:04:08.511
when they could have been better spent elsewhere.

01:04:08.511 --> 01:04:10.513
Things were not all bad.

01:04:10.513 --> 01:04:13.850
By many metrics, life in the 1970's North Korea

01:04:13.850 --> 01:04:15.351
was relatively good,

01:04:15.351 --> 01:04:17.604
at least in the first half of the decade.

01:04:17.604 --> 01:04:19.481
Residential construction projects

01:04:19.481 --> 01:04:21.399
had finally addressed the housing shortages

01:04:21.399 --> 01:04:23.485
that plagued the country since the war,

01:04:23.485 --> 01:04:25.904
and there had been undeniable development

01:04:25.904 --> 01:04:28.573
in both industry and agriculture.

01:04:28.573 --> 01:04:31.868
However, the North would soon fall rapidly behind

01:04:31.868 --> 01:04:34.454
its southern neighbors in terms of prosperity,

01:04:34.454 --> 01:04:37.457
quality of life, and industrial output.

01:04:37.457 --> 01:04:40.251
Pyongyang tried to save its flagging economy

01:04:40.251 --> 01:04:43.171
with the August Third Consumer Goods Movement,

01:04:43.171 --> 01:04:46.091
which was basically a campaign to get North Koreans

01:04:46.091 --> 01:04:48.051
to buy useless goods they didn't need

01:04:48.051 --> 01:04:51.304
and that didn't last just to create demand

01:04:51.304 --> 01:04:53.515
and boost GDP numbers.

01:04:53.515 --> 01:04:55.767
Attempts to restart the Chollima campaign

01:04:55.767 --> 01:04:57.227
for the movement failed.

01:04:57.227 --> 01:05:00.271
The exhausted workforce produced poor products,

01:05:00.271 --> 01:05:03.149
which meant even more had to be made to replace them,

01:05:03.149 --> 01:05:06.152
creating an endless cycle of decreasing quality

01:05:06.152 --> 01:05:07.570
and increasing demand

01:05:07.570 --> 01:05:10.156
that further warped economic statistics.

01:05:10.156 --> 01:05:12.659
North Korea's pride especially suffered

01:05:12.659 --> 01:05:14.327
as its old rivals in the South

01:05:14.327 --> 01:05:17.705
and in Japan began rapid economic rises

01:05:17.705 --> 01:05:20.667
that catapulted them ahead in the 1970s.

01:05:20.667 --> 01:05:22.377
As South Korea soared,

01:05:22.377 --> 01:05:25.588
North Korea became increasingly dependent on its Soviet

01:05:25.588 --> 01:05:27.507
and Chinese allies.

01:05:27.507 --> 01:05:28.800
By the end of the decade,

01:05:28.800 --> 01:05:32.846
North Korea was effectively a vasal state of the USSR,

01:05:32.846 --> 01:05:35.056
relying on them for economic subsidies

01:05:35.056 --> 01:05:36.641
and diplomatic muscle,

01:05:36.641 --> 01:05:40.311
and watching as its enemy soared ahead towards prosperity.

01:05:44.190 --> 01:05:46.067
Foreign policy changes.

01:05:47.318 --> 01:05:48.486
The shifting winds

01:05:48.486 --> 01:05:52.365
of global politics presented new challenges for North Korea.

01:05:52.365 --> 01:05:55.118
After the US' withdrawal from Vietnam,

01:05:55.118 --> 01:05:58.621
Kim entertained the idea of reunification with the South.

01:05:58.621 --> 01:06:01.749
If Vietnam could defeat the US, he argued,

01:06:01.749 --> 01:06:03.793
surely North Korea could.

01:06:03.793 --> 01:06:06.588
Kim presented this possibility to Mao Zedong,

01:06:06.588 --> 01:06:09.716
but this was not 1951 anymore.

01:06:09.716 --> 01:06:12.343
North Korea's military advantage over the South

01:06:12.343 --> 01:06:14.304
had shrunk dramatically,

01:06:14.304 --> 01:06:17.599
and the US' embarrassment in a gorilla war spoke little

01:06:17.599 --> 01:06:20.143
of its power to win a conventional one.

01:06:20.143 --> 01:06:23.229
Furthermore, Beijing had not forgotten that their soldiers

01:06:23.229 --> 01:06:25.356
had shouldered most of the fighting burden

01:06:25.356 --> 01:06:28.484
after saving Kim's last disastrous war attempt.

01:06:28.484 --> 01:06:31.696
Frankly, they did not trust Pyongyang to win.

01:06:31.696 --> 01:06:34.240
The other reason they refused to support the idea

01:06:34.240 --> 01:06:37.660
was China's newfound effort to build bridges with the West.

01:06:37.660 --> 01:06:40.788
By the mid 1970s, China was looking for ways

01:06:40.788 --> 01:06:45.043
to reduce hostilities to the US and build economic ties.

01:06:45.043 --> 01:06:47.921
The Nixon administration had been eager to do so,

01:06:47.921 --> 01:06:51.466
hoping to deepen the divides between Moscow and Beijing,

01:06:51.466 --> 01:06:53.968
and allowing North Korea to start another war

01:06:53.968 --> 01:06:56.137
would only ruin those efforts.

01:06:56.137 --> 01:06:59.057
Kim's plans were shelved when he began to realize

01:06:59.057 --> 01:07:02.518
that the old reliance on China and the USSR

01:07:02.518 --> 01:07:05.980
in an eternal union against the West was crumbling.

01:07:05.980 --> 01:07:09.776
To counter this, Kim Il-Sung found new allies outside

01:07:09.776 --> 01:07:11.236
of China and Russia.

01:07:11.236 --> 01:07:13.988
Fellow communists like Pol Pot in Cambodia

01:07:13.988 --> 01:07:16.241
were rather short-lived allies.

01:07:16.241 --> 01:07:18.159
One of the more successful areas

01:07:18.159 --> 01:07:21.204
of North Korean diplomacy was Africa.

01:07:21.204 --> 01:07:24.791
Kim found fast friends in the continent's mad dictators,

01:07:24.791 --> 01:07:27.919
like Idi Amin and Jean-Bedel Bokassa,

01:07:27.919 --> 01:07:31.756
men whose craving for power and control matched his own.

01:07:35.635 --> 01:07:38.930
Monique Nguema, the black girl from Pyongyang.

01:07:40.598 --> 01:07:43.476
Another appropriately psychotic friend Kim made

01:07:43.476 --> 01:07:45.728
was Francisco Macias Nguema,

01:07:45.728 --> 01:07:48.648
the ruthless dictator of Equatorial Guinea.

01:07:48.648 --> 01:07:52.568
Nguema turned his country into his own little hellish cult.

01:07:52.568 --> 01:07:55.571
His official nickname was "The Great Miracle,"

01:07:55.571 --> 01:07:58.908
and priest said to give praise to him in every service.

01:07:58.908 --> 01:08:01.995
Of course he shared the blood lust of North Korea too.

01:08:01.995 --> 01:08:03.079
In one instance,

01:08:03.079 --> 01:08:07.292
Nguema had 200 people massacred in a football stadium

01:08:07.292 --> 01:08:10.503
while blasting pop music over the speakers.

01:08:10.503 --> 01:08:12.547
Equatorial Guinea was easily one

01:08:12.547 --> 01:08:15.091
of the worst places in the world to live.

01:08:15.091 --> 01:08:18.970
They called it the Auschwitz of Africa for good reason.

01:08:18.970 --> 01:08:20.471
As a sign of their friendship,

01:08:20.471 --> 01:08:23.474
Nguema sent his daughter Monica to be raised and educated

01:08:23.474 --> 01:08:26.227
in Pyongyang in 1979.

01:08:26.227 --> 01:08:28.479
It was just in the nick of time too,

01:08:28.479 --> 01:08:31.649
since Nguema was ousted and killed months later,

01:08:31.649 --> 01:08:33.735
but Kim Il-Sung kept his promise

01:08:33.735 --> 01:08:36.070
to his depraved departed friend.

01:08:36.070 --> 01:08:38.197
Monica was given the best education

01:08:38.197 --> 01:08:39.907
that North Korea could provide.

01:08:39.907 --> 01:08:43.202
And Kim regularly called Monica to see how she was doing

01:08:43.202 --> 01:08:45.788
and made sure she had everything she wanted.

01:08:45.788 --> 01:08:49.500
Monica is still alive and proudly considers Kim Il-Sung

01:08:49.500 --> 01:08:51.252
to be her second father.

01:08:51.252 --> 01:08:54.255
She has written several books about her life and family,

01:08:54.255 --> 01:08:58.009
where she adamantly defends both Nguema and Kim Il-Sung

01:08:58.009 --> 01:09:02.180
as good men who were unfairly smeared by Western propaganda.

01:09:05.933 --> 01:09:07.894
Operation Paul Bunyan.

01:09:09.187 --> 01:09:11.773
But while North Korea built closer reliances

01:09:11.773 --> 01:09:14.859
with some nations, relations with the United States

01:09:14.859 --> 01:09:17.820
and South Korea continued to be difficult.

01:09:17.820 --> 01:09:20.865
The DMZ remained a Tinder box that could be ignited

01:09:20.865 --> 01:09:24.160
by the simplest thing, including a tree.

01:09:24.160 --> 01:09:27.955
On August 18th, 1976, a small group of US

01:09:27.955 --> 01:09:29.624
and South Korean soldiers,

01:09:29.624 --> 01:09:33.044
led by Captain Arthur Bonifas and Lieutenant Mark Barrett,

01:09:33.044 --> 01:09:35.380
entered the DMZ to cut down a tree

01:09:35.380 --> 01:09:36.672
which was blocking the view

01:09:36.672 --> 01:09:39.092
for a UN command post on the border.

01:09:39.092 --> 01:09:41.386
A group of North Korean soldiers came over

01:09:41.386 --> 01:09:42.720
and watched them closely.

01:09:42.720 --> 01:09:45.890
After a while, the North Koreans became belligerent.

01:09:45.890 --> 01:09:49.352
They demanded Captain Bonifas and his men stop and leave,

01:09:49.352 --> 01:09:52.271
but Bonifas turned his back to them and kept working.

01:09:52.271 --> 01:09:54.482
He didn't even see the North Korean soldiers

01:09:54.482 --> 01:09:57.610
when they suddenly and brutally attacked him.

01:09:57.610 --> 01:10:00.947
About 30 North Korean soldiers armed with crow bars,

01:10:00.947 --> 01:10:04.033
metal pipes and other implements pounced on the US

01:10:04.033 --> 01:10:05.910
and South Korean soldiers.

01:10:05.910 --> 01:10:09.372
Captain Bonifas was beaten to death on the spot.

01:10:09.372 --> 01:10:11.707
Lieutenant Barrett escaped to a nearby ditch

01:10:11.707 --> 01:10:14.293
where the North Korean soldiers found him and attacked him

01:10:14.293 --> 01:10:16.838
with the same axes the soldiers had been using

01:10:16.838 --> 01:10:18.464
to cut down the tree.

01:10:18.464 --> 01:10:21.676
Bonifas and Barrett both died from their injuries.

01:10:21.676 --> 01:10:24.262
Both men were armed but never drew their weapons.

01:10:24.262 --> 01:10:26.055
Probably scared that gunfire

01:10:26.055 --> 01:10:27.765
would only make things worse.

01:10:27.765 --> 01:10:31.310
Immediately North Korean state media spun the attack

01:10:31.310 --> 01:10:33.354
as an act of American aggression,

01:10:33.354 --> 01:10:36.399
and North Korea's international allies echoed

01:10:36.399 --> 01:10:37.692
this propaganda.

01:10:37.692 --> 01:10:41.112
Video, photographic, and eyewitness evidence refuted it,

01:10:41.112 --> 01:10:42.613
but the regime made sure

01:10:42.613 --> 01:10:45.908
that the North Korean people only saw their version

01:10:45.908 --> 01:10:46.868
of events,

01:10:46.868 --> 01:10:49.787
but if Pyongyang had hoped the US would back down,

01:10:49.787 --> 01:10:51.622
they were badly mistaken.

01:10:51.622 --> 01:10:53.708
The US refused to take the murder

01:10:53.708 --> 01:10:55.501
of two of their soldiers lightly,

01:10:55.501 --> 01:10:58.754
but they also didn't want to start a war over a tree.

01:10:58.754 --> 01:11:01.090
Cue Operation Paul Bunyan,

01:11:01.090 --> 01:11:03.885
named for the famous lumberjack folk hero.

01:11:03.885 --> 01:11:06.220
The US had a single goal.

01:11:06.220 --> 01:11:08.431
They were going to cut that tree down

01:11:08.431 --> 01:11:12.185
and they were going to dare Pyongyang to try and stop them.

01:11:12.185 --> 01:11:15.396
The US called in an army's worth of resources.

01:11:15.396 --> 01:11:18.566
100s of armed soldiers, martial arts specialists,

01:11:18.566 --> 01:11:22.069
armored vehicles, attack helicopters, a fleet of bombers,

01:11:22.069 --> 01:11:23.112
fighter jets,

01:11:23.112 --> 01:11:26.782
and not to mention the aircraft carrier USS Midway,

01:11:26.782 --> 01:11:29.076
which was moved to a station offshore.

01:11:29.076 --> 01:11:33.331
Practically every US and allied military base in East Asia

01:11:33.331 --> 01:11:35.500
was put on full alert, ready to assist

01:11:35.500 --> 01:11:38.961
if the North Koreans tried to stop them cutting that tree.

01:11:38.961 --> 01:11:40.296
With enough firepower

01:11:40.296 --> 01:11:43.132
to conquer a small country behind them,

01:11:43.132 --> 01:11:45.218
the US sent a team into the DMZ

01:11:45.218 --> 01:11:48.095
to chop down the tree once and for all.

01:11:48.095 --> 01:11:50.556
A few 100 North Korean soldiers on the border

01:11:50.556 --> 01:11:53.976
could only watch in awe as the US troops brought it down,

01:11:53.976 --> 01:11:57.396
while helicopters and bombers circled on the horizon.

01:11:57.396 --> 01:12:00.608
45 minutes later, Operation Paul Bunyan

01:12:00.608 --> 01:12:02.276
was declared a success.

01:12:02.276 --> 01:12:04.737
The stump was left standing for a few years

01:12:04.737 --> 01:12:06.781
and now a memorial stands on the spot

01:12:06.781 --> 01:12:08.741
to honor Bonifas and Barrett.

01:12:08.741 --> 01:12:10.743
North Korea, apparently shocked

01:12:10.743 --> 01:12:13.287
by the lengths the US would go for a tree,

01:12:13.287 --> 01:12:15.706
didn't go so far as to apologize,

01:12:15.706 --> 01:12:18.584
but Kim Il-Sung expressed his regret

01:12:18.584 --> 01:12:20.836
that the incident had gotten out of hand

01:12:20.836 --> 01:12:24.382
and said both sides needed to commit to keeping the peace.

01:12:24.382 --> 01:12:25.550
It wasn't much,

01:12:25.550 --> 01:12:28.177
but it was the closest the Kim regime had come

01:12:28.177 --> 01:12:29.887
to accepting responsibility

01:12:29.887 --> 01:12:33.599
for something bad in its entire history thus far.

01:12:36.936 --> 01:12:38.312
Flagpole War.

01:12:39.522 --> 01:12:43.484
The Paul Bunyan incident didn't solve issues along the DMZ,

01:12:43.484 --> 01:12:44.902
not by a long shot,

01:12:44.902 --> 01:12:48.489
but subsequent disagreements were generally more civil.

01:12:48.489 --> 01:12:51.450
In fact, they could be downright silly at times.

01:12:51.450 --> 01:12:55.454
The Flagpole War of the 1980s was a good example,

01:12:55.454 --> 01:12:57.707
and it's exactly what it sounded like.

01:12:57.707 --> 01:13:01.836
South Korea erected a 98 meter flagpole near the border

01:13:01.836 --> 01:13:04.297
so that their flag could be seen by the North.

01:13:04.297 --> 01:13:06.257
Taking some lessons from the showmanship

01:13:06.257 --> 01:13:09.093
of their American rivals, the North answered back

01:13:09.093 --> 01:13:13.264
with a 160 meter flagpole that dwarfed their neighbors.

01:13:13.264 --> 01:13:16.559
The flag alone weighed almost 600 pounds.

01:13:16.559 --> 01:13:20.062
And to this day, this little sign of North Korean vanity

01:13:20.062 --> 01:13:23.107
is the tallest flagpole in the world.

01:13:26.402 --> 01:13:28.696
The emergence of Kim Jong-Il.

01:13:29.864 --> 01:13:33.200
By 1980, Kim Il-Sung was pushing 70.

01:13:33.200 --> 01:13:35.911
North Korea's economic progress had stagnated

01:13:35.911 --> 01:13:37.538
and foreign relations had been stuck

01:13:37.538 --> 01:13:41.083
in a perpetual stalemate for almost three decades.

01:13:41.083 --> 01:13:42.793
There might have been a sense of anxiety

01:13:42.793 --> 01:13:45.463
about what could happen when the great leader died

01:13:45.463 --> 01:13:48.674
and the nation faced its mounting problems alone.

01:13:48.674 --> 01:13:51.427
Kim Il-Sung had a solution to those anxieties

01:13:51.427 --> 01:13:54.013
and its name was Kim Jong-Il.

01:13:54.013 --> 01:13:56.474
Kim Jong-Il was hidden from the spotlight

01:13:56.474 --> 01:13:58.726
for the first 30 years of his life.

01:13:58.726 --> 01:14:01.896
Born in a Soviet military camp in 1941

01:14:01.896 --> 01:14:03.856
to Kim Il-Sung and his first wife,

01:14:03.856 --> 01:14:07.151
Kim's childhood is obscured behind a ridiculous level

01:14:07.151 --> 01:14:09.612
of absurd and fancy full stories.

01:14:09.612 --> 01:14:12.198
Kim Jong-Il first emerged into the corridors

01:14:12.198 --> 01:14:14.700
of power in the 1970s,

01:14:14.700 --> 01:14:17.078
playing a key role in party politics,

01:14:17.078 --> 01:14:19.246
even as he was hidden from public view.

01:14:19.246 --> 01:14:22.291
He joined the Central committee in 1972

01:14:22.291 --> 01:14:26.712
and by 1974, he was the designated heir to his father.

01:14:26.712 --> 01:14:29.924
Il was groomed for succession through experience.

01:14:29.924 --> 01:14:32.885
He was given important roles in managing espionage

01:14:32.885 --> 01:14:34.720
and propaganda for the regime

01:14:34.720 --> 01:14:37.890
and would gradually accrue more power behind the scenes

01:14:37.890 --> 01:14:39.767
until the 1990s.

01:14:39.767 --> 01:14:42.728
From the 1980s, he was put into public view

01:14:42.728 --> 01:14:46.273
and given a thorough heroic treatment by propaganda.

01:14:46.273 --> 01:14:49.318
Soon his portrait could be found alongside his father's

01:14:49.318 --> 01:14:51.987
in every home in the DPRK.

01:14:51.987 --> 01:14:55.574
Kim Jong-Il was described as the party center.

01:14:55.574 --> 01:14:57.952
And state propaganda assured the people

01:14:57.952 --> 01:15:00.913
that as Kim Sung's old age approached,

01:15:00.913 --> 01:15:03.958
the party center would maintain the revolution

01:15:03.958 --> 01:15:06.502
and continue the work that his father began.

01:15:08.796 --> 01:15:12.258
Kidnapping of Shin Sang-ok and Choi Eun-hee.

01:15:13.676 --> 01:15:16.387
One of Kim Jong-Il's first responsibilities

01:15:16.387 --> 01:15:18.013
was to coordinate propaganda

01:15:18.013 --> 01:15:20.558
to improve the DPRK case's image.

01:15:20.558 --> 01:15:24.103
Despite his ideological opposition to Western ideas,

01:15:24.103 --> 01:15:27.231
Kim Jong-Il was famously a huge film buff

01:15:27.231 --> 01:15:30.067
and owned a massive collection of foreign films

01:15:30.067 --> 01:15:32.737
that would've earned a regular North Korean a trip

01:15:32.737 --> 01:15:34.113
to the labor camps.

01:15:34.113 --> 01:15:37.491
Working with the propaganda and agitation department,

01:15:37.491 --> 01:15:38.701
Kim Jong-Il dreamed

01:15:38.701 --> 01:15:42.496
of making North Korea a sort of communist Hollywood.

01:15:42.496 --> 01:15:45.791
Instead of themes of freedom or tales of cowboys

01:15:45.791 --> 01:15:48.419
and US soldiers, like the Americans made,

01:15:48.419 --> 01:15:51.130
he dreamed of a film industry that sang the praises

01:15:51.130 --> 01:15:53.799
of communism and retold the glories

01:15:53.799 --> 01:15:57.011
of Kim Il-Sung and his glorious revolution.

01:15:57.011 --> 01:15:59.972
The trouble was that North Korea didn't have the people

01:15:59.972 --> 01:16:02.683
to make films that could compete with Hollywood.

01:16:02.683 --> 01:16:05.978
Kim Jong-Il made a few of his own during the 1970s,

01:16:05.978 --> 01:16:08.856
but any applause they got from the North Korean audience

01:16:08.856 --> 01:16:09.940
was forced.

01:16:09.940 --> 01:16:12.359
Kim knew he needed people with talent

01:16:12.359 --> 01:16:16.197
to make his dream come true, and he knew where to find them.

01:16:16.197 --> 01:16:18.282
In January, 1978,

01:16:18.282 --> 01:16:19.492
North Korean agents

01:16:19.492 --> 01:16:22.328
approached South Korean actress Choi Eun-Hee

01:16:22.328 --> 01:16:24.079
while she was in Hong Kong.

01:16:24.079 --> 01:16:27.333
They shoved her onto a boat and took her back to North Korea

01:16:27.333 --> 01:16:29.376
where she was given a tour of the country

01:16:29.376 --> 01:16:31.045
and met Kim Il-Sung.

01:16:31.045 --> 01:16:33.756
Despite her kidnapping, Choi was treated well

01:16:33.756 --> 01:16:36.967
and spent time with Kim visiting theaters, operas,

01:16:36.967 --> 01:16:38.928
and parties across the country.

01:16:38.928 --> 01:16:41.597
Six months later, North Korean agents swept up

01:16:41.597 --> 01:16:44.517
another South Korean film expert in Hong Kong,

01:16:44.517 --> 01:16:46.644
the director Shin Sang-Ok.

01:16:46.644 --> 01:16:48.896
Shin happened to be Choi's ex-husband,

01:16:48.896 --> 01:16:51.106
and Kim intentionally kidnapped both

01:16:51.106 --> 01:16:53.025
to reunite them in North Korea

01:16:53.025 --> 01:16:55.694
and compel them to stay to make films for him.

01:16:55.694 --> 01:16:58.489
After several failed escape attempts from Shin,

01:16:58.489 --> 01:16:59.532
they gave in.

01:16:59.532 --> 01:17:01.075
Choi and Shin remarried

01:17:01.075 --> 01:17:03.619
and spent the next eight years pumping out movies

01:17:03.619 --> 01:17:04.662
for the regime.

01:17:04.662 --> 01:17:07.748
Some of the films were exactly what you'd expect.

01:17:07.748 --> 01:17:10.960
Film productions of Kim Jong-Il's own screenplays

01:17:10.960 --> 01:17:14.046
or tales of Kim Il-Sung's glorious resistance

01:17:14.046 --> 01:17:15.631
against the Japanese.

01:17:15.631 --> 01:17:18.217
Choi even won an award for her performance

01:17:18.217 --> 01:17:19.927
in one propaganda film

01:17:19.927 --> 01:17:22.179
about a peasant woman joining the communists

01:17:22.179 --> 01:17:24.431
in Japanese-occupied China,

01:17:24.431 --> 01:17:26.851
but the best film had to be Pulgasari,

01:17:26.851 --> 01:17:30.312
a North Korean Godzilla ripoff about a magic dragon

01:17:30.312 --> 01:17:32.565
that overthrows a corrupt emperor.

01:17:32.565 --> 01:17:34.275
You can watch the film online.

01:17:34.275 --> 01:17:37.778
Kenpachiro Satsuma, one of the actors who played Godzilla,

01:17:37.778 --> 01:17:39.238
admitted that Pulgarsari

01:17:39.238 --> 01:17:42.825
was actually better than some of the Godzilla films.

01:17:42.825 --> 01:17:45.369
Unfortunately there would be no sequel.

01:17:45.369 --> 01:17:47.204
Choi and Shin were well treated,

01:17:47.204 --> 01:17:48.998
but they were still prisoners.

01:17:48.998 --> 01:17:51.250
During a visit to Vienna to secure funding

01:17:51.250 --> 01:17:52.626
for their next big hit,

01:17:52.626 --> 01:17:55.546
they managed to sneak away from their North Korean guards

01:17:55.546 --> 01:17:57.840
and escaped to the US embassy.

01:17:57.840 --> 01:17:59.300
North Korea's film industry

01:17:59.300 --> 01:18:02.553
would never see wonders like Pulgarsari again,

01:18:02.553 --> 01:18:05.890
but at least Choi and Shin could finally be free.

01:18:09.727 --> 01:18:11.353
Seed-bearing program.

01:18:12.521 --> 01:18:15.274
ChoI and Shin were not the only people kidnapped

01:18:15.274 --> 01:18:17.776
and taken in North Korea in this period

01:18:17.776 --> 01:18:20.321
and many would not have the chance to escape.

01:18:20.321 --> 01:18:23.741
Throughout the 1970s, Pyongyang kidnapped 100s

01:18:23.741 --> 01:18:27.161
of foreigners and smuggled them back to the DPRK.

01:18:27.161 --> 01:18:29.580
Most of the targets were taken from Japan,

01:18:29.580 --> 01:18:32.041
although kidnappings from other countries like France

01:18:32.041 --> 01:18:34.001
and Malaysia were also known.

01:18:34.001 --> 01:18:36.295
There was no real pattern to them.

01:18:36.295 --> 01:18:39.006
They would occur at any place at any time.

01:18:39.006 --> 01:18:42.635
Sometimes taking young couples, other times a lone man

01:18:42.635 --> 01:18:45.054
or even a 13-year-old girl.

01:18:45.054 --> 01:18:47.264
The victims would be taken to North Korea

01:18:47.264 --> 01:18:48.682
and forced to live in the country

01:18:48.682 --> 01:18:50.476
for the rest of their lives.

01:18:50.476 --> 01:18:52.186
If they were abducted as a couple,

01:18:52.186 --> 01:18:53.687
they would be split up for a time

01:18:53.687 --> 01:18:56.982
and then reunited after a thorough indoctrination.

01:18:56.982 --> 01:18:59.443
If they were alone, they would eventually be paired up

01:18:59.443 --> 01:19:01.987
with another captive of the opposite sex.

01:19:01.987 --> 01:19:03.322
They would be given a home

01:19:03.322 --> 01:19:05.699
and expected to conceive children.

01:19:05.699 --> 01:19:09.036
That was the reason why they were taken in the first place.

01:19:09.036 --> 01:19:11.121
North Korea wanted those children

01:19:11.121 --> 01:19:13.415
to turn them into loyal spies.

01:19:13.415 --> 01:19:15.000
Marriage between North Koreans

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:16.835
and foreigners were forbidden,

01:19:16.835 --> 01:19:18.837
and so racial homogeneity

01:19:18.837 --> 01:19:21.382
was almost universal in North Korea.

01:19:21.382 --> 01:19:24.385
Therefore, a spy who did not look like a North Korean

01:19:24.385 --> 01:19:27.554
was an extremely valuable asset to the regime.

01:19:27.554 --> 01:19:30.766
A similar tactic was the seed-bearing strategy

01:19:30.766 --> 01:19:32.351
where young North Korean women

01:19:32.351 --> 01:19:35.229
would be sent out to seduce powerful foreign men

01:19:35.229 --> 01:19:37.481
like politicians and businessmen.

01:19:37.481 --> 01:19:39.942
They'd get pregnant and then the North Korean government

01:19:39.942 --> 01:19:42.152
would use the children to blackmail the men

01:19:42.152 --> 01:19:43.654
to give them concessions

01:19:43.654 --> 01:19:46.407
or other support from their position of power.

01:19:46.407 --> 01:19:48.534
The ends of both schemes were similar,

01:19:48.534 --> 01:19:51.996
to breed a crop of ethnically camouflaged spies

01:19:51.996 --> 01:19:52.830
who could blend

01:19:52.830 --> 01:19:56.417
into society anywhere North Korea needed them to.

01:19:56.417 --> 01:20:00.087
To this day, we do not know how successful these spies were.

01:20:00.087 --> 01:20:03.465
We do not know of any of these children actually being used

01:20:03.465 --> 01:20:05.134
for their intended purpose.

01:20:05.134 --> 01:20:07.094
It's possible the plan was scrapped

01:20:07.094 --> 01:20:09.430
or that they've been so successful

01:20:09.430 --> 01:20:11.515
that no one ever caught them.

01:20:11.515 --> 01:20:15.269
North Korea only came clean about the abductions in 2002

01:20:15.269 --> 01:20:18.480
as part of a new diplomatic chapter with Japan.

01:20:18.480 --> 01:20:22.401
Still, the numbers they confess to taking, no more than 13,

01:20:22.401 --> 01:20:23.986
are much lower than the numbers

01:20:23.986 --> 01:20:26.905
that survivors and others suggest.

01:20:26.905 --> 01:20:28.657
Just five of the abductees

01:20:28.657 --> 01:20:30.868
were returned to Japan later that year,

01:20:30.868 --> 01:20:32.703
and the fates of dozens of other missing people

01:20:32.703 --> 01:20:34.872
and their children are unknown.

01:20:38.500 --> 01:20:39.877
Rangoon bombing.

01:20:41.045 --> 01:20:43.422
North Korea's criminal behavior seemed

01:20:43.422 --> 01:20:45.591
to get worse in the 1980s,

01:20:45.591 --> 01:20:49.178
perhaps reflecting the newfound influence of Kim Jong-Il.

01:20:49.178 --> 01:20:50.888
Two horrendous terrorist attacks

01:20:50.888 --> 01:20:54.141
on foreign soil shocked the world in that decade

01:20:54.141 --> 01:20:57.311
and increasingly isolated the DPRK.

01:20:57.311 --> 01:20:59.354
The first was an attempted assassination

01:20:59.354 --> 01:21:02.608
of the South Korean President Chun Doo-Hwan during a visit

01:21:02.608 --> 01:21:05.778
to Rangoon, modern day Yangon, in Burma.

01:21:05.778 --> 01:21:08.322
On the 9th of October, 1983,

01:21:08.322 --> 01:21:11.033
Chun, along with a host of other South Korean officials

01:21:11.033 --> 01:21:14.411
and advisors, was due to attend a wreath laying ceremony

01:21:14.411 --> 01:21:16.663
at the Martyr's Mausoleum dedicated

01:21:16.663 --> 01:21:19.333
to several Burmese national heroes.

01:21:19.333 --> 01:21:23.337
At 10:25 AM, just before the ceremony was due to start,

01:21:23.337 --> 01:21:25.005
a bomb hidden in the building

01:21:25.005 --> 01:21:27.633
by North Korean agents exploded.

01:21:27.633 --> 01:21:31.303
The blast destroyed the memorial, killing 21 people

01:21:31.303 --> 01:21:33.055
an wounding 46.

01:21:33.055 --> 01:21:33.889
Among the dead

01:21:33.889 --> 01:21:36.600
were several high-ranking South Korean officials,

01:21:36.600 --> 01:21:38.227
including the Foreign Minister

01:21:38.227 --> 01:21:40.187
and the Deputy Prime Minister,

01:21:40.187 --> 01:21:42.981
along with journalists and Burmese civilians.

01:21:42.981 --> 01:21:44.566
Luckily for President Chun,

01:21:44.566 --> 01:21:46.485
his car had been caught up in traffic

01:21:46.485 --> 01:21:48.320
and he escaped unharmed.

01:21:48.320 --> 01:21:50.531
North Korea was an obvious suspect,

01:21:50.531 --> 01:21:52.658
And police quickly identified three

01:21:52.658 --> 01:21:54.743
North Korean military officers

01:21:54.743 --> 01:21:58.122
who had secretly entered Yangon and received a package

01:21:58.122 --> 01:22:00.290
from a North Korean diplomatic mission,

01:22:00.290 --> 01:22:03.544
which was later found to have been explosives.

01:22:03.544 --> 01:22:07.089
Police closed in but the suspects did not go easily.

01:22:07.089 --> 01:22:09.758
One suspect was killed in a firefight with police

01:22:09.758 --> 01:22:12.761
after taking down three police officers.

01:22:12.761 --> 01:22:15.055
The remaining two were captured after attempting

01:22:15.055 --> 01:22:17.182
to kill themselves with a grenade.

01:22:17.182 --> 01:22:20.352
One of these men, Kang Min-Chul, avoided the death penalty

01:22:20.352 --> 01:22:22.604
by confessing the details of the crime

01:22:22.604 --> 01:22:24.606
and implicating the regime.

01:22:24.606 --> 01:22:27.484
The Rangoon goon bombing shattered North Korean relations

01:22:27.484 --> 01:22:30.779
with multiple countries, especially Myanmar,

01:22:30.779 --> 01:22:33.407
who were appalled that they would attempt not only

01:22:33.407 --> 01:22:35.617
to murder the leader of South Korea,

01:22:35.617 --> 01:22:39.746
but to do so at a sacred site within a neutral country.

01:22:42.583 --> 01:22:45.836
1987 Korean Air Flight 858.

01:22:47.171 --> 01:22:50.507
The second and far worse crime occurred four years later

01:22:50.507 --> 01:22:53.468
aboard South Korean Air Flight 858.

01:22:53.468 --> 01:22:56.263
On the 29th of November, 1987,

01:22:56.263 --> 01:22:58.056
two North Korean agents working

01:22:58.056 --> 01:23:01.476
on Kim Jong-Il's orders boarded flight 858

01:23:01.476 --> 01:23:03.687
using false Japanese passports

01:23:03.687 --> 01:23:05.981
and speaking Japanese taught to them by some

01:23:05.981 --> 01:23:08.483
of the captured Japanese citizens.

01:23:08.483 --> 01:23:10.944
The plane was flying from Baghdad to Seoul,

01:23:10.944 --> 01:23:13.197
with several stopovers in between.

01:23:13.197 --> 01:23:16.992
The agents secretly planted an explosive device disguised

01:23:16.992 --> 01:23:18.368
in an electronic radio

01:23:18.368 --> 01:23:20.621
in the luggage storage above their seats.

01:23:20.621 --> 01:23:23.582
Then left the plane when it stopped over in Abu Dhabi.

01:23:23.582 --> 01:23:26.126
The plane continued on its journey unaware

01:23:26.126 --> 01:23:28.170
of the deadly package it carried.

01:23:28.170 --> 01:23:29.504
A few hours later,

01:23:29.504 --> 01:23:33.050
the bomb detonated over the Andaman Sea in Southeast Asia,

01:23:33.050 --> 01:23:36.637
killing all 115 people on board.

01:23:36.637 --> 01:23:38.931
The agents tried to flee through the Middle East,

01:23:38.931 --> 01:23:40.557
but were caught in Bahrain.

01:23:40.557 --> 01:23:44.102
They both tried to commit suicide, but only one succeeded.

01:23:44.102 --> 01:23:47.022
The survivor, a woman named Kim Hyon-Hui,

01:23:47.022 --> 01:23:50.025
was detained and quickly linked to the attack.

01:23:50.025 --> 01:23:53.487
Investigation and interrogation soon revealed the truth.

01:23:53.487 --> 01:23:56.198
Kim Hyon-Hui had been taken from a young age

01:23:56.198 --> 01:23:58.575
and forced through North Korea's spy program,

01:23:58.575 --> 01:24:01.161
trained to be completely loyal to the regime.

01:24:01.161 --> 01:24:03.247
Kim Jong-il personally ordered her

01:24:03.247 --> 01:24:06.541
and her partner to bomb the plane to scare South Korea

01:24:06.541 --> 01:24:10.212
and frighten people away from the upcoming 1988 Olympics

01:24:10.212 --> 01:24:11.088
in Seoul.

01:24:11.088 --> 01:24:14.174
For her part, Kim Hyon-Hui was sentenced to death,

01:24:14.174 --> 01:24:16.927
but she was pardoned by the South Korean government,

01:24:16.927 --> 01:24:19.012
who argued that the indoctrinated girl

01:24:19.012 --> 01:24:22.224
was as much a victim of the regime as anyone else.

01:24:22.224 --> 01:24:24.559
It was a controversial decision.

01:24:24.559 --> 01:24:27.729
And Hyon-Hui lives with constant security out of fear

01:24:27.729 --> 01:24:29.731
of revenge from the victim's families

01:24:29.731 --> 01:24:32.609
or the North Korean government to this day.

01:24:32.609 --> 01:24:34.486
She has since announced the regime

01:24:34.486 --> 01:24:37.072
and appears to be genuinely remorseful,

01:24:37.072 --> 01:24:38.949
but the decision to let her off the hook

01:24:38.949 --> 01:24:40.951
has angered many people.

01:24:40.951 --> 01:24:44.621
The murder of 115 people aboard Flight 858

01:24:44.621 --> 01:24:46.665
was one of the most egregious acts

01:24:46.665 --> 01:24:50.252
of violence committed by North Korea since the Korean War.

01:24:50.252 --> 01:24:52.963
The international community was outraged

01:24:52.963 --> 01:24:55.757
and the US officially declared North Korea

01:24:55.757 --> 01:24:57.384
a terrorist state.

01:24:57.384 --> 01:24:59.970
Of course North Korea officially denies

01:24:59.970 --> 01:25:02.014
that it had anything to do with it,

01:25:02.014 --> 01:25:05.225
but the evidence against them is unquestionable.

01:25:08.979 --> 01:25:10.397
Megaprojects.

01:25:11.481 --> 01:25:15.277
Clearly the 1980s were a decade of external problems.

01:25:15.277 --> 01:25:17.654
Pyongyang tried to distract from these issues

01:25:17.654 --> 01:25:21.366
by funding massive internal projects to placate the people.

01:25:21.366 --> 01:25:24.286
Some of these projects were genuinely useful,

01:25:24.286 --> 01:25:26.830
others were mere exercises in vanity

01:25:26.830 --> 01:25:30.167
and some turned out to be miserable failures.

01:25:30.167 --> 01:25:32.711
The Nampo Dam on the west coast of the country

01:25:32.711 --> 01:25:35.672
was the great internal achievement of the decade.

01:25:35.672 --> 01:25:38.592
Built between 1981 and 1986,

01:25:38.592 --> 01:25:42.387
this massive $4 billion tidal barrage separates

01:25:42.387 --> 01:25:44.890
the Taedong River from the Yellow Sea.

01:25:44.890 --> 01:25:47.476
It prevents seawater contamination of the river,

01:25:47.476 --> 01:25:50.187
allowing it to be used to supply water for human,

01:25:50.187 --> 01:25:53.190
industrial, and agricultural needs.

01:25:53.190 --> 01:25:56.026
It is undeniably a feat of engineering

01:25:56.026 --> 01:25:59.446
and is still a proud icon of regime propaganda

01:25:59.446 --> 01:26:02.115
and a popular tourist destination to boot,

01:26:02.115 --> 01:26:04.618
but while the Nampo Dam had a purpose,

01:26:04.618 --> 01:26:06.953
the Juche Tower did not.

01:26:06.953 --> 01:26:10.457
The Juche Tower is a 560 foot tall monument

01:26:10.457 --> 01:26:13.126
to the regime's ideology in Pyongyang.

01:26:13.126 --> 01:26:14.544
It makes for a pretty sight

01:26:14.544 --> 01:26:18.548
and it was an impressive 70th birthday gift to Kim Il-Sung,

01:26:18.548 --> 01:26:21.051
but it was little more than a monument to the cult

01:26:21.051 --> 01:26:22.636
of the Kim dynasty.

01:26:22.636 --> 01:26:25.222
Then, again, at least it was completed,

01:26:25.222 --> 01:26:28.850
unlike Pyongyang's other flagship 1980s project,

01:26:28.850 --> 01:26:30.644
the Ryugyong Hotel.

01:26:30.644 --> 01:26:34.356
This 1,000 foot tall pyramid skyscraper towers

01:26:34.356 --> 01:26:35.899
above the city skyline

01:26:35.899 --> 01:26:40.320
and was supposed to be an icon of a modernizing North Korea.

01:26:40.320 --> 01:26:42.906
It was planned to have restaurants, guest rooms,

01:26:42.906 --> 01:26:46.243
casinos and lounges, all to attract foreign visitors

01:26:46.243 --> 01:26:48.995
and crucially, foreign investment.

01:26:48.995 --> 01:26:52.457
What North Korea actually got was an endless money pit

01:26:52.457 --> 01:26:55.335
where construction and planning problems led the project

01:26:55.335 --> 01:26:56.378
to be abandoned.

01:26:56.378 --> 01:26:58.505
It was started in 1987,

01:26:58.505 --> 01:27:02.300
intended for Kim Il-Sung's 80th birthday in 1992,

01:27:02.300 --> 01:27:05.804
but it was abandoned, and is unfinished to this day.

01:27:05.804 --> 01:27:09.433
It was meant to be a monument to the nation's greatness,

01:27:09.433 --> 01:27:12.269
but instead it stands as a symbol to the vanity

01:27:12.269 --> 01:27:13.895
and wastefulness of a regime

01:27:13.895 --> 01:27:16.815
that would waste billions on vanity projects

01:27:16.815 --> 01:27:19.359
while their countrymen sink into poverty.

01:27:23.113 --> 01:27:25.282
The collapse of global communism.

01:27:26.741 --> 01:27:28.869
Change hit the world hard and fast

01:27:28.869 --> 01:27:30.787
and for all of its isolation,

01:27:30.787 --> 01:27:33.165
even North Korea would feel the effects.

01:27:33.165 --> 01:27:34.249
Under Gorbachev,

01:27:34.249 --> 01:27:37.544
Moscow became increasingly skeptical of North Korea

01:27:37.544 --> 01:27:41.047
and tried to push it to roll back its totalitarian control.

01:27:41.047 --> 01:27:44.801
Moscow's first formal delegation to Seoul in 1987

01:27:44.801 --> 01:27:47.637
was also a disaster for the North's hard line

01:27:47.637 --> 01:27:48.763
against the South,

01:27:48.763 --> 01:27:51.558
and it forced Pyongyang to start its own process

01:27:51.558 --> 01:27:54.936
of diplomatic engagement with the South in the years after.

01:27:54.936 --> 01:27:56.313
Under Deng Xiaoping,

01:27:56.313 --> 01:27:59.232
China also rolled back its aggressive state control

01:27:59.232 --> 01:28:02.861
of the economy and embraced limited economic liberalization.

01:28:02.861 --> 01:28:05.071
This led China to open up to the West,

01:28:05.071 --> 01:28:06.990
leaving North Korea to become something

01:28:06.990 --> 01:28:09.159
of an embarrassing irritant to them.

01:28:09.159 --> 01:28:11.786
Beijing did not abandon its old ally

01:28:11.786 --> 01:28:14.080
and economic aid continued,

01:28:14.080 --> 01:28:17.000
but diplomatic support for North Korea was less vocal

01:28:17.000 --> 01:28:19.544
as China sought a new place in the world diplomatic

01:28:19.544 --> 01:28:20.837
and economic order.

01:28:20.837 --> 01:28:25.842
Meanwhile, the rapid disintegration of the USSR in 1991

01:28:25.842 --> 01:28:30.013
was as much of a surprise to its allies as to its enemies

01:28:30.013 --> 01:28:33.016
and cut off a major ally for North Korea.

01:28:33.016 --> 01:28:35.185
As global communism collapsed,

01:28:35.185 --> 01:28:37.437
North Korea withdrew into itself.

01:28:37.437 --> 01:28:40.273
The regime re-anchored itself in Juche,

01:28:40.273 --> 01:28:42.943
insisting that North Korea's self-reliance

01:28:42.943 --> 01:28:45.820
was the key that would allow the nation to survive

01:28:45.820 --> 01:28:48.240
while other communist countries failed.

01:28:48.240 --> 01:28:50.116
Given China's liberalization

01:28:50.116 --> 01:28:52.577
and Gorbachev's opening to the West,

01:28:52.577 --> 01:28:55.664
Pyongyang probably wasn't wrong on this point.

01:28:55.664 --> 01:28:59.084
Opening itself up to new ideas could well have been fatal

01:28:59.084 --> 01:29:01.545
for North Korea's totalitarian regime.

01:29:01.545 --> 01:29:05.924
And so the hermit nation doubled down on its isolation.

01:29:09.678 --> 01:29:11.263
Nuclear North Korea.

01:29:12.430 --> 01:29:15.600
The increasingly rogue North Korea sought protection

01:29:15.600 --> 01:29:18.144
in nuclear weapons, but even there,

01:29:18.144 --> 01:29:20.981
the new realities of world politics were clear.

01:29:20.981 --> 01:29:24.442
The North had been eyeing nuclear technology for decades

01:29:24.442 --> 01:29:26.236
and had nuclear power plants,

01:29:26.236 --> 01:29:28.238
largely thanks to Soviet support,

01:29:28.238 --> 01:29:30.907
but it was still a long way from making nuclear weapons

01:29:30.907 --> 01:29:31.783
of its own.

01:29:31.783 --> 01:29:35.412
In the 1990s, the US began putting increasing pressure

01:29:35.412 --> 01:29:37.747
on North Korea to open up its reactors

01:29:37.747 --> 01:29:40.083
to international inspectors.

01:29:40.083 --> 01:29:43.545
In theory, North Korea's interest in nuclear technology

01:29:43.545 --> 01:29:46.047
was purely for energy purposes.

01:29:46.047 --> 01:29:49.718
The loss of fuel supplies and subsidies from the USSR

01:29:49.718 --> 01:29:52.429
had compromised the country's energy sector,

01:29:52.429 --> 01:29:54.180
but the risk of them repurposing it

01:29:54.180 --> 01:29:56.766
for nuclear weapons was obvious.

01:29:56.766 --> 01:29:58.393
Better, Washington argued,

01:29:58.393 --> 01:30:01.313
to stop them before they can repurpose that material

01:30:01.313 --> 01:30:04.024
into weapons than wait for them to do it.

01:30:04.024 --> 01:30:05.650
When the North suddenly withdrew

01:30:05.650 --> 01:30:09.112
from the International Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty

01:30:09.112 --> 01:30:13.950
in March, 1993, it triggered the first global nuclear scare

01:30:13.950 --> 01:30:16.036
of the post-Cold War World.

01:30:16.036 --> 01:30:17.829
There were talks of nuclear war.

01:30:17.829 --> 01:30:19.623
And a North Korean diplomat threatened

01:30:19.623 --> 01:30:23.918
that his nation "turn Seoul into a sea of fire."

01:30:23.918 --> 01:30:26.463
Like every North Korean nuclear scare,

01:30:26.463 --> 01:30:28.298
the boasting king to nothing.

01:30:28.298 --> 01:30:31.509
They didn't have the will or weapons to follow through.

01:30:31.509 --> 01:30:33.762
Furthermore, a US delegation led

01:30:33.762 --> 01:30:37.932
by former US President Jimmy Carter arrived in 1994

01:30:37.932 --> 01:30:39.976
and managed to convince Kim Il-Sung

01:30:39.976 --> 01:30:43.021
to scale back the nuclear program if the US agreed

01:30:43.021 --> 01:30:46.149
to provide safer non-weaponizable alternatives

01:30:46.149 --> 01:30:48.818
for the DPRK's energy needs.

01:30:48.818 --> 01:30:49.653
For a moment,

01:30:49.653 --> 01:30:52.405
it looked like North Korea's path might change.

01:30:52.405 --> 01:30:54.741
The world had forced a readjustment.

01:30:54.741 --> 01:30:57.494
The DPRK had agreed to international help,

01:30:57.494 --> 01:30:59.079
and Western help at that,

01:30:59.079 --> 01:31:01.539
for a critical part of its economy.

01:31:01.539 --> 01:31:03.833
Even better, Kim agreed to host a meeting

01:31:03.833 --> 01:31:06.294
with the South Korean president in Pyongyang

01:31:06.294 --> 01:31:11.299
in late July, 1994, an unprecedented diplomatic gesture.

01:31:11.591 --> 01:31:13.677
It was a glimpse of hope,

01:31:13.677 --> 01:31:17.097
the potential for a more cooperative North Korea,

01:31:17.097 --> 01:31:19.391
but that glimpse wouldn't last

01:31:19.391 --> 01:31:21.935
and neither would Kim Il-Sung.

01:31:26.356 --> 01:31:27.941
Death of the great leader.

01:31:29.651 --> 01:31:33.113
Just before noon on the 7th of July, 1994,

01:31:33.113 --> 01:31:37.033
82-year-old Kim Il-Sung collapsed at his private residence

01:31:37.033 --> 01:31:38.952
in Hyangsan province.

01:31:38.952 --> 01:31:41.579
He'd suffered a massive heart attack.

01:31:41.579 --> 01:31:44.708
The best doctors in the country were flown in to help him,

01:31:44.708 --> 01:31:46.793
but in the early hours of July 8th,

01:31:46.793 --> 01:31:50.296
the great leader of North Korea was declared dead.

01:31:50.296 --> 01:31:53.758
The state had secretly preparing for his death for years.

01:31:53.758 --> 01:31:55.844
Arrangements for national announcements,

01:31:55.844 --> 01:31:58.096
public mourning, and an elaborate funeral

01:31:58.096 --> 01:31:59.931
were already in place.

01:31:59.931 --> 01:32:01.599
Still, tradition demanded

01:32:01.599 --> 01:32:04.936
that his death only be announced 34 hours later.

01:32:04.936 --> 01:32:07.564
Every North Korean remembers where they were

01:32:07.564 --> 01:32:09.441
when they heard the news of his death.

01:32:09.441 --> 01:32:12.193
Neighbors gathered around the only TV in the street

01:32:12.193 --> 01:32:13.445
to hear the news.

01:32:13.445 --> 01:32:14.821
Students were called together

01:32:14.821 --> 01:32:17.490
so the announcement could be made to the whole school.

01:32:17.490 --> 01:32:19.033
Production lines halted

01:32:19.033 --> 01:32:21.411
as the news spread through the factories.

01:32:21.411 --> 01:32:26.416
The 34,000 statues of Kim Il-Sung dotted around the country

01:32:26.541 --> 01:32:30.670
became pilgrimage points for a nation consumed with grief.

01:32:30.670 --> 01:32:32.839
From the outside, the outpouring of grief

01:32:32.839 --> 01:32:35.383
for Kim Il-Sung's Death seems bizarre.

01:32:35.383 --> 01:32:36.885
Was it all for show?

01:32:36.885 --> 01:32:40.013
A performative act by people who knew they could be punished

01:32:40.013 --> 01:32:43.099
for not seeming sad enough or was it all genuine?

01:32:43.099 --> 01:32:45.226
A sign of the thorough brainwashing

01:32:45.226 --> 01:32:47.312
that North Korea had been subjected to

01:32:47.312 --> 01:32:50.106
by Kim's regime for the last 40 years.

01:32:50.106 --> 01:32:52.400
Eyewitnesses vary on their answer.

01:32:52.400 --> 01:32:55.403
Many people in North Korea had never known life outside

01:32:55.403 --> 01:32:57.405
of the cult of the Kim dynasty,

01:32:57.405 --> 01:33:00.074
and the loss of the great leader was an emotional blow

01:33:00.074 --> 01:33:01.993
that upended their worldview.

01:33:01.993 --> 01:33:03.369
There were others, of course,

01:33:03.369 --> 01:33:06.581
who saw him as a tyrant, even if they couldn't voice it.

01:33:06.581 --> 01:33:09.125
They knew what had happened to friends, colleagues,

01:33:09.125 --> 01:33:12.587
and family members who had dared criticize him in the past.

01:33:12.587 --> 01:33:15.673
Supposedly Kim Il-Sung's elaborate state funeral

01:33:15.673 --> 01:33:18.593
attracted 2 million people to Pyongyang.

01:33:18.593 --> 01:33:22.096
Video footage showed weeping crowds falling to their knees

01:33:22.096 --> 01:33:24.057
as the convoy rolled past.

01:33:24.057 --> 01:33:26.768
Women collapsed into the arms of their husbands

01:33:26.768 --> 01:33:29.020
as they visited Kim lying in state.

01:33:29.020 --> 01:33:31.773
Again, it is impossible to draw the line

01:33:31.773 --> 01:33:34.484
between what was real and what was for show.

01:33:34.484 --> 01:33:38.446
One person who was definitely on show was Kim Jong-Il.

01:33:38.446 --> 01:33:40.406
For him, the funeral of his father

01:33:40.406 --> 01:33:43.743
was the first official act of his new regime.

01:33:43.743 --> 01:33:47.080
Kim was laid to rest in the Kumsusan Palace of the Sun

01:33:47.080 --> 01:33:48.581
in a glass coffin,

01:33:48.581 --> 01:33:52.669
where his embalmed body can still be seen by visitors today.

01:33:52.669 --> 01:33:56.589
He was also made Eternal President of the People's Republic,

01:33:56.589 --> 01:33:59.467
a symbol of his continual presence in the political

01:33:59.467 --> 01:34:02.178
and ideological life of North Korea.

01:34:06.099 --> 01:34:08.059
Reflecting on Kim Il-Sung.

01:34:09.227 --> 01:34:12.355
With Kim's death, a new chapter of the nation's history

01:34:12.355 --> 01:34:13.648
was about to begin,

01:34:13.648 --> 01:34:16.067
but we cannot proceed without taking a moment

01:34:16.067 --> 01:34:17.986
to reflect on the man's life.

01:34:17.986 --> 01:34:19.904
Modern historian like to move away

01:34:19.904 --> 01:34:22.365
from the stories of great men,

01:34:22.365 --> 01:34:26.411
but Kim Il-Sung was undeniably a special figure.

01:34:26.411 --> 01:34:27.871
His personality cult

01:34:27.871 --> 01:34:30.748
and practical power made him the most important person

01:34:30.748 --> 01:34:32.917
in his nation for half a century,

01:34:32.917 --> 01:34:35.128
and he used that influence to reshape the lives

01:34:35.128 --> 01:34:36.713
of millions of people.

01:34:36.713 --> 01:34:39.966
Few people ever lived such an impactful life.

01:34:39.966 --> 01:34:41.634
Kim must have been disappointed.

01:34:41.634 --> 01:34:43.219
Despite his efforts to hide it,

01:34:43.219 --> 01:34:45.597
North Korea had fallen behind its Southern enemies

01:34:45.597 --> 01:34:49.267
in prosperity, industry, technology, education,

01:34:49.267 --> 01:34:51.060
diplomacy, and more.

01:34:51.060 --> 01:34:54.939
The dreams of reunification seemed like a distant memory

01:34:54.939 --> 01:34:57.650
as western military technology continued

01:34:57.650 --> 01:35:00.945
to eclipse their outdated Soviet era weapons.

01:35:00.945 --> 01:35:04.407
Newfound diplomatic avenues between North and South showed

01:35:04.407 --> 01:35:05.950
that the North was starting to accept

01:35:05.950 --> 01:35:07.785
that its neighbor was here to stay.

01:35:07.785 --> 01:35:11.414
The continued economic rise of the capitalist nations,

01:35:11.414 --> 01:35:13.291
the liberalization of China,

01:35:13.291 --> 01:35:16.920
and the collapse of the USSR painted a grim picture

01:35:16.920 --> 01:35:20.506
for Kim's beloved Marxist-Leninist ideology.

01:35:20.506 --> 01:35:22.717
Many would say it was good riddance.

01:35:22.717 --> 01:35:26.054
Kim Il-Sung directly or indirectly caused the deaths

01:35:26.054 --> 01:35:29.474
of millions of people between his wars, death camps,

01:35:29.474 --> 01:35:32.018
firing squads, and famines.

01:35:32.018 --> 01:35:34.020
For every person shedding a tear

01:35:34.020 --> 01:35:37.440
in the streets of Pyongyang, there were probably many more

01:35:37.440 --> 01:35:39.776
around the world celebrating the demise

01:35:39.776 --> 01:35:43.404
of one of the century's most brutal dictators,

01:35:43.404 --> 01:35:45.615
but if anyone hoped that the great leader's death

01:35:45.615 --> 01:35:48.034
would improve things in North Korea,

01:35:48.034 --> 01:35:51.079
they were about to be sorely disappointed.

01:35:56.668 --> 01:35:58.544
The reign of Kim Jong-Il.

01:35:59.921 --> 01:36:01.881
The legend of Kim Jong-Il.

01:36:03.591 --> 01:36:06.135
Kim Il-Sung's death was rather sudden,

01:36:06.135 --> 01:36:09.555
but Kim Jong-Il's rise had been anything but.

01:36:09.555 --> 01:36:12.809
Kim Jong-Il had held an important place in the operation

01:36:12.809 --> 01:36:15.853
and propaganda of the regime for years.

01:36:15.853 --> 01:36:18.147
However, he was not his father.

01:36:18.147 --> 01:36:20.817
He lacked the true revolutionary pedigree

01:36:20.817 --> 01:36:23.528
and exciting life story of Kim Il-Sung.

01:36:23.528 --> 01:36:26.114
If he was going to inspire the same loyalty

01:36:26.114 --> 01:36:28.658
and enthusiasm, his propaganda machine

01:36:28.658 --> 01:36:30.743
would have to work even harder.

01:36:30.743 --> 01:36:31.661
As a result,

01:36:31.661 --> 01:36:34.831
North Korean propaganda churned ridiculous stories

01:36:34.831 --> 01:36:37.125
about Il's life and skills

01:36:37.125 --> 01:36:40.211
to make up for his rather uninspiring life story.

01:36:40.211 --> 01:36:43.214
It was said he was born on a sacred mountain

01:36:43.214 --> 01:36:46.551
and a new star appeared in the sky to mark his birth,

01:36:46.551 --> 01:36:49.178
or that his mood could change the weather.

01:36:49.178 --> 01:36:51.055
According to the propaganda,

01:36:51.055 --> 01:36:53.891
Kim was a creator and an innovator.

01:36:53.891 --> 01:36:57.478
He wrote 100s of movie scripts and operas during his life

01:36:57.478 --> 01:36:59.772
on top of the many ideological works

01:36:59.772 --> 01:37:01.983
that flowed from his pen like scriptures

01:37:01.983 --> 01:37:03.526
from the hands of a prophet,

01:37:03.526 --> 01:37:07.071
but maybe his greatest creation came in the 2000s

01:37:07.071 --> 01:37:10.450
when he invented a reward for outstanding students,

01:37:10.450 --> 01:37:13.828
a piece of meat stuck between two pieces of bread.

01:37:13.828 --> 01:37:16.789
The West quickly ripped off this stunning innovation

01:37:16.789 --> 01:37:18.332
and called it a hamburger,

01:37:18.332 --> 01:37:21.044
but North Korea knows the real truth.

01:37:21.044 --> 01:37:23.379
Kim was also a peerless sportsman.

01:37:23.379 --> 01:37:26.799
During his first game of bowling, he hit a perfect 300.

01:37:26.799 --> 01:37:29.927
Then of course there was his legendary golfing talent.

01:37:29.927 --> 01:37:32.847
Kim hit 11 holes in one in his first round

01:37:32.847 --> 01:37:34.265
of golf in Pyongyang,

01:37:34.265 --> 01:37:38.436
and he was so good that he decided to never play again.

01:37:38.436 --> 01:37:39.479
Why would he need to

01:37:39.479 --> 01:37:41.731
when he was already the best in the world?

01:37:41.731 --> 01:37:44.442
Even his toilet habits were mythologized

01:37:44.442 --> 01:37:46.402
or his lack thereof.

01:37:46.402 --> 01:37:49.363
According to the government, Kim Jong-Il never needed

01:37:49.363 --> 01:37:52.700
to use the toilet or attend to the basic bodily needs

01:37:52.700 --> 01:37:55.161
that mere mortals dealt with every day.

01:37:55.161 --> 01:37:57.288
It's likely that North Korean propaganda

01:37:57.288 --> 01:37:59.499
is bending the truth a little bit.

01:37:59.499 --> 01:38:01.417
In reality, very little is known

01:38:01.417 --> 01:38:03.461
about Kim Jong-Il's private life.

01:38:03.461 --> 01:38:05.213
He possessed multiple mistresses

01:38:05.213 --> 01:38:06.964
and had at least six children,

01:38:06.964 --> 01:38:09.884
although more might have existed out of public view.

01:38:09.884 --> 01:38:13.304
Despite his image as a staunch North Korean patriot,

01:38:13.304 --> 01:38:16.724
his undying love of Western films was a poorly kept secret

01:38:16.724 --> 01:38:18.059
of his private life

01:38:18.059 --> 01:38:20.436
and one of the only things we really know

01:38:20.436 --> 01:38:22.730
about his life behind closed doors.

01:38:22.730 --> 01:38:26.400
The propaganda made the new Kim out to be extraordinary,

01:38:26.400 --> 01:38:29.487
but reality was ready to put that to the test.

01:38:32.865 --> 01:38:34.575
The North Korean famine.

01:38:35.785 --> 01:38:38.704
Between debt, isolation, energy issues,

01:38:38.704 --> 01:38:40.665
and economic stagnation,

01:38:40.665 --> 01:38:43.126
it would've taken an extraordinary man

01:38:43.126 --> 01:38:45.503
to meet the challenges facing North Korea,

01:38:45.503 --> 01:38:48.256
and the new Kim did not measure up.

01:38:48.256 --> 01:38:51.342
The North's underlying collectivization policy kept

01:38:51.342 --> 01:38:54.512
the country on a knife's edge at the best of times.

01:38:54.512 --> 01:38:56.848
Therefore, when flooding caused crop failures

01:38:56.848 --> 01:38:59.267
across the nation in 1994

01:38:59.267 --> 01:39:02.353
and with food aid from the USSR long gone,

01:39:02.353 --> 01:39:05.148
North Korea fell into a dreadful famine,

01:39:05.148 --> 01:39:09.360
which the regime euphemistically called the "Arduous March."

01:39:09.360 --> 01:39:12.488
100s of 1,000s of people began to starve.

01:39:12.488 --> 01:39:14.282
Social order broke down.

01:39:14.282 --> 01:39:15.324
The black market,

01:39:15.324 --> 01:39:18.494
already a ubiquitous feature of North Korean life,

01:39:18.494 --> 01:39:21.038
became a lifeline for malnourished families

01:39:21.038 --> 01:39:22.623
who were easily exploited.

01:39:22.623 --> 01:39:24.500
Many people were forced to migrate

01:39:24.500 --> 01:39:26.711
in desperate search for food.

01:39:26.711 --> 01:39:28.546
This was technically illegal

01:39:28.546 --> 01:39:31.007
as the law required most people to have a permit

01:39:31.007 --> 01:39:32.383
to leave their town,

01:39:32.383 --> 01:39:34.719
but so many people had no other choice

01:39:34.719 --> 01:39:37.930
that there was no practical way to enforce the law.

01:39:37.930 --> 01:39:40.725
There were food riots in Hamhung and Sinuiju,

01:39:40.725 --> 01:39:44.061
and in some cities roaming gangs of starving orphans took

01:39:44.061 --> 01:39:46.480
to the streets in desperate search of food.

01:39:46.480 --> 01:39:49.233
The famine had political consequences too.

01:39:49.233 --> 01:39:51.944
A group of senior military officers headquartered

01:39:51.944 --> 01:39:55.031
in Hamhung City, one of the worst affected areas,

01:39:55.031 --> 01:39:58.367
held secret meetings in autumn, 1995.

01:39:58.367 --> 01:40:00.703
They discussed the idea of overthrowing Kim

01:40:00.703 --> 01:40:03.247
for his failures to address the crisis.

01:40:03.247 --> 01:40:06.042
State security services found out about the meetings,

01:40:06.042 --> 01:40:10.254
however, and all of the officers were arrested and shot.

01:40:10.254 --> 01:40:14.133
Kim Jong-Il was characteristically evasive about the issue.

01:40:14.133 --> 01:40:16.552
In a December, 1996 speech,

01:40:16.552 --> 01:40:19.597
Kim downplayed the famine as a food problem

01:40:19.597 --> 01:40:22.600
and was more concerned about the party's reputation

01:40:22.600 --> 01:40:24.352
than the suffering of his people.

01:40:24.352 --> 01:40:26.229
He blamed local party officials

01:40:26.229 --> 01:40:28.773
for failing to properly educate the masses

01:40:28.773 --> 01:40:31.692
in socialist ideas, which made them less loyal

01:40:31.692 --> 01:40:33.861
and was leading to social breakdown.

01:40:33.861 --> 01:40:36.572
He lamented that "the food problem

01:40:36.572 --> 01:40:38.908
is creating a state of anarchy,"

01:40:38.908 --> 01:40:42.495
but failed to offer any real solutions to this crisis.

01:40:42.495 --> 01:40:45.998
Kim was even reluctant to accept food aid from China

01:40:45.998 --> 01:40:49.126
because he felt it weakened and degraded his country.

01:40:51.963 --> 01:40:54.298
The Simhwajo and the end of famine.

01:40:55.841 --> 01:40:59.470
In 1997, drought extended the famine for another year,

01:40:59.470 --> 01:41:03.015
but as the famine raged, Kim Jong-Il kept scrambling

01:41:03.015 --> 01:41:05.309
to protect the regime's reputation.

01:41:05.309 --> 01:41:08.187
Kim made it illegal to utter the words famine

01:41:08.187 --> 01:41:10.940
or starvation in public or private.

01:41:10.940 --> 01:41:14.151
Violators could expect a visit from the Simhwajo,

01:41:14.151 --> 01:41:18.322
a secret police force established in 1996 to target those

01:41:18.322 --> 01:41:21.450
who tarnished the government's image amidst the famine.

01:41:21.450 --> 01:41:24.161
No one was safe from the Simhwajo.

01:41:24.161 --> 01:41:26.414
The agricultural secretary of the party

01:41:26.414 --> 01:41:30.084
was executed by firing squad on their orders.

01:41:30.084 --> 01:41:33.421
The general party secretary was tortured to death.

01:41:33.421 --> 01:41:34.839
And numerous provincial

01:41:34.839 --> 01:41:37.174
and municipal party leaders disappeared,

01:41:37.174 --> 01:41:38.759
never to be seen again.

01:41:38.759 --> 01:41:42.013
In all, over 10,000 people were killed

01:41:42.013 --> 01:41:45.391
and another 15,000 were put into concentration camps

01:41:45.391 --> 01:41:47.685
by this shadowy organization.

01:41:47.685 --> 01:41:49.645
Despite their efforts to hide it, though,

01:41:49.645 --> 01:41:50.896
international observers

01:41:50.896 --> 01:41:54.984
and NGO workers soon exposed the extent of the crisis.

01:41:54.984 --> 01:41:56.110
By the late '90s,

01:41:56.110 --> 01:41:58.612
Pyongyang was forced to accept food aid,

01:41:58.612 --> 01:42:01.407
which finally brought the crisis under control,

01:42:01.407 --> 01:42:04.577
but not before countless people had perished.

01:42:04.577 --> 01:42:06.162
Pyongyang's official estimate

01:42:06.162 --> 01:42:10.416
is that 220,000 people died during the famine.

01:42:10.416 --> 01:42:12.918
International observers insisted was higher,

01:42:12.918 --> 01:42:17.131
anywhere between 600,000 and 3.5 million.

01:42:21.010 --> 01:42:22.928
The battle of Yeonpyeong Island.

01:42:24.263 --> 01:42:25.931
The famine might explain one

01:42:25.931 --> 01:42:27.767
of the biggest skirmishes between North

01:42:27.767 --> 01:42:29.935
and South since the armistice.

01:42:29.935 --> 01:42:32.063
North Korea was always unhappy

01:42:32.063 --> 01:42:34.106
with the armistice's naval boundary

01:42:34.106 --> 01:42:37.360
that gave South Korea control over several islands

01:42:37.360 --> 01:42:40.112
and valuable fishing spots in the Yellow Sea.

01:42:40.112 --> 01:42:41.781
With North Korean starving,

01:42:41.781 --> 01:42:45.576
those fishing grounds looked awfully tempting to the regime.

01:42:45.576 --> 01:42:49.246
In June, 1999, North Korea sent out small fleets

01:42:49.246 --> 01:42:50.706
of patrol in fishing boats

01:42:50.706 --> 01:42:53.918
across the naval boundary near Eonpyeong Island.

01:42:53.918 --> 01:42:57.421
Naturally South Korea responded with their own patrols,

01:42:57.421 --> 01:43:00.007
but neither side wanted to restart the war

01:43:00.007 --> 01:43:01.425
over some fish.

01:43:01.425 --> 01:43:02.468
For several days,

01:43:02.468 --> 01:43:04.762
North Korean ships would cross the boundary,

01:43:04.762 --> 01:43:08.349
antagonize the South Koreans, and then retreat back.

01:43:08.349 --> 01:43:11.102
Each time, both sides sent a few more ships

01:43:11.102 --> 01:43:14.355
and started to bring in heavily armed torpedo boats

01:43:14.355 --> 01:43:16.148
to intimidate their opponents.

01:43:16.148 --> 01:43:17.400
After a week of this,

01:43:17.400 --> 01:43:20.528
South Korea launched a bumping offensive.

01:43:20.528 --> 01:43:23.114
Basically the ships started ramming each other.

01:43:23.114 --> 01:43:24.615
This carried on for a few days

01:43:24.615 --> 01:43:26.867
and ships on both sides were damaged.

01:43:26.867 --> 01:43:27.952
It was risky,

01:43:27.952 --> 01:43:31.455
since accidentally sinking a ship could make things worse

01:43:31.455 --> 01:43:33.833
or one of the military ships could panic

01:43:33.833 --> 01:43:36.669
and turn it into a shooting offensive instead.

01:43:36.669 --> 01:43:39.255
Unfortunately, that's exactly what happened

01:43:39.255 --> 01:43:40.840
on the 15th of June.

01:43:40.840 --> 01:43:44.051
A North Korean patrol boat panicked after surrounded

01:43:44.051 --> 01:43:47.680
by South Korean ships and opened fire with its cannons.

01:43:47.680 --> 01:43:51.308
The South Koreans shot back and for 15 minutes,

01:43:51.308 --> 01:43:52.977
the war was back on.

01:43:52.977 --> 01:43:55.521
In the end, one North Korean ship was sunk

01:43:55.521 --> 01:43:57.773
and five others were badly damaged.

01:43:57.773 --> 01:44:00.776
At least 17 North Korean sailors died,

01:44:00.776 --> 01:44:04.071
but the South Koreans only had a few minor injuries.

01:44:04.071 --> 01:44:06.490
The North Koreans limped back to safety.

01:44:06.490 --> 01:44:08.826
The battle of Yeonpyeong island was over,

01:44:08.826 --> 01:44:11.745
but the peninsula braced itself for the consequences

01:44:11.745 --> 01:44:14.331
and a potential restart of the war.

01:44:14.331 --> 01:44:16.709
Fortunately, nothing came of it.

01:44:16.709 --> 01:44:19.378
North Korea had learned its lesson for now.

01:44:19.378 --> 01:44:21.589
North Korea propaganda told the people

01:44:21.589 --> 01:44:24.341
that they had won a tremendous victory

01:44:24.341 --> 01:44:27.928
and sunk at least 10 South Korean battleships,

01:44:27.928 --> 01:44:29.805
and then quickly buried the event.

01:44:33.476 --> 01:44:34.393
Songun.

01:44:35.561 --> 01:44:37.229
The Battle of Yeonpyeong Island

01:44:37.229 --> 01:44:39.940
was a poor showing for the DPRK,

01:44:39.940 --> 01:44:42.568
which must have stung for Kim Jong-Il.

01:44:42.568 --> 01:44:45.070
Although he never served on the frontline himself,

01:44:45.070 --> 01:44:47.490
Il was obsessed with the military.

01:44:47.490 --> 01:44:50.868
He had been appointed to the military commission in 1980

01:44:50.868 --> 01:44:52.536
and had been made Supreme Commander

01:44:52.536 --> 01:44:56.665
of the Korean People's Army in 1991, giving him years

01:44:56.665 --> 01:45:00.169
of prior experience overseeing military affairs.

01:45:00.169 --> 01:45:02.129
Kim's enthusiasm for the military

01:45:02.129 --> 01:45:04.840
was expressed through his ideal of Songun,

01:45:04.840 --> 01:45:07.009
or military first.

01:45:07.009 --> 01:45:10.387
Kim placed the military at the center of public life,

01:45:10.387 --> 01:45:13.682
ramping up military propaganda and placing its needs

01:45:13.682 --> 01:45:16.227
at the top of government priority lists.

01:45:16.227 --> 01:45:18.896
By songun's logic, it was the military,

01:45:18.896 --> 01:45:20.356
not the common people,

01:45:20.356 --> 01:45:22.858
who acted as vanguards for the revolution,

01:45:22.858 --> 01:45:24.401
and it was they who were the key

01:45:24.401 --> 01:45:26.987
to North Korea's long-term survival.

01:45:26.987 --> 01:45:30.491
The military became the model for all of society.

01:45:30.491 --> 01:45:33.536
Military discipline, obedience, and loyalty

01:45:33.536 --> 01:45:35.746
were to be emulated by all people

01:45:35.746 --> 01:45:38.290
in all aspects of North Korean life.

01:45:38.290 --> 01:45:42.127
Propaganda recentered the soldier and cast all citizens

01:45:42.127 --> 01:45:47.132
as soldiers in the endless war against the DPRK's enemies.

01:45:51.136 --> 01:45:52.846
Free markets in North Korea.

01:45:54.098 --> 01:45:56.350
Kim didn't neglect the economy either,

01:45:56.350 --> 01:45:57.851
but his indecisiveness

01:45:57.851 --> 01:46:00.771
and ineffectiveness did little to help anyone.

01:46:00.771 --> 01:46:04.483
Songun itself did provide some economic improvement.

01:46:04.483 --> 01:46:05.734
There were plenty of jobs

01:46:05.734 --> 01:46:07.736
to be had in upgrading the military,

01:46:07.736 --> 01:46:09.572
not to mention in conscription,

01:46:09.572 --> 01:46:11.031
but those alone weren't enough

01:46:11.031 --> 01:46:14.618
to address the country's obvious economic shortcomings.

01:46:14.618 --> 01:46:17.746
In 2002, international observers were shocked

01:46:17.746 --> 01:46:21.375
to see North Korea seemingly embrace market economics

01:46:21.375 --> 01:46:23.669
with the July 1st measures.

01:46:23.669 --> 01:46:25.045
Among a number of things,

01:46:25.045 --> 01:46:27.590
the July 1st measures adjusted the price of rice

01:46:27.590 --> 01:46:28.966
to follow the market,

01:46:28.966 --> 01:46:31.218
gave companies and managers greater freedom

01:46:31.218 --> 01:46:33.387
to purchase supplies in that market

01:46:33.387 --> 01:46:35.889
and work to establish official private markets

01:46:35.889 --> 01:46:39.059
for goods and services inside the DPRK.

01:46:39.059 --> 01:46:42.271
While hailed as a major reform in foreign media,

01:46:42.271 --> 01:46:45.399
in reality, the laws were a little more than a legalization

01:46:45.399 --> 01:46:48.319
of black market trade that had been happening for years.

01:46:48.319 --> 01:46:49.737
They were an acknowledgement

01:46:49.737 --> 01:46:52.156
of the country's underlying problems,

01:46:52.156 --> 01:46:53.866
not a solution to them.

01:46:53.866 --> 01:46:58.078
The illusion of a new economic turn was furthered in 2004

01:46:58.078 --> 01:47:01.290
with the opening of the Kaesong Industrial Park.

01:47:01.290 --> 01:47:04.084
This was a joint endeavor by North and South

01:47:04.084 --> 01:47:06.045
to improve economic ties.

01:47:06.045 --> 01:47:08.714
The Kaesong Park sits about 10 miles north

01:47:08.714 --> 01:47:10.507
of the demilitarized zone

01:47:10.507 --> 01:47:12.301
and allowed South Korean companies

01:47:12.301 --> 01:47:15.596
to employ North Korean labor to produce their goods.

01:47:15.596 --> 01:47:18.098
The wages were paid directly to the government,

01:47:18.098 --> 01:47:21.018
giving the north a useful source of foreign currency

01:47:21.018 --> 01:47:24.396
in exchange for cheap labor for the Southern companies.

01:47:24.396 --> 01:47:28.192
Although small in scale, it was a productive diplomatic step

01:47:28.192 --> 01:47:29.652
for the two Koreas

01:47:29.652 --> 01:47:32.988
and was an unusually direct attempt by Pyongyang

01:47:32.988 --> 01:47:36.575
to harness the power of capitalist business practices.

01:47:36.575 --> 01:47:38.744
Despite the hope of foreign observers,

01:47:38.744 --> 01:47:40.871
these changes were not as significant

01:47:40.871 --> 01:47:42.623
as foreign media presented them,

01:47:42.623 --> 01:47:45.125
and Pyongyang quickly got cold feet.

01:47:45.125 --> 01:47:46.210
After a few years,

01:47:46.210 --> 01:47:48.962
they clamped down hard on market training,

01:47:48.962 --> 01:47:52.883
banning all working age men and later all women under 50

01:47:52.883 --> 01:47:54.677
from participating in it.

01:47:54.677 --> 01:47:57.471
These bans probably didn't have much real effect

01:47:57.471 --> 01:48:00.557
on black market trading, but it signaled that Kim Jong-Il

01:48:00.557 --> 01:48:04.269
had not suddenly become a fan of free market economics.

01:48:08.941 --> 01:48:11.485
George Bush and the axis of evil.

01:48:12.653 --> 01:48:15.030
As North Korea entered the new millennium,

01:48:15.030 --> 01:48:18.492
it found itself increasingly villainized by the world.

01:48:18.492 --> 01:48:19.702
After 2000,

01:48:19.702 --> 01:48:22.621
the Bush administration took an increasingly firm line

01:48:22.621 --> 01:48:25.332
on Pyongyang and turned up their rhetoric.

01:48:25.332 --> 01:48:27.918
North Korea also faced renewed scrutiny

01:48:27.918 --> 01:48:29.461
from an international community

01:48:29.461 --> 01:48:32.131
that saw it as a relic of times passed.

01:48:32.131 --> 01:48:35.259
One driver of this new scrutiny was Lee Soon Ok,

01:48:35.259 --> 01:48:37.094
a defector who had spent five years

01:48:37.094 --> 01:48:39.513
in a North Korean concentration camp.

01:48:39.513 --> 01:48:43.267
Her 1999 memoir told tales of forced labor,

01:48:43.267 --> 01:48:46.478
the torture of prisoners, mandatory abortions,

01:48:46.478 --> 01:48:48.522
and public executions.

01:48:48.522 --> 01:48:51.942
In 2002, as part of the Bush administration's harder line

01:48:51.942 --> 01:48:55.237
on North Korea, she was invited to speak to the US Congress

01:48:55.237 --> 01:48:57.072
about her experiences there,

01:48:57.072 --> 01:48:59.867
holding up the dark underbelly of Kim's Korea

01:48:59.867 --> 01:49:01.201
for the world to see.

01:49:01.201 --> 01:49:03.954
In 2002, Bush described North Korea,

01:49:03.954 --> 01:49:07.624
alongside Iraq and Iran, as an axis of evil.

01:49:07.624 --> 01:49:09.585
In the wake of the 9/11 attacks,

01:49:09.585 --> 01:49:13.172
the US was wary of rogue states, like the DPRK,

01:49:13.172 --> 01:49:16.091
sponsoring attacks on American civilians.

01:49:16.091 --> 01:49:17.718
Given Kim Jong-Il's involvement

01:49:17.718 --> 01:49:21.555
with terror attacks such as the bombing of Flight 858,

01:49:21.555 --> 01:49:24.224
it wasn't an unreasonable concern.

01:49:24.224 --> 01:49:27.853
The US' allies joined in its caution towards Pyongyang,

01:49:27.853 --> 01:49:30.272
and neither Russia nor China was strong enough

01:49:30.272 --> 01:49:33.192
to be an alternative ally to challenge the US

01:49:33.192 --> 01:49:35.235
as they had during the Cold War.

01:49:39.281 --> 01:49:40.908
Nuclear North Korea.

01:49:42.576 --> 01:49:44.203
It's perhaps no surprise

01:49:44.203 --> 01:49:47.623
that Kim Jong-Il continued his country's nuclear program

01:49:47.623 --> 01:49:49.208
amidst this hostility.

01:49:49.208 --> 01:49:51.919
The 1994 nuclear agreement spearheaded

01:49:51.919 --> 01:49:55.464
by Jimmy Carter failed to prevent North Korea continuing

01:49:55.464 --> 01:49:57.591
its nuclear missile development.

01:49:57.591 --> 01:49:59.301
The Clinton administration had tried

01:49:59.301 --> 01:50:01.553
to engage Pyongyang in negotiations

01:50:01.553 --> 01:50:04.223
to stall the development of ballistic missiles,

01:50:04.223 --> 01:50:05.933
but achieved very little.

01:50:05.933 --> 01:50:09.728
And Kim Jong-IL became skilled at using the nuclear program

01:50:09.728 --> 01:50:12.731
as leverage to gain more economic aid.

01:50:12.731 --> 01:50:15.984
By 2002, the CIA believed North Korea possessed

01:50:15.984 --> 01:50:17.820
at least one nuclear weapon

01:50:17.820 --> 01:50:20.739
and had the capacity to create even more.

01:50:20.739 --> 01:50:23.617
However, the first known successful detonation

01:50:23.617 --> 01:50:26.662
didn't occur until October, 2006.

01:50:26.662 --> 01:50:29.456
Reality still constrained Kim, though.

01:50:29.456 --> 01:50:32.209
His nuclear weapons would not solve the energy

01:50:32.209 --> 01:50:35.170
or economic crisises afflicting his country.

01:50:35.170 --> 01:50:38.841
Pyongyang ultimately needed a functioning nation more

01:50:38.841 --> 01:50:40.801
than they needed nuclear weapons.

01:50:40.801 --> 01:50:45.389
And so in 2007, after multiple conferences with the US,

01:50:45.389 --> 01:50:48.433
South Korea, Japan, Russia, and China,

01:50:48.433 --> 01:50:51.645
North Korea agreed to suspend its weapons program

01:50:51.645 --> 01:50:54.690
and shut down its main nuclear reactor at Yongbyon

01:50:54.690 --> 01:50:57.234
in exchange for diplomatic concessions

01:50:57.234 --> 01:51:00.654
and massive amounts of fuel and economic aid.

01:51:00.654 --> 01:51:02.865
It was a short-lived concession.

01:51:02.865 --> 01:51:05.492
The North refused to accept international observers

01:51:05.492 --> 01:51:08.829
to inspect its reactors and continue to test rockets

01:51:08.829 --> 01:51:12.249
that could be capable of delivering nuclear payloads.

01:51:12.249 --> 01:51:13.750
When the UN sanctioned them,

01:51:13.750 --> 01:51:17.337
the DPRK announced it was resuming its weapons program

01:51:17.337 --> 01:51:20.549
and reactor operations in full capacity.

01:51:25.220 --> 01:51:28.765
The Won revaluation crisis of 2009.

01:51:30.100 --> 01:51:33.103
The biggest stumble of Kim's regime probably came

01:51:33.103 --> 01:51:36.523
with the disastrous money reforms in 2009.

01:51:36.523 --> 01:51:39.026
That year, Pyongyang had the bright idea

01:51:39.026 --> 01:51:40.736
of reforming the currency.

01:51:40.736 --> 01:51:43.238
It was standard fare for a communist regime,

01:51:43.238 --> 01:51:45.157
announced that all existing bank notes

01:51:45.157 --> 01:51:48.076
will be taken out of circulation and made worthless,

01:51:48.076 --> 01:51:50.579
and people have a short window to exchange them

01:51:50.579 --> 01:51:52.122
for new bank notes.

01:51:52.122 --> 01:51:54.666
However, Pyongyang set daily limits

01:51:54.666 --> 01:51:57.377
on how much currency people could exchange,

01:51:57.377 --> 01:51:59.546
which meant that most people would lose money

01:51:59.546 --> 01:52:02.716
by being unable to convert it in the short timeframe.

01:52:02.716 --> 01:52:04.259
This was intentional.

01:52:04.259 --> 01:52:06.386
The regime wanted to reduce the money supply

01:52:06.386 --> 01:52:09.890
to reduce inflation while wiping out illegal savings made

01:52:09.890 --> 01:52:12.893
by black marketeers and other criminals.

01:52:12.893 --> 01:52:15.646
The end goal was for the new one Won

01:52:15.646 --> 01:52:18.690
to buy as much as the old 100 Won,

01:52:18.690 --> 01:52:21.234
but economics is not that simple,

01:52:21.234 --> 01:52:24.196
especially not with Kim Jong-Il at the helm.

01:52:24.196 --> 01:52:26.365
It seems that Kim Jong-Il felt the reforms

01:52:26.365 --> 01:52:28.241
would punish loyal workers.

01:52:28.241 --> 01:52:31.453
After all, why should they lose money under the reforms?

01:52:31.453 --> 01:52:32.704
He had a solution.

01:52:32.704 --> 01:52:34.373
Every government employee,

01:52:34.373 --> 01:52:36.792
which meant almost everyone in the country,

01:52:36.792 --> 01:52:39.002
would keep the same numerical wage

01:52:39.002 --> 01:52:41.505
after the reforms as before.

01:52:41.505 --> 01:52:45.175
Of course, since one Won would be worth 100 times more

01:52:45.175 --> 01:52:46.510
after the reforms,

01:52:46.510 --> 01:52:49.262
Kim was basically increasing nearly every wage

01:52:49.262 --> 01:52:52.140
in the country by 10,000%.

01:52:52.140 --> 01:52:54.851
Obviously, this was a catastrophe.

01:52:54.851 --> 01:52:57.479
The reforms produced confusion, chaos,

01:52:57.479 --> 01:52:59.564
and colossal inflation.

01:52:59.564 --> 01:53:00.816
Prices soared.

01:53:00.816 --> 01:53:02.401
The government tried to control them,

01:53:02.401 --> 01:53:05.445
but reality forced people to ignore the price caps.

01:53:05.445 --> 01:53:08.532
The regime was forced to close markets and shops

01:53:08.532 --> 01:53:10.117
to try and reign things in.

01:53:10.117 --> 01:53:13.412
Economic confusion and panic produced shortages

01:53:13.412 --> 01:53:14.788
of basic goods.

01:53:14.788 --> 01:53:18.709
These reforms affected everyone from peasants to generals,

01:53:18.709 --> 01:53:20.919
and perhaps for the first time ever,

01:53:20.919 --> 01:53:23.964
the idea that the regime might be overthrown became

01:53:23.964 --> 01:53:25.757
a real possibility.

01:53:25.757 --> 01:53:29.052
Foreign students remembered North Koreans openly complaining

01:53:29.052 --> 01:53:30.137
about the policy,

01:53:30.137 --> 01:53:32.723
and one North Korean diplomat angrily told

01:53:32.723 --> 01:53:33.974
a foreign representative

01:53:33.974 --> 01:53:37.561
that the government "doesn't understand what it's doing."

01:53:37.561 --> 01:53:39.646
Never had criticism of the regime

01:53:39.646 --> 01:53:43.900
by its own citizens been so public or so widespread.

01:53:43.900 --> 01:53:47.779
By April of 2010, however, conditions had stabilized.

01:53:47.779 --> 01:53:50.741
As people figured out the actual value of money,

01:53:50.741 --> 01:53:53.535
the economy started to function properly again.

01:53:53.535 --> 01:53:56.872
Soon after, the government rolled back almost all bans

01:53:56.872 --> 01:53:58.081
on market activity

01:53:58.081 --> 01:54:01.960
and explicitly ordered local authorities not to intervene

01:54:01.960 --> 01:54:04.713
in markets except to deal with illegal goods.

01:54:04.713 --> 01:54:06.548
The revaluation debacle

01:54:06.548 --> 01:54:09.426
was almost certainly Kim Jong-Il's doing.

01:54:09.426 --> 01:54:13.096
One historian described him as comically incompetent

01:54:13.096 --> 01:54:16.516
on economic issues, and only he could have proposed

01:54:16.516 --> 01:54:20.645
such an obviously stupid plan without anyone criticizing it.

01:54:20.645 --> 01:54:22.189
Several high ranking officials,

01:54:22.189 --> 01:54:25.275
including the head of economic policy in the KWP

01:54:25.275 --> 01:54:28.612
were scapegoated and executed or arrested,

01:54:28.612 --> 01:54:30.864
and the regime quickly buried the event

01:54:30.864 --> 01:54:33.366
and denied anything bad happened.

01:54:33.366 --> 01:54:35.744
It might not be the most exciting episode

01:54:35.744 --> 01:54:37.454
in North Korean history,

01:54:37.454 --> 01:54:39.790
but it might well be the closest the regime came

01:54:39.790 --> 01:54:41.291
to collapsing from within.

01:54:45.212 --> 01:54:47.172
Skirmishes with South Korea.

01:54:48.673 --> 01:54:49.966
Internal problems

01:54:49.966 --> 01:54:53.261
did not stop North Korea creating external problems

01:54:53.261 --> 01:54:54.387
for itself, though.

01:54:54.387 --> 01:54:56.515
Kim apparently hadn't let go of the dispute

01:54:56.515 --> 01:54:58.809
over fishing grounds in the Yellow Sea

01:54:58.809 --> 01:55:01.978
that it spilled over into skirmishes early into his reign.

01:55:01.978 --> 01:55:04.940
North and South again exchanged fire

01:55:04.940 --> 01:55:09.945
over fishing rights off Daecheong Island in November, 2009,

01:55:10.028 --> 01:55:14.116
resulting in an uncertain number of North Korean casualties.

01:55:14.116 --> 01:55:15.826
Given the tension in the area,

01:55:15.826 --> 01:55:19.204
it was natural for South Korea to keep ships nearby.

01:55:19.204 --> 01:55:22.332
One of those ships was the ROKS Cheonan.

01:55:22.332 --> 01:55:25.085
On the night of the 26th of March, 2010,

01:55:25.085 --> 01:55:28.088
the Cheonan was suddenly rocked by an explosion.

01:55:28.088 --> 01:55:30.298
The shocked crew scrambled to save her,

01:55:30.298 --> 01:55:33.093
but within 10 minutes, the ship had broken in half

01:55:33.093 --> 01:55:36.096
and sunk just off the coast of Baengnyeong Island.

01:55:36.096 --> 01:55:39.474
46 of its 104 crew drowned.

01:55:39.474 --> 01:55:42.853
South Korean officials scrambled for an explanation.

01:55:42.853 --> 01:55:44.563
There were no reports of conflict

01:55:44.563 --> 01:55:46.690
or North Korean ships in the area.

01:55:46.690 --> 01:55:49.818
An extensive investigation eventually determined

01:55:49.818 --> 01:55:53.655
that a North Korean torpedo had detonated beneath the ship.

01:55:53.655 --> 01:55:55.907
Fragments of the torpedo were recovered,

01:55:55.907 --> 01:55:58.994
and it was concluded that a small North Korean submarine

01:55:58.994 --> 01:56:00.370
had fired on them.

01:56:00.370 --> 01:56:02.581
Pyongyang denied the accusation,

01:56:02.581 --> 01:56:05.417
and was supported by both China and Russia.

01:56:05.417 --> 01:56:07.377
Counter arguments claimed that the Cheonan

01:56:07.377 --> 01:56:09.254
had collided with the sea floor

01:56:09.254 --> 01:56:12.257
and caused damage that led to the sudden explosion

01:56:12.257 --> 01:56:14.509
or that it had struck a sea mine.

01:56:14.509 --> 01:56:16.511
Several academic studies have failed

01:56:16.511 --> 01:56:18.263
to settle on an explanation,

01:56:18.263 --> 01:56:20.974
but South Korea and its allies continue to believe

01:56:20.974 --> 01:56:23.226
that North Korea was responsible.

01:56:23.226 --> 01:56:26.771
The sinking of the Cheonan caused relations to nose dive

01:56:26.771 --> 01:56:30.483
and rhetoric on both sides heated up in the following years.

01:56:30.483 --> 01:56:32.694
These tensions led to another engagement

01:56:32.694 --> 01:56:35.614
between North and South at Yeonpyeong Island.

01:56:35.614 --> 01:56:38.909
When South Korean forces performed naval exercises

01:56:38.909 --> 01:56:40.535
around the disputed island,

01:56:40.535 --> 01:56:44.915
North Korea fired almost 200 artillery shells at homes

01:56:44.915 --> 01:56:48.335
and military installations, which killed four people.

01:56:48.335 --> 01:56:49.878
and injured around 20.

01:56:49.878 --> 01:56:53.590
The South fired back and killed 10 North Korean soldiers

01:56:53.590 --> 01:56:55.759
before both sides seized fire.

01:56:55.759 --> 01:56:57.802
The North blamed the South for provoking them

01:56:57.802 --> 01:56:59.679
with military exercises.

01:56:59.679 --> 01:57:00.847
While the South insisted

01:57:00.847 --> 01:57:03.016
that the North bore full responsibility

01:57:03.016 --> 01:57:05.560
for opening fire without just cause.

01:57:05.560 --> 01:57:07.812
It is possible that the North was trying

01:57:07.812 --> 01:57:10.106
to make a statement against South Korea's admittance

01:57:10.106 --> 01:57:12.817
to the G20 earlier in 2010.

01:57:12.817 --> 01:57:14.653
Whatever the reason for the attack,

01:57:14.653 --> 01:57:17.697
it's likely Kim Jong-Il himself was involved.

01:57:17.697 --> 01:57:19.908
He had visited one of the artillery bases

01:57:19.908 --> 01:57:22.786
where Shells had been fired from the day before,

01:57:22.786 --> 01:57:24.996
and such a blatant provocation

01:57:24.996 --> 01:57:27.040
would've needed high level approval,

01:57:27.040 --> 01:57:29.000
but if Kim Jong-Il really was committed

01:57:29.000 --> 01:57:32.170
to armed provocation, then South Korea

01:57:32.170 --> 01:57:34.589
was about to catch a lucky break.

01:57:38.802 --> 01:57:40.428
Death of a dictator.

01:57:41.846 --> 01:57:45.892
In 2011, death once again struck the Kim regime

01:57:45.892 --> 01:57:47.018
without warning.

01:57:47.018 --> 01:57:48.645
On the 19th of December,

01:57:48.645 --> 01:57:50.522
the government announced the sudden death

01:57:50.522 --> 01:57:54.776
of Kim Jong-Il from a heart attack two days earlier.

01:57:54.776 --> 01:57:57.862
(speaking in Korean)

01:58:07.080 --> 01:58:10.166
(speaking in Korean)

01:58:13.837 --> 01:58:16.673
It claimed he'd been traveling aboard his personal train

01:58:16.673 --> 01:58:18.591
when he suffered the fatal attack.

01:58:18.591 --> 01:58:20.760
South Korean intelligence was skeptical

01:58:20.760 --> 01:58:22.929
of his claim since their spies reported

01:58:22.929 --> 01:58:25.598
that his train hadn't moved around the time of his death,

01:58:25.598 --> 01:58:28.727
but whatever the real circumstances of his death were,

01:58:28.727 --> 01:58:31.313
have been completely buried by the regime.

01:58:31.313 --> 01:58:33.023
As with his father's death,

01:58:33.023 --> 01:58:37.193
the DPRK was consumed with scenes of grief and distress.

01:58:37.193 --> 01:58:39.863
Crowds wept as they listened to the announcement,

01:58:39.863 --> 01:58:42.073
and his funeral was an elaborate spectacle

01:58:42.073 --> 01:58:43.700
for the tearful masses.

01:58:43.700 --> 01:58:46.661
Once again, how sincere these displays were

01:58:46.661 --> 01:58:48.121
is up for debate.

01:58:48.121 --> 01:58:49.956
Kim Jong-Il had officially ruled

01:58:49.956 --> 01:58:52.751
for less than half the length of his father's reign,

01:58:52.751 --> 01:58:54.461
and unlike his father

01:58:54.461 --> 01:58:57.297
had not thrown out any Japanese occupiers

01:58:57.297 --> 01:59:00.425
or waged any wars against its great enemies.

01:59:00.425 --> 01:59:04.179
Il's reign was also one of clear economic deprivation,

01:59:04.179 --> 01:59:07.390
of famine, and of North Korea's further decline

01:59:07.390 --> 01:59:08.892
into a pariah state,

01:59:08.892 --> 01:59:12.437
and even the laughing stock of the international community,

01:59:12.437 --> 01:59:14.981
who only got taken seriously when it threatened

01:59:14.981 --> 01:59:16.358
to destroy the world,

01:59:16.358 --> 01:59:19.736
promises it almost certainly couldn't back up.

01:59:19.736 --> 01:59:22.447
Still, the propaganda machine didn't slow down

01:59:22.447 --> 01:59:25.408
for his death any more than it did for his life.

01:59:25.408 --> 01:59:26.785
According to the regime,

01:59:26.785 --> 01:59:29.329
storms paused and the sky glowed red

01:59:29.329 --> 01:59:30.914
at the moment of his death.

01:59:30.914 --> 01:59:33.208
He was given the posthumous internal title

01:59:33.208 --> 01:59:37.420
of Grand Marshall, a symbol of his focus on the military

01:59:37.420 --> 01:59:39.839
and a sign of how important the military had become

01:59:39.839 --> 01:59:42.092
to the regime under his leadership.

01:59:42.092 --> 01:59:44.969
It was time for a new Kim to take power,

01:59:44.969 --> 01:59:48.181
but unlike Kim Jong-Il who had almost two decades

01:59:48.181 --> 01:59:50.767
of experience in politics under his belt,

01:59:50.767 --> 01:59:54.646
the newcomer to the throne was untested, inexperienced,

01:59:54.646 --> 01:59:57.774
and an unknown quantity for the rest of the world,

01:59:57.774 --> 02:00:02.737
Kim Jong Un.

02:00:03.863 --> 02:00:05.657
The reign of Kim Jong Un.

02:00:06.908 --> 02:00:09.035
Kim Jong Un's origins.

02:00:10.328 --> 02:00:12.372
Unlike his father, Kim Jong Un

02:00:12.372 --> 02:00:15.458
was not originally meant to be his father's successor.

02:00:15.458 --> 02:00:17.794
His elder half-brother, Kim Jong Nam,

02:00:17.794 --> 02:00:20.797
was the intended heir until he embarrassed the nation

02:00:20.797 --> 02:00:23.258
by getting caught using a fake passport

02:00:23.258 --> 02:00:26.511
to visit Disneyland, Tokyo in 2001.

02:00:26.511 --> 02:00:29.139
The new Kim had actually spent a large part

02:00:29.139 --> 02:00:31.724
of his childhood outside of North Korea.

02:00:31.724 --> 02:00:35.228
He spent most of the 1990s being educated in Europe,

02:00:35.228 --> 02:00:37.522
first in Switzerland, and then in Germany.

02:00:37.522 --> 02:00:40.900
By all accounts, Kim Jong Un was a normal kid.

02:00:40.900 --> 02:00:44.404
Apparently he was a quiet but generally pleasant young man,

02:00:44.404 --> 02:00:46.865
and no one could have expected that he was destined

02:00:46.865 --> 02:00:49.492
to be a totalitarian dictator.

02:00:49.492 --> 02:00:51.953
He loved basketball from a young age

02:00:51.953 --> 02:00:53.830
and remains a fan to this day,

02:00:53.830 --> 02:00:57.000
and classmates remember he was into video games too.

02:00:57.000 --> 02:00:58.460
Kim returned to North Korea

02:00:58.460 --> 02:01:00.712
to study at Kim Il Sung University.

02:01:00.712 --> 02:01:02.172
And very little is known

02:01:02.172 --> 02:01:05.258
about his life until his father suffered a small stroke

02:01:05.258 --> 02:01:06.676
in 2008.

02:01:06.676 --> 02:01:08.720
This health scare forced Kim Jong-Il

02:01:08.720 --> 02:01:10.430
to consider succession.

02:01:10.430 --> 02:01:14.350
And in 2009, word spread through the ranks of the KWP

02:01:14.350 --> 02:01:16.603
that a new heir had been chosen.

02:01:16.603 --> 02:01:20.106
Kim Jong Un stepped into the spotlight in late 2010.

02:01:20.106 --> 02:01:22.066
He was promoted to four star general

02:01:22.066 --> 02:01:24.486
despite having no military experience

02:01:24.486 --> 02:01:25.820
and began attending events

02:01:25.820 --> 02:01:29.199
and on the spot guidance sessions with his father.

02:01:29.199 --> 02:01:32.535
Propaganda had signaled him as the heir apparent,

02:01:32.535 --> 02:01:35.038
but he was never actually announced as such

02:01:35.038 --> 02:01:36.915
before his father's demise.

02:01:36.915 --> 02:01:38.082
It must have been a shock

02:01:38.082 --> 02:01:41.085
to find power falling into his hands so soon,

02:01:41.085 --> 02:01:43.838
for him and everyone else in Pyongyang.

02:01:47.800 --> 02:01:49.010
Un's reforms.

02:01:50.345 --> 02:01:52.847
With the little grounding in the running of the country

02:01:52.847 --> 02:01:55.725
and plenty of foreign experience under his belt,

02:01:55.725 --> 02:01:59.103
it was no surprise that Kim Jong Un caused a change

02:01:59.103 --> 02:02:00.688
in North Korean government.

02:02:00.688 --> 02:02:02.857
A hallmark of Kim Jong Un's tenure

02:02:02.857 --> 02:02:05.527
has been a pivot away from the military

02:02:05.527 --> 02:02:07.237
and back towards the party.

02:02:07.237 --> 02:02:09.864
Party officials, not military officials,

02:02:09.864 --> 02:02:12.992
have increasingly become the most influential figures

02:02:12.992 --> 02:02:13.868
in government.

02:02:13.868 --> 02:02:16.204
The Permanent National Defense Commission

02:02:16.204 --> 02:02:19.207
was abolished in favor of a State Affairs Commission

02:02:19.207 --> 02:02:22.001
that focused less on external military threats

02:02:22.001 --> 02:02:25.296
and more on internal economic and social goals.

02:02:25.296 --> 02:02:27.924
This change has several root causes.

02:02:27.924 --> 02:02:30.385
The first might be that Kim Jong Un himself

02:02:30.385 --> 02:02:34.097
does not have strong military credentials, unlike his father

02:02:34.097 --> 02:02:37.809
who held nominal leadership positions in the armed forces

02:02:37.809 --> 02:02:39.686
and coordinated foreign operations

02:02:39.686 --> 02:02:41.771
for military intelligence.

02:02:41.771 --> 02:02:45.233
Un's military titles are a little more than ceremonial.

02:02:45.233 --> 02:02:46.526
The decreasing emphasis

02:02:46.526 --> 02:02:49.779
on the military also reflected a changing world.

02:02:49.779 --> 02:02:52.991
The prospect of North Korea resolving any of its disputes

02:02:52.991 --> 02:02:56.244
with military force is more unlikely than ever,

02:02:56.244 --> 02:02:59.497
plus its enemies are now incomparably more advanced

02:02:59.497 --> 02:03:01.207
than them on the battlefield.

02:03:01.207 --> 02:03:04.127
There is no reason to expect the military to be the key

02:03:04.127 --> 02:03:07.171
to a prosperous future for the DPRK.

02:03:07.171 --> 02:03:10.049
That isn't to say the military isn't still important,

02:03:10.049 --> 02:03:11.175
of course it is,

02:03:11.175 --> 02:03:15.013
however it is not the absolute priority of Un's regime

02:03:15.013 --> 02:03:16.723
as it was for his father,

02:03:16.723 --> 02:03:19.475
and the generals seem to have lost their place in favor

02:03:19.475 --> 02:03:23.229
of the party apparatchiks and industrial managers.

02:03:27.567 --> 02:03:29.444
The purge of Jang Song-Thaek.

02:03:30.945 --> 02:03:34.824
Given the power of the Kim Cult, it was perhaps inevitable

02:03:34.824 --> 02:03:36.576
that the biggest threats to the regime

02:03:36.576 --> 02:03:38.620
would emerge within the family.

02:03:38.620 --> 02:03:42.457
Kim Jong Un came to see one in his uncle, Jang Song-Thaek.

02:03:42.457 --> 02:03:44.959
Song-Thaek was a veteran administrator

02:03:44.959 --> 02:03:46.711
with decades of experience

02:03:46.711 --> 02:03:49.088
and many loyal allies in the regime.

02:03:49.088 --> 02:03:52.300
The prospect of him succeeding his brother, Kim Jong-Il,

02:03:52.300 --> 02:03:55.928
had been a possibility considered by foreign intelligence

02:03:55.928 --> 02:03:59.849
and, it seems, in the corridors of power and Pyongyang.

02:03:59.849 --> 02:04:02.769
The old guard of Pyongyang cannot have been thrilled

02:04:02.769 --> 02:04:06.397
to be led by a young, inexperienced Kim Jong Un.

02:04:06.397 --> 02:04:10.026
So Jang represented a potential alternative.

02:04:10.026 --> 02:04:12.904
At first, Jang maintained significant power

02:04:12.904 --> 02:04:14.530
under his nephew's regime.

02:04:14.530 --> 02:04:17.659
He took a leading role in diplomatic relations with China

02:04:17.659 --> 02:04:21.496
and continued to exercise significant influence over policy.

02:04:21.496 --> 02:04:23.414
However, by late 2012,

02:04:23.414 --> 02:04:26.501
Kim Jong Un began pushing him out of power.

02:04:26.501 --> 02:04:28.795
He was moved out of diplomatic affairs

02:04:28.795 --> 02:04:31.839
and excluded from national security meetings.

02:04:31.839 --> 02:04:35.051
The breaking point appears to have been over fish.

02:04:35.051 --> 02:04:38.596
Jang and Un had a falling out over control over fisheries

02:04:38.596 --> 02:04:39.847
in the Yellow Sea.

02:04:39.847 --> 02:04:42.809
Details are vague, but the New York Times reported

02:04:42.809 --> 02:04:46.688
that gunfire was exchanged between forces loyal to Jang

02:04:46.688 --> 02:04:49.065
and those loyal to Kim Jong Un.

02:04:49.065 --> 02:04:51.943
Shortly after, Jang was stripped of his post,

02:04:51.943 --> 02:04:54.487
accused of treason, and arrested.

02:04:54.487 --> 02:04:59.075
A scathing 3000 word statement declared Jang a traitor

02:04:59.075 --> 02:05:02.745
who worked to undermine the DPRK for decades.

02:05:02.745 --> 02:05:06.457
He was accused of countless crimes ranging from conspiracy

02:05:06.457 --> 02:05:11.003
to corrupt the youth, right down to half-heartedly clapping.

02:05:11.003 --> 02:05:16.008
Jang was executed by firing squad on December 12th, 2013.

02:05:16.175 --> 02:05:18.803
Some of Jang's allies also fell from grace,

02:05:18.803 --> 02:05:22.598
most harshly of all, the deputy security ministers,

02:05:22.598 --> 02:05:25.977
O Sang Hon, who was burned to death with a flamethrower

02:05:25.977 --> 02:05:27.520
in 2014.

02:05:27.520 --> 02:05:31.649
It was the most high profile purge in the DPR case history

02:05:31.649 --> 02:05:34.485
and a powerful statement of Kim Jong Un's power,

02:05:34.485 --> 02:05:36.738
which showed that he was no less ruthless

02:05:36.738 --> 02:05:38.197
than his predecessors

02:05:42.368 --> 02:05:44.036
Kim Jong Un's image.

02:05:45.413 --> 02:05:48.791
That being said, Kim has tried to show himself as a softer,

02:05:48.791 --> 02:05:50.793
more friendly leader than his father.

02:05:50.793 --> 02:05:53.588
Kim Il-Sung and Kim Jong-Il had projected the image

02:05:53.588 --> 02:05:56.174
of a paternal but firm military leader

02:05:56.174 --> 02:05:58.760
with deep ideological commitments.

02:05:58.760 --> 02:06:01.846
Kim Jong Un, on the other hand, quickly established himself

02:06:01.846 --> 02:06:04.766
as more concerned with social and economic issues

02:06:04.766 --> 02:06:07.810
than military ones and proved to be more open

02:06:07.810 --> 02:06:10.563
to foreign culture within limits.

02:06:10.563 --> 02:06:13.649
In July, 2012, Kim shocked the world

02:06:13.649 --> 02:06:17.153
by appearing at a flashy pop concert in Pyonyang,

02:06:17.153 --> 02:06:18.821
complete with Western music

02:06:18.821 --> 02:06:21.824
and unusually scandalous costume choices

02:06:21.824 --> 02:06:24.285
for an overly modest North Korea.

02:06:24.285 --> 02:06:27.246
There were also performers dressed as Western icons

02:06:27.246 --> 02:06:29.999
like Mickey Mouse and Winnie the Pooh.

02:06:29.999 --> 02:06:33.461
Kim's companion to this concert also turned heads.

02:06:33.461 --> 02:06:37.340
His wife, Ri Sol Ju, previous wives and mistresses

02:06:37.340 --> 02:06:39.759
had mostly been hidden from public view.

02:06:39.759 --> 02:06:44.138
So Kim's public display of his wife was a surprising change.

02:06:44.138 --> 02:06:47.308
It suggested that this new Kim was more approachable,

02:06:47.308 --> 02:06:50.269
more human, and less detached from the world

02:06:50.269 --> 02:06:52.605
as his venerated forerunners were.

02:06:52.605 --> 02:06:54.857
Experts have attributed Kim's new style

02:06:54.857 --> 02:06:56.776
to his childhood in Switzerland.

02:06:56.776 --> 02:06:59.278
He grew up experiencing Western culture

02:06:59.278 --> 02:07:01.614
and hadn't expected to be leader,

02:07:01.614 --> 02:07:05.201
so it is natural for him to be less hostile to the West

02:07:05.201 --> 02:07:07.662
and less aloof than previous leaders.

02:07:10.540 --> 02:07:12.333
Basketball diplomacy.

02:07:13.751 --> 02:07:17.171
Nowhere has Kim's differences in attitude been more apparent

02:07:17.171 --> 02:07:19.507
than in his love of basketball.

02:07:19.507 --> 02:07:22.593
Kim's obsession with basketball has been lifelong.

02:07:22.593 --> 02:07:24.011
Schoolmates recalled that Kim

02:07:24.011 --> 02:07:26.389
was an enthusiastic basketball player

02:07:26.389 --> 02:07:28.266
and was often found sketching pictures

02:07:28.266 --> 02:07:30.017
of Michael Jordan in class.

02:07:30.017 --> 02:07:32.061
While he was generally shy,

02:07:32.061 --> 02:07:34.897
Kim was an entirely different person on the court,

02:07:34.897 --> 02:07:37.483
being more confident and competitive when playing

02:07:37.483 --> 02:07:39.569
than he ever was in regular life.

02:07:39.569 --> 02:07:42.864
Apparently, he had a room in his apartment in Germany filled

02:07:42.864 --> 02:07:44.782
with NBA merchandise

02:07:44.782 --> 02:07:47.660
and photos of famous players like Kobe Bryant.

02:07:47.660 --> 02:07:50.830
Unlike his father's love of Western films, however,

02:07:50.830 --> 02:07:53.833
Kim Jong Un has not been shy about showing his love

02:07:53.833 --> 02:07:57.336
for this iconically American game to the public.

02:07:57.336 --> 02:08:01.757
In 2013, legendary basketball player Dennis Rodman

02:08:01.757 --> 02:08:04.218
was surprised to receive an invite from Kim

02:08:04.218 --> 02:08:05.887
to visit Pyongyang.

02:08:05.887 --> 02:08:07.930
Rodman accepted and traveled there

02:08:07.930 --> 02:08:10.933
with several other players and a pack of journalists.

02:08:10.933 --> 02:08:12.268
This was the start of one

02:08:12.268 --> 02:08:15.479
of history's most bizarre friendships.

02:08:15.479 --> 02:08:18.190
Rodman has visited Kim several times,

02:08:18.190 --> 02:08:20.651
and the two enjoy a good relationship.

02:08:20.651 --> 02:08:23.112
Kim and Rodman have been pictured watching games

02:08:23.112 --> 02:08:26.324
and laughing together, and the two have exchanged gifts.

02:08:26.324 --> 02:08:30.912
In 2014, Rodman was roundly criticized in the Western media

02:08:30.912 --> 02:08:33.873
for singing Happy Birthday to the dictator.

02:08:33.873 --> 02:08:37.793
- Happy birthday to you.

02:08:37.793 --> 02:08:42.048
Happy birthday to you. (audience clapping)

02:08:42.048 --> 02:08:43.883
Happy birthday to you.

02:08:46.510 --> 02:08:48.346
Happy birthday to you.

02:08:52.433 --> 02:08:55.019
- [Narrator] Rodman has continued his friendship with Kim

02:08:55.019 --> 02:08:57.730
and visited North Korea multiple times.

02:08:57.730 --> 02:09:00.733
While Rodman has no official diplomatic role,

02:09:00.733 --> 02:09:02.944
his ability to exercise soft power

02:09:02.944 --> 02:09:05.529
and potentially influence Kim as his friend

02:09:05.529 --> 02:09:07.990
or raise delicate issues directly

02:09:07.990 --> 02:09:10.952
has been considered a useful diplomatic tool.

02:09:10.952 --> 02:09:12.411
Although Rodman does not appear

02:09:12.411 --> 02:09:14.580
to have achieved any diplomatic progress

02:09:14.580 --> 02:09:16.666
with this friendship, it remains one

02:09:16.666 --> 02:09:19.835
of the most unusual anecdotes in the history

02:09:19.835 --> 02:09:22.171
of an already unusual country.

02:09:26.092 --> 02:09:27.259
Culture laws.

02:09:28.344 --> 02:09:31.597
Kim's acknowledgement of foreign culture is surprising,

02:09:31.597 --> 02:09:34.934
but it is tightly controlled and very limited.

02:09:34.934 --> 02:09:37.895
It might even be misleading since in many ways,

02:09:37.895 --> 02:09:40.356
Kim Jong Un is harsher on foreign culture

02:09:40.356 --> 02:09:41.983
than his predecessors were.

02:09:41.983 --> 02:09:45.611
He has instituted a variety of harsh cultural laws designed

02:09:45.611 --> 02:09:47.947
to protect against foreign influence

02:09:47.947 --> 02:09:50.574
and preserve North Korea's own culture.

02:09:50.574 --> 02:09:54.120
Many things that the regime deems to be anti-socialist

02:09:54.120 --> 02:09:55.663
have been all but outlawed.

02:09:55.663 --> 02:09:57.873
The internet is the obvious first priority

02:09:57.873 --> 02:09:59.667
for controlling modern culture.

02:09:59.667 --> 02:10:01.085
Only a handful of people

02:10:01.085 --> 02:10:03.504
in the country may access the global internet,

02:10:03.504 --> 02:10:05.423
and even academic institutions

02:10:05.423 --> 02:10:07.383
are not permitted full access.

02:10:07.383 --> 02:10:10.011
The average North Korean is only permitted access

02:10:10.011 --> 02:10:14.056
to North Korea's special internet service called Kwangmyong.

02:10:14.056 --> 02:10:17.977
Kwangmyong is an entirely isolated network exclusive

02:10:17.977 --> 02:10:20.021
to the country that allows the regime

02:10:20.021 --> 02:10:23.774
to control all the information its citizens can access.

02:10:23.774 --> 02:10:25.067
Outside of the internet,

02:10:25.067 --> 02:10:26.527
music, film, and fashion

02:10:26.527 --> 02:10:28.654
which contradicts Pyongyang's ideals

02:10:28.654 --> 02:10:30.948
and sense of morality are banned.

02:10:30.948 --> 02:10:34.493
One of South Korea's most famous exports, K-pop,

02:10:34.493 --> 02:10:37.788
has been described as a vicious cancer by Kim,

02:10:37.788 --> 02:10:39.206
and the New York Times reported

02:10:39.206 --> 02:10:42.084
that seven people had been executed for listening to

02:10:42.084 --> 02:10:44.128
or sharing K-pop music.

02:10:44.128 --> 02:10:46.797
Western fashion, typically seen as too revealing

02:10:46.797 --> 02:10:48.883
and immodest, is prohibited.

02:10:48.883 --> 02:10:52.261
Haircuts are also famously controlled too.

02:10:52.261 --> 02:10:56.766
There are 15 state-permitted haircuts as of 2017.

02:10:56.766 --> 02:10:58.684
All of them designed to be practical

02:10:58.684 --> 02:11:00.519
for the good socialist worker

02:11:00.519 --> 02:11:02.813
and free of the needless extravagance

02:11:02.813 --> 02:11:04.648
of a capitalist consumer.

02:11:04.648 --> 02:11:07.359
These laws may seem strange to an outsider,

02:11:07.359 --> 02:11:10.571
but they make sense to the internal logic of North Korea.

02:11:10.571 --> 02:11:13.783
To allow any uncontrolled aspects of Western culture

02:11:13.783 --> 02:11:18.037
to slip through is to risk the fate of the USSR or China,

02:11:18.037 --> 02:11:21.373
who collapsed or reformed in the face of Western pressure.

02:11:21.373 --> 02:11:24.710
Furthermore, the thorough commodification of Western culture

02:11:24.710 --> 02:11:27.213
is a blatant capitalist intrusion

02:11:27.213 --> 02:11:30.758
upon the North's continued commitment to socialism.

02:11:30.758 --> 02:11:34.804
In Kim's eyes, the K-pop itself isn't really the issue,

02:11:34.804 --> 02:11:36.597
but what it represents,

02:11:36.597 --> 02:11:39.975
a seemingly unstoppable wave of foreign influence

02:11:39.975 --> 02:11:42.103
that his regime must contain

02:11:42.103 --> 02:11:44.772
in order to protect North Korea's way of life.

02:11:48.526 --> 02:11:50.986
Day in the life of an average North Korean.

02:11:52.363 --> 02:11:54.240
So what does life look like

02:11:54.240 --> 02:11:56.325
for an average North Korean today?

02:11:56.325 --> 02:11:58.869
Most people wake up, attend to their family,

02:11:58.869 --> 02:12:01.122
go to their state-assigned job

02:12:01.122 --> 02:12:03.624
and savor their leisure time when they can.

02:12:03.624 --> 02:12:06.460
Propaganda speakers blare in the background

02:12:06.460 --> 02:12:08.003
and state mandated events

02:12:08.003 --> 02:12:10.756
or holidays occasionally disrupt life,

02:12:10.756 --> 02:12:13.217
but the average day for a North Korean citizen

02:12:13.217 --> 02:12:15.719
is not some alien venture.

02:12:15.719 --> 02:12:17.012
The average North Korean

02:12:17.012 --> 02:12:19.890
is far poorer than the average Westerner.

02:12:19.890 --> 02:12:23.144
They do not have access to the same diverse range of food,

02:12:23.144 --> 02:12:26.230
heaps of modern technology, fancy clothes,

02:12:26.230 --> 02:12:27.940
or other luxuries.

02:12:27.940 --> 02:12:31.944
As of 2019, just 26% of households

02:12:31.944 --> 02:12:33.737
had access to electricity,

02:12:33.737 --> 02:12:37.616
rising to just over a third for those in urban areas.

02:12:37.616 --> 02:12:38.993
Some of the larger cities

02:12:38.993 --> 02:12:41.787
have also seen increased automobile ownership

02:12:41.787 --> 02:12:42.997
in recent years,

02:12:42.997 --> 02:12:46.959
although the average rural family will never own a vehicle.

02:12:46.959 --> 02:12:50.796
Some of these more rural areas are truly undeveloped.

02:12:50.796 --> 02:12:53.799
Isolated villages might not even have running water,

02:12:53.799 --> 02:12:55.426
let alone electricity.

02:12:55.426 --> 02:12:57.928
Although most people live in relative poverty,

02:12:57.928 --> 02:13:01.056
there is a growing middle class in the big cities.

02:13:01.056 --> 02:13:03.851
A comfortable lifestyle with expensive restaurants

02:13:03.851 --> 02:13:05.144
and a department stores

02:13:05.144 --> 02:13:08.230
are increasingly available to the middle classes,

02:13:08.230 --> 02:13:10.816
even if that middle class is a small percentage

02:13:10.816 --> 02:13:12.193
of the population.

02:13:12.193 --> 02:13:16.447
The contrast between rich and poor can be astounding.

02:13:16.447 --> 02:13:19.366
Defectors have always stressed that above all,

02:13:19.366 --> 02:13:21.744
North Koreans are normal people too.

02:13:21.744 --> 02:13:24.788
The regime and its ideology are more prominent in their life

02:13:24.788 --> 02:13:27.041
than such things are for most people,

02:13:27.041 --> 02:13:29.793
but they fade into the background in the day to day.

02:13:29.793 --> 02:13:31.420
Like everyone else in the world,

02:13:31.420 --> 02:13:33.631
the average North Korean is more concerned

02:13:33.631 --> 02:13:36.759
about their family, their job, their love life,

02:13:36.759 --> 02:13:38.886
their friends and hobbies than they are

02:13:38.886 --> 02:13:41.805
about the ideological mission of their country.

02:13:41.805 --> 02:13:44.433
Many may believe wholeheartedly in it

02:13:44.433 --> 02:13:46.310
and some certainly oppose it,

02:13:46.310 --> 02:13:49.104
but most people fall somewhere in between.

02:13:49.104 --> 02:13:51.106
As long as they can live their lives,

02:13:51.106 --> 02:13:53.359
politics is a secondary concern.

02:13:57.780 --> 02:13:59.281
Nuclear threats.

02:14:00.491 --> 02:14:03.494
It can be easy to forget that North Korea is a nation

02:14:03.494 --> 02:14:05.788
of normal people when most of our exposure

02:14:05.788 --> 02:14:07.456
to the country seems to come

02:14:07.456 --> 02:14:11.085
from its promises of nuclear destruction upon its enemies.

02:14:11.085 --> 02:14:15.256
Kim Jong Un has reemphasized the old idea of Byungjin,

02:14:15.256 --> 02:14:18.425
applied specifically to the country's nuclear mission,

02:14:18.425 --> 02:14:20.678
believing that the economic future of the nation

02:14:20.678 --> 02:14:25.099
is inseparable from its ability to acquire nuclear weapons.

02:14:25.099 --> 02:14:27.434
Even education is pivoted towards it,

02:14:27.434 --> 02:14:29.061
with the best students encouraged

02:14:29.061 --> 02:14:31.272
to enter nuclear related fields

02:14:31.272 --> 02:14:33.649
and graduates frequently being snapped up

02:14:33.649 --> 02:14:36.193
by the nuclear weapons development sector.

02:14:36.193 --> 02:14:38.779
While Kim Jong-Il had seen to the creation

02:14:38.779 --> 02:14:41.323
of his country's first nuclear weapon,

02:14:41.323 --> 02:14:43.951
Kim Jong Un's task was delivery.

02:14:43.951 --> 02:14:46.412
His regime has been especially interested

02:14:46.412 --> 02:14:49.331
in ballistic missile technology that would allow it

02:14:49.331 --> 02:14:52.543
to deliver those weapons onto enemy soil.

02:14:52.543 --> 02:14:55.045
Kim signaled his commitment to this early,

02:14:55.045 --> 02:14:57.756
even in the face of international condemnation.

02:14:57.756 --> 02:15:00.217
The launch of the Kwangmyongsong-3 satellite

02:15:00.217 --> 02:15:03.512
in December, 2012 was roundly condemned

02:15:03.512 --> 02:15:06.223
because it was seen as a thinly veiled attempt

02:15:06.223 --> 02:15:08.767
to test ballistic missile technology.

02:15:08.767 --> 02:15:11.562
Since the rocket utilized the same technology,

02:15:11.562 --> 02:15:14.440
the launch led to increased rhetoric on both sides,

02:15:14.440 --> 02:15:16.150
which only worsened when the North claimed

02:15:16.150 --> 02:15:20.237
to detonate another nuclear device in early 2013.

02:15:20.237 --> 02:15:23.574
During a disarmament conference in Geneva, shortly after,

02:15:23.574 --> 02:15:25.993
a North Korean diplomat even threatened

02:15:25.993 --> 02:15:29.538
the final destruction of South Korea.

02:15:29.538 --> 02:15:32.791
As has become a pattern for Kim Jong Un's regime,

02:15:32.791 --> 02:15:35.753
these provocative nuclear tests heightened tensions

02:15:35.753 --> 02:15:38.297
for a few months before ebbing away.

02:15:38.297 --> 02:15:42.760
It occurred again in November, 2017 when the DPRK test fired

02:15:42.760 --> 02:15:45.763
its first nuclear capable ballistic missile,

02:15:45.763 --> 02:15:46.597
the Hwasong-15.

02:15:47.556 --> 02:15:49.516
The Hwasong test was critical

02:15:49.516 --> 02:15:52.561
because it proved that North Korea had missiles capable

02:15:52.561 --> 02:15:55.481
of hitting the continental United States.

02:16:01.195 --> 02:16:02.446
Cyber warfare.

02:16:03.781 --> 02:16:06.367
While its nuclear program grabs headlines,

02:16:06.367 --> 02:16:09.411
arguably Pyongyang's most potent modern weapon

02:16:09.411 --> 02:16:10.788
is cyber warfare.

02:16:10.788 --> 02:16:13.207
Even Kim Jong-Il was conscious of the power

02:16:13.207 --> 02:16:16.794
of new technology and supposedly once said,

02:16:16.794 --> 02:16:18.796
"if the internet is like a gun,

02:16:18.796 --> 02:16:21.632
cyber attacks are like atomic bombs."

02:16:21.632 --> 02:16:25.010
The North's cyber capabilities are nothing to scoff at.

02:16:25.010 --> 02:16:27.846
Pyongyang maintains an army of talented hackers

02:16:27.846 --> 02:16:30.182
that strengthened the regime in many ways.

02:16:30.182 --> 02:16:32.893
From running international scams to steal money,

02:16:32.893 --> 02:16:36.605
to hacking into foreign military databases to pillage data,

02:16:36.605 --> 02:16:39.942
a 2019 UN report estimated that North Korea

02:16:39.942 --> 02:16:44.113
had raised $2 billion from this type of cyber crime.

02:16:44.113 --> 02:16:46.615
Most people in the West first realized the power

02:16:46.615 --> 02:16:49.451
of North Korean cyber crime in 2014

02:16:49.451 --> 02:16:51.370
when Sony released the Seth Rogen

02:16:51.370 --> 02:16:54.415
and James Franco comedy, The Interview,

02:16:54.415 --> 02:16:58.335
a film where the clumsy heroes must infiltrate North Korea

02:16:58.335 --> 02:17:00.796
and assassinate Kim Jong Un himself.

02:17:00.796 --> 02:17:04.716
Pyongyang was furious, calling it provocative insanity

02:17:04.716 --> 02:17:08.595
and a most blatant act of terrorism and war.

02:17:08.595 --> 02:17:12.850
In response, DPRK hackers broke into Sony systems,

02:17:12.850 --> 02:17:15.310
leaking emails, salaries, scripts,

02:17:15.310 --> 02:17:18.313
and even whole films that hadn't been released.

02:17:18.313 --> 02:17:20.357
The entire company was crippled

02:17:20.357 --> 02:17:22.943
for days in what President Obama announced

02:17:22.943 --> 02:17:25.571
as an act of cyber vandalism.

02:17:25.571 --> 02:17:28.323
A more elaborate and damaging cyber attack occurred

02:17:28.323 --> 02:17:32.202
throughout 2015 when hackers spent months infiltrating

02:17:32.202 --> 02:17:34.246
the Bangladesh National Bank.

02:17:34.246 --> 02:17:37.416
They spent months creating back doors into systems

02:17:37.416 --> 02:17:39.626
that allowed them to place withdrawal requests

02:17:39.626 --> 02:17:41.503
for massive amounts of money.

02:17:41.503 --> 02:17:44.923
The hackers attempted to withdraw almost a billion dollars

02:17:44.923 --> 02:17:49.887
in February, 2016 and made off with $101 million

02:17:49.970 --> 02:17:52.222
before security systems caught on.

02:17:52.222 --> 02:17:53.307
That same year,

02:17:53.307 --> 02:17:56.560
North Korean hackers stole over 200 gigabytes

02:17:56.560 --> 02:17:59.813
of top secret military intelligence from South Korea

02:17:59.813 --> 02:18:02.983
in 2016, including detailed plans

02:18:02.983 --> 02:18:04.610
for a conflict with the North

02:18:04.610 --> 02:18:07.696
and an assassination plot for Kim Jong Un.

02:18:07.696 --> 02:18:09.907
Probably the worst cyber attack

02:18:09.907 --> 02:18:12.826
was a 2017 ransomware attack

02:18:12.826 --> 02:18:16.330
where around 300,000 computers across the world

02:18:16.330 --> 02:18:18.457
were struck with a crypto worm.

02:18:18.457 --> 02:18:21.084
North Korean hackers targeted computers belonging

02:18:21.084 --> 02:18:24.671
to numerous organizations ranging from Microsoft

02:18:24.671 --> 02:18:26.924
to the British National Health Service,

02:18:26.924 --> 02:18:30.219
demanding payment in Bitcoin for the attack to stop.

02:18:30.219 --> 02:18:33.722
It took over seven hours for the attack to be contained

02:18:33.722 --> 02:18:36.225
and several days for it to be fully stopped,

02:18:36.225 --> 02:18:39.686
and in that time, it caused billions in damages.

02:18:39.686 --> 02:18:42.606
The world has adapted to North Korea's capabilities

02:18:42.606 --> 02:18:46.026
and governments now take the threat extremely seriously,

02:18:46.026 --> 02:18:48.028
but it is only a matter of time

02:18:48.028 --> 02:18:50.656
until Pyongyang's hackers strike again.

02:18:54.952 --> 02:18:55.994
Education.

02:18:57.663 --> 02:19:01.500
Of course, building that hacking network requires education,

02:19:01.500 --> 02:19:03.126
and that is something that the regime

02:19:03.126 --> 02:19:06.338
has also taken seriously since its inception.

02:19:06.338 --> 02:19:10.217
Universal education was put in place in 1959,

02:19:10.217 --> 02:19:13.178
guaranteeing up to 11 years of free education,

02:19:13.178 --> 02:19:15.847
including costs of uniforms, textbooks,

02:19:15.847 --> 02:19:18.350
and other necessities for all children.

02:19:18.350 --> 02:19:21.520
Official statistics assert that almost all children

02:19:21.520 --> 02:19:24.064
are enrolled for education in North Korea,

02:19:24.064 --> 02:19:26.817
and while some surely slipped through the cracks,

02:19:26.817 --> 02:19:30.737
all evidence supports the idea that education is one area

02:19:30.737 --> 02:19:33.282
that the DPRK has succeeded with.

02:19:33.282 --> 02:19:35.617
In 2012, Kim Jong Un expanded

02:19:35.617 --> 02:19:38.120
and adjusted that education provision.

02:19:38.120 --> 02:19:41.415
Now the state guarantees 12 years of education

02:19:41.415 --> 02:19:45.127
on a 6, 3, 3 system of six years in elementary,

02:19:45.127 --> 02:19:47.588
three in middle school, and three in high school.

02:19:47.588 --> 02:19:51.258
Of course propaganda is a big part of that education.

02:19:51.258 --> 02:19:52.551
The history of the revolution

02:19:52.551 --> 02:19:54.678
and the deeds of the Kim Dynasty

02:19:54.678 --> 02:19:57.180
are mandatory subjects in school,

02:19:57.180 --> 02:20:00.809
but North Korean children also receive a robust education

02:20:00.809 --> 02:20:04.187
in literacy, mathematics, and other subjects

02:20:04.187 --> 02:20:06.315
that stand up to the education available

02:20:06.315 --> 02:20:08.233
in most developed countries.

02:20:08.233 --> 02:20:10.694
Higher education is more limited.

02:20:10.694 --> 02:20:12.279
Being so closed off,

02:20:12.279 --> 02:20:15.240
North Korea has a small community of academics

02:20:15.240 --> 02:20:16.533
and very little chance

02:20:16.533 --> 02:20:19.453
to participate in global academic debate.

02:20:19.453 --> 02:20:21.580
Higher education, therefore, focuses

02:20:21.580 --> 02:20:23.874
on producing practical skills,

02:20:23.874 --> 02:20:27.252
especially in fields that have military applications.

02:20:27.252 --> 02:20:29.630
The peak of the higher education period

02:20:29.630 --> 02:20:32.507
is Pyongyang's Kim Il-Sung University.

02:20:32.507 --> 02:20:36.637
With 16,000 students, it is by far the largest

02:20:36.637 --> 02:20:39.431
and best funded university in the country.

02:20:39.431 --> 02:20:42.184
In recent years, Kim Jong Un has opened the country

02:20:42.184 --> 02:20:44.728
to limited academic exchange.

02:20:44.728 --> 02:20:47.564
Several hundred students, mostly Chinese,

02:20:47.564 --> 02:20:49.733
are permitted to study in North Korea,

02:20:49.733 --> 02:20:52.027
although they are closely watched.

02:20:52.027 --> 02:20:54.071
Increasingly the most exceptional

02:20:54.071 --> 02:20:56.031
and trustworthy North Korean students

02:20:56.031 --> 02:20:58.408
have been granted permission to study abroad.

02:20:58.408 --> 02:21:02.079
The regime has long recognized that North Korean education

02:21:02.079 --> 02:21:04.331
cannot match that available elsewhere

02:21:04.331 --> 02:21:07.542
or else Kim Jong Un himself would've been fully educated

02:21:07.542 --> 02:21:08.710
in country.

02:21:08.710 --> 02:21:11.713
And these students offer a chance to bring foreign knowledge

02:21:11.713 --> 02:21:14.633
and skills back for the benefit of the DPRK.

02:21:18.387 --> 02:21:20.097
Tourism in North Korea.

02:21:21.223 --> 02:21:22.933
Students aren't the only people coming

02:21:22.933 --> 02:21:26.478
into North Korea more often since Kim Jong Un took power.

02:21:26.478 --> 02:21:29.314
As of 2013, tightly controlled

02:21:29.314 --> 02:21:31.274
and well-monitored tourist groups

02:21:31.274 --> 02:21:33.276
have been allowed to enter North Korea.

02:21:33.276 --> 02:21:35.237
This is no simple holiday.

02:21:35.237 --> 02:21:38.532
Regime officials travel with tour groups everywhere.

02:21:38.532 --> 02:21:41.535
Itineraries must be adhered to without question,

02:21:41.535 --> 02:21:44.621
and tourists may not ask unapproved questions

02:21:44.621 --> 02:21:48.250
or enter unapproved places during their time in the DPRK.

02:21:48.250 --> 02:21:50.001
Most foreign tourists will stay

02:21:50.001 --> 02:21:53.422
at the Yanggakdo International Hotel in Pyongyang.

02:21:53.422 --> 02:21:56.883
It has many of the amenities one would expect from a hotel,

02:21:56.883 --> 02:22:01.012
a restaurant, a pool, a sauna, and even a massage room.

02:22:01.012 --> 02:22:03.682
Guests might find it hard to relax, though.

02:22:03.682 --> 02:22:06.435
It is generally accepted that the authorities spy

02:22:06.435 --> 02:22:09.813
on every guest and the entire fifth floor

02:22:09.813 --> 02:22:12.315
is strictly off limits to tourists,

02:22:12.315 --> 02:22:15.402
where many believe the North Koreans oversee surveillance

02:22:15.402 --> 02:22:16.528
of the guests.

02:22:16.528 --> 02:22:17.696
Tourists are ushered

02:22:17.696 --> 02:22:21.283
to carefully prepared propaganda sites around the country.

02:22:21.283 --> 02:22:24.327
These include the giant statues of the Kim family,

02:22:24.327 --> 02:22:26.747
great projects like the Nampo Dam,

02:22:26.747 --> 02:22:29.416
and a series of resorts, aquatic parks,

02:22:29.416 --> 02:22:32.627
and other tourist sites constructed in the recent years.

02:22:32.627 --> 02:22:35.881
Despite the propaganda hurled at them, tourists report

02:22:35.881 --> 02:22:38.550
that the North Korean people are generally friendly

02:22:38.550 --> 02:22:41.052
and somewhat curious about foreigners.

02:22:41.052 --> 02:22:43.513
They are still careful not to utter anything

02:22:43.513 --> 02:22:46.141
that will send them to a concentration camp,

02:22:46.141 --> 02:22:48.351
but tourism has allowed North Koreans

02:22:48.351 --> 02:22:50.395
to see that those beyond their borders

02:22:50.395 --> 02:22:52.314
aren't the destructive monsters

02:22:52.314 --> 02:22:54.608
that state propaganda depicts them as.

02:22:58.195 --> 02:22:59.946
Otto Frederick Warmbier.

02:23:01.072 --> 02:23:04.242
The rules governing tourism are rigidly enforced.

02:23:04.242 --> 02:23:06.369
As one American college student learned

02:23:06.369 --> 02:23:07.996
in the most tragic way.

02:23:07.996 --> 02:23:09.539
Otto Frederick Warmbier

02:23:09.539 --> 02:23:12.250
was a bright and friendly American college student

02:23:12.250 --> 02:23:14.002
who loved to travel.

02:23:14.002 --> 02:23:17.672
In December, 2015, he took the opportunity of a lifetime

02:23:17.672 --> 02:23:19.216
to visit North Korea.

02:23:19.216 --> 02:23:22.135
After a whirlwind five day tour,

02:23:22.135 --> 02:23:23.929
Warmbier was ready to go back home

02:23:23.929 --> 02:23:26.056
with the other members of his tour group.

02:23:26.056 --> 02:23:28.391
However, as he waited in the terminal,

02:23:28.391 --> 02:23:32.020
two North Korean soldiers approached him and took him away.

02:23:32.020 --> 02:23:34.689
Warmbier's life and that of his family

02:23:34.689 --> 02:23:37.067
were about to change forever.

02:23:37.067 --> 02:23:40.362
Warmbier was accused of stealing a propaganda poster

02:23:40.362 --> 02:23:42.072
from Yanggakdo Hotel.

02:23:42.072 --> 02:23:44.950
This is extremely illegal in North Korea

02:23:44.950 --> 02:23:47.369
and is seen as an attack on the regime.

02:23:47.369 --> 02:23:50.330
No one knows what Warmbier experienced in captivity.

02:23:50.330 --> 02:23:52.999
All we have is a confession where Warmbier claims

02:23:52.999 --> 02:23:55.335
that the US government put him up to the crime

02:23:55.335 --> 02:23:58.964
and had manipulated him into attacking the DPRK.

02:23:58.964 --> 02:24:01.299
The absurd confession didn't save him

02:24:01.299 --> 02:24:05.387
and Warmbier was sentenced to 15 years in a labor camp.

02:24:05.387 --> 02:24:07.848
- Oh, I was used and manipulated.

02:24:11.935 --> 02:24:14.271
Please, you have to save me.

02:24:17.357 --> 02:24:19.776
Please save my life.

02:24:19.776 --> 02:24:22.153
- [Narrator] The US government continued to negotiate

02:24:22.153 --> 02:24:23.572
for Warmbier's release

02:24:23.572 --> 02:24:27.826
and finally got it 17 months later in June, 2017,

02:24:27.826 --> 02:24:30.203
but something was horribly wrong.

02:24:30.203 --> 02:24:31.872
The North Koreans informed them

02:24:31.872 --> 02:24:36.167
that Warmbier had fallen into a coma back in April, 2016.

02:24:36.167 --> 02:24:38.295
They blamed food poisoning.

02:24:38.295 --> 02:24:41.339
Warmbier was breathing, but was completely paralyzed

02:24:41.339 --> 02:24:42.757
and unresponsive

02:24:42.757 --> 02:24:45.260
and was only kept alive with a feeding tube.

02:24:45.260 --> 02:24:47.512
Warmbier was flown back to the US,

02:24:47.512 --> 02:24:49.598
but there was nothing anyone could do.

02:24:49.598 --> 02:24:51.850
Doctors believed his brain had been deprived

02:24:51.850 --> 02:24:55.061
of oxygen causing permanent brain damage.

02:24:55.061 --> 02:24:56.021
One suggestion

02:24:56.021 --> 02:24:58.899
was that the North Koreans used water torture on him.

02:24:58.899 --> 02:25:01.568
Other Americans who had been in North Korean captivity

02:25:01.568 --> 02:25:03.612
had suffered it, and one man admitted

02:25:03.612 --> 02:25:05.447
to seeing a young American boy

02:25:05.447 --> 02:25:08.325
matching Warmbier's description left unconscious

02:25:08.325 --> 02:25:11.328
and covered in water being dragged through a prison,

02:25:11.328 --> 02:25:12.996
With no hope of recovery,

02:25:12.996 --> 02:25:17.417
Warmbier's feeding tube was removed on June 19th, 2017.

02:25:17.417 --> 02:25:20.587
The US government condemned North Korea for his death,

02:25:20.587 --> 02:25:22.422
but the regime played the victim.

02:25:22.422 --> 02:25:25.342
They called the news reports a smear campaign

02:25:25.342 --> 02:25:27.594
and said that they had only ever shown mercy

02:25:27.594 --> 02:25:31.056
to a "criminal of the enemy state."

02:25:36.061 --> 02:25:37.562
Escaping North Korea.

02:25:38.855 --> 02:25:41.232
With everything we've heard, it's no surprise

02:25:41.232 --> 02:25:44.527
that so many people want to get out of North Korea.

02:25:44.527 --> 02:25:47.739
People have been escaping North Korea since its inception.

02:25:47.739 --> 02:25:50.659
The number of successful North Korean defectors

02:25:50.659 --> 02:25:52.327
has varied over time.

02:25:52.327 --> 02:25:54.663
It peaked at several 1,000 per year,

02:25:54.663 --> 02:25:57.916
with at least as many failed attempts under Kim Jong-Il

02:25:57.916 --> 02:26:00.919
before declining sharply under the tighter policies

02:26:00.919 --> 02:26:02.295
of Kim Jong Un.

02:26:02.295 --> 02:26:07.300
In 2022, just 67 defectors made it to South Korea.

02:26:07.384 --> 02:26:10.261
This decline has been driven almost entirely

02:26:10.261 --> 02:26:12.055
by improved border security

02:26:12.055 --> 02:26:14.557
along the few possible escape routes.

02:26:14.557 --> 02:26:18.979
The most obvious but risky escape route is across the DMZ.

02:26:18.979 --> 02:26:22.816
The border with South Korea is watched carefully by soldiers

02:26:22.816 --> 02:26:26.111
and is covered in barbed wire fences, watch towers,

02:26:26.111 --> 02:26:28.196
and even minefields.

02:26:28.196 --> 02:26:30.865
An alternative route is across the northern border

02:26:30.865 --> 02:26:31.866
with China.

02:26:31.866 --> 02:26:34.536
This border is watched too with barbed wire

02:26:34.536 --> 02:26:37.580
and guard patrols, covering huge parts of the border,

02:26:37.580 --> 02:26:41.126
but not all of the terrain can be easily watched.

02:26:41.126 --> 02:26:44.713
Mountainous passages and sheer cliffs offer a chance

02:26:44.713 --> 02:26:46.297
to slip by unnoticed.

02:26:46.297 --> 02:26:50.301
Guards can sometimes be bribed too, but it's risky.

02:26:50.301 --> 02:26:54.305
Even if a defector can get into China, they're not safe.

02:26:54.305 --> 02:26:56.808
The Chinese government has a standard policy

02:26:56.808 --> 02:26:59.894
to deport all defectors back to North Korea.

02:26:59.894 --> 02:27:02.647
Instead, the defectors must travel through China

02:27:02.647 --> 02:27:04.399
and enter Southeast Asia.

02:27:04.399 --> 02:27:07.569
Some go by land while others follow the Mekong River

02:27:07.569 --> 02:27:10.488
until they reach the safety of countries like Thailand.

02:27:10.488 --> 02:27:13.408
Sea escapes to the Philippines are also known.

02:27:13.408 --> 02:27:15.452
When they reach a country that won't deport them

02:27:15.452 --> 02:27:16.536
to North Korea,

02:27:16.536 --> 02:27:19.539
the defectors can present themselves to authorities.

02:27:19.539 --> 02:27:21.958
South Korea had a long standing program

02:27:21.958 --> 02:27:24.377
to take in defectors from anywhere

02:27:24.377 --> 02:27:26.713
and will make arrangements for these escapees

02:27:26.713 --> 02:27:28.298
to settle in their country.

02:27:28.298 --> 02:27:30.592
Anyone who is caught while attempting to escape

02:27:30.592 --> 02:27:32.677
can expect harsh punishment.

02:27:32.677 --> 02:27:34.804
Many will just be shot on site.

02:27:34.804 --> 02:27:38.349
An underground network has sprung up to aid defectors,

02:27:38.349 --> 02:27:41.102
but the new policies make this riskier than ever.

02:27:41.102 --> 02:27:42.103
Ha Jin-Woo,

02:27:42.103 --> 02:27:45.356
an activist who helps other defectors escape via China,

02:27:45.356 --> 02:27:47.859
estimated for the BBC that the success rate

02:27:47.859 --> 02:27:52.280
for defection has fallen from about 50% under Kim Jong-Il

02:27:52.280 --> 02:27:55.158
to less than 10% in recent years.

02:27:58.661 --> 02:28:00.705
Assassination of Kim Jong-Nam.

02:28:01.956 --> 02:28:05.001
In reality, there is little hope of safety

02:28:05.001 --> 02:28:06.795
or escape from the regime,

02:28:06.795 --> 02:28:09.589
not even for the leader's own brother.

02:28:09.589 --> 02:28:12.884
Kim Jong Un's elder half-brother, Kim Jong Nam,

02:28:12.884 --> 02:28:14.761
lived a mostly private life,

02:28:14.761 --> 02:28:18.098
Traveling around the world since being passed over as heir,

02:28:18.098 --> 02:28:20.433
he lived in several places around the world

02:28:20.433 --> 02:28:22.185
and enjoyed a comfortable life thanks

02:28:22.185 --> 02:28:23.520
to his family's wealth.

02:28:23.520 --> 02:28:26.106
However, he was candid in his criticism

02:28:26.106 --> 02:28:27.774
of his half brother's regime,

02:28:27.774 --> 02:28:31.528
telling one Japanese journalist that "without reforms,

02:28:31.528 --> 02:28:33.655
North Korea will collapse."

02:28:33.655 --> 02:28:34.864
Nam's frankness

02:28:34.864 --> 02:28:37.075
and his brother's vengeance caught up with him

02:28:37.075 --> 02:28:39.285
in February, 2017.

02:28:39.285 --> 02:28:41.996
While waiting for a flight at Kuala Lumpur Airport

02:28:41.996 --> 02:28:44.582
in Malaysia, two women approached Nam.

02:28:44.582 --> 02:28:47.085
One threw a bottle of liquid at his face

02:28:47.085 --> 02:28:49.754
while another covered his mouth with a damp cloth.

02:28:49.754 --> 02:28:52.757
After a brief scuffle, the two women ran away

02:28:52.757 --> 02:28:55.927
and Nam immediately suspected he'd been poisoned.

02:28:55.927 --> 02:28:57.178
Nam was right.

02:28:57.178 --> 02:29:00.598
The women had attacked him with a VX nerve agent,

02:29:00.598 --> 02:29:02.517
a highly illegal chemical weapon

02:29:02.517 --> 02:29:04.727
that is banned in most countries.

02:29:04.727 --> 02:29:06.521
Nam rushed to get medical aid,

02:29:06.521 --> 02:29:09.107
but within 20 minutes, he was dead.

02:29:09.107 --> 02:29:12.068
It did not take long to determine his identity,

02:29:12.068 --> 02:29:13.736
and authorities were quick to conclude

02:29:13.736 --> 02:29:15.613
that this was an assassination.

02:29:15.613 --> 02:29:18.700
The two women were identified as a Vietnamese citizen

02:29:18.700 --> 02:29:20.618
and an Indonesian citizen,

02:29:20.618 --> 02:29:22.579
but when they were questioned by police,

02:29:22.579 --> 02:29:25.582
they claimed they knew nothing about a nerve agent.

02:29:25.582 --> 02:29:27.167
Both women claimed they'd been approached

02:29:27.167 --> 02:29:28.960
to take part in a prank show

02:29:28.960 --> 02:29:30.628
and had performed several pranks

02:29:30.628 --> 02:29:33.256
on unsuspecting people before this.

02:29:33.256 --> 02:29:35.175
It is believed that Kim Jong Un

02:29:35.175 --> 02:29:38.136
had a standing order for his half-brother's murder.

02:29:38.136 --> 02:29:40.763
North Korean agents recruited the two women

02:29:40.763 --> 02:29:44.142
under false claims of working for a TV prank show

02:29:44.142 --> 02:29:46.019
and had them perform several pranks

02:29:46.019 --> 02:29:48.313
to trick them into thinking it was real.

02:29:48.313 --> 02:29:50.690
Murder charges were dropped against the women,

02:29:50.690 --> 02:29:52.775
but the agents who put them up to the act

02:29:52.775 --> 02:29:53.902
have never been caught.

02:29:56.946 --> 02:29:59.324
Kim and Trump reconciliation.

02:30:00.575 --> 02:30:03.828
Clearly, dealing with North Korea is always a delicate

02:30:03.828 --> 02:30:05.413
and dangerous endeavor.

02:30:05.413 --> 02:30:09.417
Naturally, the election of the very undelicate Donald Trump

02:30:09.417 --> 02:30:10.418
as US president

02:30:10.418 --> 02:30:15.048
in 2016 caused some concern regarding the Korean issue.

02:30:15.048 --> 02:30:17.508
Kim Jong Un did not give up his nuclear tests

02:30:17.508 --> 02:30:20.261
in the face of this new unpredictable leader,

02:30:20.261 --> 02:30:22.931
and Twitter became the bizarre new avenue

02:30:22.931 --> 02:30:25.308
for Trump's unique brand of diplomacy,

02:30:25.308 --> 02:30:29.479
where he famously threatened North Korea's Little Rocket Man

02:30:29.479 --> 02:30:33.191
with his much bigger and more functional Nuclear Button.

02:30:33.191 --> 02:30:35.109
We do not know what North Korea thought

02:30:35.109 --> 02:30:36.486
about this new approach.

02:30:36.486 --> 02:30:38.613
However, following heightened tensions

02:30:38.613 --> 02:30:41.658
from the Hwasong Missile test in 2017,

02:30:41.658 --> 02:30:44.410
Korea's diplomatic tune suddenly changed.

02:30:44.410 --> 02:30:46.079
The North sent a delegation

02:30:46.079 --> 02:30:49.540
to the Winter Olympics in Seoul in early 2018

02:30:49.540 --> 02:30:51.167
and extended an invite

02:30:51.167 --> 02:30:53.711
to the South Korean President, Bon Ki-Moon,

02:30:53.711 --> 02:30:55.004
to visit the North.

02:30:55.004 --> 02:30:57.131
The leaders of both Korea's also met

02:30:57.131 --> 02:30:59.050
at the demilitarized zone

02:30:59.050 --> 02:31:01.386
and agreed to work towards denuclearization

02:31:01.386 --> 02:31:02.512
of the peninsula.

02:31:02.512 --> 02:31:04.889
This was followed by an agreement between Kim

02:31:04.889 --> 02:31:06.975
and Trump in Singapore in June,

02:31:06.975 --> 02:31:10.353
where Trump echoed the commitment to denuclearization

02:31:10.353 --> 02:31:13.481
and agreed to scale back military exercises

02:31:13.481 --> 02:31:15.066
as a sign of goodwill.

02:31:15.066 --> 02:31:16.985
Maybe it shouldn't be a surprise

02:31:16.985 --> 02:31:19.112
that such an unusual president

02:31:19.112 --> 02:31:22.657
would be the key to making progress with an unusual nation.

02:31:22.657 --> 02:31:26.369
In June, 2019, Donald Trump and King Jong Un

02:31:26.369 --> 02:31:29.289
had an unprecedented meeting at the DMZ

02:31:29.289 --> 02:31:32.542
where they discussed plans for further deescalation

02:31:32.542 --> 02:31:34.877
and additional talks in the near future.

02:31:34.877 --> 02:31:37.422
For a while, things seemed to be looking up.

02:31:37.422 --> 02:31:41.426
Unfortunately, these talks broke down in October, 2019

02:31:41.426 --> 02:31:42.844
and a hope for a new age

02:31:42.844 --> 02:31:45.346
of North Korean relations collapsed.

02:31:45.346 --> 02:31:49.058
Kim was not ready to make concessions on the nuclear issue

02:31:49.058 --> 02:31:52.353
and he soon resumed his tests in spite of American

02:31:52.353 --> 02:31:54.522
and South Korean protests.

02:31:54.522 --> 02:31:57.608
Once again, the nation would retreat inwards,

02:31:57.608 --> 02:32:00.445
continuing to cut itself off from the outside world

02:32:00.445 --> 02:32:03.281
and maintaining its own tightly controlled bubble

02:32:03.281 --> 02:32:05.825
where its citizens' abilities to move, work,

02:32:05.825 --> 02:32:07.660
or even voice opinions

02:32:07.660 --> 02:32:10.747
was restricted in the name of collective security.

02:32:10.747 --> 02:32:12.874
Little did anyone know this state

02:32:12.874 --> 02:32:15.168
would soon describe most of the world.

02:32:19.464 --> 02:32:21.883
North Korea and COVID-19.

02:32:23.343 --> 02:32:26.429
North Korea's isolation proved to be a blessing

02:32:26.429 --> 02:32:29.849
in January, 2020 when COVID-19 hit.

02:32:29.849 --> 02:32:33.269
With entry to the country already under strict control

02:32:33.269 --> 02:32:36.105
and borders vigilantly watched by soldiers,

02:32:36.105 --> 02:32:38.858
it was easy for North Korea to seal itself off

02:32:38.858 --> 02:32:40.109
from the pandemic.

02:32:40.109 --> 02:32:42.403
Officially North Korea avoided COVID

02:32:42.403 --> 02:32:46.032
for the whole of 2020 and 2021.

02:32:46.032 --> 02:32:49.702
Outside sources are skeptical that it was completely free,

02:32:49.702 --> 02:32:52.747
but no evidence of any widespread pandemic exists

02:32:52.747 --> 02:32:54.248
for the first two years.

02:32:54.248 --> 02:32:57.293
In fact, not much evidence for anything exists

02:32:57.293 --> 02:32:59.087
for those years from North Korea.

02:32:59.087 --> 02:33:01.172
Foreign governments had bigger concerns,

02:33:01.172 --> 02:33:03.216
and the North had no interest in opening up

02:33:03.216 --> 02:33:06.094
in letting the virus through, so we know even less

02:33:06.094 --> 02:33:08.596
about what happened there than we usually do.

02:33:08.596 --> 02:33:12.642
We do know that North Korea took COVID extremely seriously.

02:33:12.642 --> 02:33:14.685
Strict lockdowns were put in place

02:33:14.685 --> 02:33:17.772
and thorough quarantine procedures were established

02:33:17.772 --> 02:33:20.733
for anyone with symptoms resembling COVID.

02:33:20.733 --> 02:33:23.861
When a single COVID-19 case was rumored in the city

02:33:23.861 --> 02:33:27.448
of Kaesong, Kim Jong Un locked down the whole city

02:33:27.448 --> 02:33:28.866
for three weeks.

02:33:28.866 --> 02:33:30.284
It was a false alarm,

02:33:30.284 --> 02:33:33.955
but it shows how harsh Kim's response to the pandemic was.

02:33:33.955 --> 02:33:35.456
It was reported that violators

02:33:35.456 --> 02:33:38.960
of North Korea's movement restrictions were executed,

02:33:38.960 --> 02:33:40.211
and in one case,

02:33:40.211 --> 02:33:43.089
the North Korean Navy killed a South Korean fisherman

02:33:43.089 --> 02:33:46.509
and sunk his ship because he posed a COVID risk.

02:33:46.509 --> 02:33:49.720
International trade almost completely stopped

02:33:49.720 --> 02:33:51.013
and the regime rolled back

02:33:51.013 --> 02:33:54.100
its public parades citing health concerns.

02:33:54.100 --> 02:33:57.186
However, given how tightly controlled life usually was

02:33:57.186 --> 02:34:00.064
in North Korea, the pandemic was much less

02:34:00.064 --> 02:34:03.734
of a change there than it was for most people in the world.

02:34:05.653 --> 02:34:07.905
North Korea's late pandemic.

02:34:09.532 --> 02:34:13.494
However, these measures weren't enough to escape entirely.

02:34:13.494 --> 02:34:16.622
North Korea announced its first COVID case to the world

02:34:16.622 --> 02:34:19.125
on the 12th of May, 2022.

02:34:19.125 --> 02:34:22.170
The government declared a national emergency

02:34:22.170 --> 02:34:23.754
and Kim issued a statement saying

02:34:23.754 --> 02:34:26.257
that the nation faced its greatest challenge

02:34:26.257 --> 02:34:27.884
since the revolution.

02:34:27.884 --> 02:34:30.761
With reports of starvation due to food shortages

02:34:30.761 --> 02:34:34.015
on top of North Korea's poor medical system,

02:34:34.015 --> 02:34:37.018
outside observers feared a catastrophe.

02:34:37.018 --> 02:34:38.311
The fact that Pyongyang

02:34:38.311 --> 02:34:40.605
had turned down multiple vaccine offers

02:34:40.605 --> 02:34:42.565
was also a big concern.

02:34:42.565 --> 02:34:44.942
North Korea insisted that other countries

02:34:44.942 --> 02:34:47.111
that needed the more get them first,

02:34:47.111 --> 02:34:48.779
although some saw the stubbornness

02:34:48.779 --> 02:34:52.033
of Juche ideology at the core of their refusal,

02:34:52.033 --> 02:34:55.453
and there were fears that this decision would backfire.

02:34:55.453 --> 02:34:57.580
Fortunately, North Korea only faced

02:34:57.580 --> 02:35:00.625
the much less deadly omicron variant.

02:35:00.625 --> 02:35:01.667
What happened next

02:35:01.667 --> 02:35:04.462
is up to whether you trust government statistics.

02:35:04.462 --> 02:35:07.089
Although almost 5 million cases were reported

02:35:07.089 --> 02:35:08.257
in a matter of months,

02:35:08.257 --> 02:35:11.093
hitting 20% of the country's population,

02:35:11.093 --> 02:35:14.514
only 74 people were reported to have died,

02:35:14.514 --> 02:35:17.266
and the pandemic fizzled out by September.

02:35:17.266 --> 02:35:20.561
Most scholars on the topic believe the actual death toll

02:35:20.561 --> 02:35:23.231
is higher, probably in the 1,000s,

02:35:23.231 --> 02:35:26.067
but probably far smaller than the death toll seen

02:35:26.067 --> 02:35:28.277
in South Korea or other countries

02:35:28.277 --> 02:35:31.030
that face the deadlier early waves.

02:35:31.030 --> 02:35:32.323
Like the rest of the world,

02:35:32.323 --> 02:35:35.409
North Korea emerged from the pandemic shaken

02:35:35.409 --> 02:35:39.789
and facing the prospect of a new and uncertain future.

02:35:43.376 --> 02:35:45.711
North Korea in 2023.

02:35:47.046 --> 02:35:50.925
2023 has been a relatively quiet year for North Korea.

02:35:50.925 --> 02:35:52.885
It has continued its missile tests

02:35:52.885 --> 02:35:55.555
and issued its usual bluing statements

02:35:55.555 --> 02:35:57.974
about destroying the US and South Korea

02:35:57.974 --> 02:36:01.352
if they provoke them, but nothing out of the ordinary.

02:36:01.352 --> 02:36:04.564
In May, they tried to launch their first spy satellite based

02:36:04.564 --> 02:36:07.483
on technology from its ICBM project,

02:36:07.483 --> 02:36:10.319
but the rocket crashed into the sea after launch.

02:36:10.319 --> 02:36:12.280
They tried and failed again in August,

02:36:12.280 --> 02:36:15.241
and will no doubt try further tests in the future.

02:36:15.241 --> 02:36:17.577
North Korea grabbed headlines in late July

02:36:17.577 --> 02:36:21.247
with the rare defection of a US soldier across the border.

02:36:21.247 --> 02:36:24.375
Private Travis King was stationed in South Korea

02:36:24.375 --> 02:36:26.961
and was taking a walking tour of the border

02:36:26.961 --> 02:36:28.963
when he suddenly ran away from his group

02:36:28.963 --> 02:36:31.465
and crossed into North Korean territory.

02:36:31.465 --> 02:36:32.925
King, who is Black,

02:36:32.925 --> 02:36:35.469
blamed racism and mistreatment in the US

02:36:35.469 --> 02:36:37.013
for making him defect.

02:36:37.013 --> 02:36:40.057
In truth, it probably had to do with him facing punishment

02:36:40.057 --> 02:36:42.685
for an assault he committed in South Korea.

02:36:42.685 --> 02:36:45.813
King was released back to US custody in September,

02:36:45.813 --> 02:36:48.024
and his fate is yet to be decided.

02:36:48.024 --> 02:36:51.402
Pyongyang has also grabbed headlines for its tacit support

02:36:51.402 --> 02:36:53.613
of Russia's invasion of Ukraine.

02:36:53.613 --> 02:36:56.449
Kim Jong Un met Vladimir Putin in September

02:36:56.449 --> 02:36:57.783
to discuss the possibility

02:36:57.783 --> 02:37:00.077
of supplying weapons for the war effort.

02:37:00.077 --> 02:37:02.163
Kim, like Putin, sees the conflict

02:37:02.163 --> 02:37:04.790
as a proxy war against its great enemies

02:37:04.790 --> 02:37:06.917
in the United States and Nato.

02:37:06.917 --> 02:37:10.338
Things are quite different today than from the 1950s,

02:37:10.338 --> 02:37:12.840
but Pyongyang and Moscow still see themselves

02:37:12.840 --> 02:37:15.468
as allies in an endless confrontation

02:37:15.468 --> 02:37:18.220
against the capitalist Western powers.

02:37:18.220 --> 02:37:21.515
Whether that war ever comes and whether the Kim regime

02:37:21.515 --> 02:37:24.477
will be around to see it is anyone's guess.

02:37:27.104 --> 02:37:28.689
The future of North Korea.

02:37:30.107 --> 02:37:33.819
It has been said that North Korea has two paths to collapse,

02:37:33.819 --> 02:37:36.405
to reform or not to reform.

02:37:36.405 --> 02:37:40.034
To continue unchanged will inevitably bring about collapse

02:37:40.034 --> 02:37:41.744
as the world leaves it behind,

02:37:41.744 --> 02:37:44.538
but mismanaged reform that doesn't do enough

02:37:44.538 --> 02:37:47.917
or does too much too quickly risks toppling

02:37:47.917 --> 02:37:49.627
the system altogether.

02:37:49.627 --> 02:37:51.796
Back in 2011, Kim Jong-Nam,

02:37:51.796 --> 02:37:54.131
who might be expected to have known a thing or two

02:37:54.131 --> 02:37:56.133
about his family's regime commented

02:37:56.133 --> 02:37:59.845
that "the North Korean leadership is stuck in a bind.

02:37:59.845 --> 02:38:03.099
Without reforms, the country's economy will go bankrupt,

02:38:03.099 --> 02:38:05.142
but reforms are fraught with the danger

02:38:05.142 --> 02:38:06.769
of systemic collapse."

02:38:06.769 --> 02:38:10.439
Kim Jong Un seems to be trying to forge a middle path.

02:38:10.439 --> 02:38:13.234
Kim's internal shift away from military power,

02:38:13.234 --> 02:38:15.861
his openness to tourism and education,

02:38:15.861 --> 02:38:18.239
and his embracing of modern technology

02:38:18.239 --> 02:38:20.783
and some limited foreign culture hints

02:38:20.783 --> 02:38:22.618
at a prospect of change.

02:38:22.618 --> 02:38:25.788
However, the ever tighter grip the regime wields

02:38:25.788 --> 02:38:29.166
over its people, its stronger border enforcement,

02:38:29.166 --> 02:38:32.628
and its continued nuclear threats show that Pyongyang

02:38:32.628 --> 02:38:35.798
is far from ready to set aside its old ways

02:38:35.798 --> 02:38:38.926
and seek a new path of peace and cooperation.

02:38:38.926 --> 02:38:41.554
As global tensions increase between the West

02:38:41.554 --> 02:38:43.681
and both Russia and China,

02:38:43.681 --> 02:38:47.226
North Korea continues to be anchored to its old allies,

02:38:47.226 --> 02:38:50.062
even if it increasingly feels like a bizarre relic

02:38:50.062 --> 02:38:51.564
of a bygone era.

02:38:51.564 --> 02:38:55.693
Meanwhile, the contrast between North and South is extreme.

02:38:55.693 --> 02:38:59.071
Per capita income in the South is about 15 times higher

02:38:59.071 --> 02:39:02.283
than the North, by far the largest income gap

02:39:02.283 --> 02:39:05.411
between two nations that share a land border anywhere

02:39:05.411 --> 02:39:06.579
in the world.

02:39:06.579 --> 02:39:09.582
To put that in context, the much touted disparity

02:39:09.582 --> 02:39:11.500
between West and East Germany

02:39:11.500 --> 02:39:14.670
that helped inspire the toppling of the Berlin Wall

02:39:14.670 --> 02:39:18.883
was an income ratio of three to one in favor of the West.

02:39:18.883 --> 02:39:22.470
The shock so many North Korean defectors feel upon reaching

02:39:22.470 --> 02:39:26.056
the South is entirely unsurprising.

02:39:26.056 --> 02:39:29.268
Many people have tried to predict where North Korea will go,

02:39:29.268 --> 02:39:31.604
and many people have been wrong.

02:39:31.604 --> 02:39:34.482
For now, North Korea is here to stay.

02:39:34.482 --> 02:39:36.901
It shows no sign of imminent collapse,

02:39:36.901 --> 02:39:38.861
and no one has the inclination

02:39:38.861 --> 02:39:41.322
to force it over the edge either.

02:39:41.322 --> 02:39:45.451
Still, its economic failures and its inability to keep up

02:39:45.451 --> 02:39:48.621
with a changing world Might one day spell the end

02:39:48.621 --> 02:39:50.831
for this peculiar little country,

02:39:50.831 --> 02:39:53.542
or at least for its government.

